<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany to Maintain Economic Growth: Bundesbank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The German central bank Thursday
presented an optimistic outlook for continued German economic
growth, supported by booming exports and rising domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
In its monthly report, the Bundesbank did not see any big
threat from the Asian crisis to German economic growth despite a
sharp fall in exports to the crisis-ridden area.
</P>
<P>
It pointed out that the crisis-hit Asian countries accounted
for merely 5 percent of German exports while the main importers of
German products, especially in Europe, had picked up momentum in
their domestic economies.
</P>
<P>
Exports overall "had clearly risen" this year, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
Strong exports had been joined by clearly rising domestic
demand in driving the economy ahead, the bank stressed.
</P>
<P>
It reported that new domestic orders for the manufacturing
sector increased by nearly 5.5 percent in the four months of this
year over the last four months of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The bank also noted a revival of domestic investments.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the bad news for German economy was
that recession would continue to hit the construction sector and
that joblessness, at 11.2 percent in May, which it described as
still "unacceptably high" after a fall of 200,000 so far this
year, would remain the country's main problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
