<HEADLINE> Women's Status Raised Thanks to Actions Echoing the Fourth World Conference on Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Women's status has been
significantly raised during the past few years thanks to efforts
by countries and non-governmental organizations in line with the
spirit of the Fourth World Conference on Women (FWCW).
</P>
<P>
Chen Muhua, FWCW president and president of the All-China
Women's Federation, said this in the Beijing Seminar on the
Follow-Up Action to FWCW, where over 300 women delegates from all
over the world gather and present reports on recent progress of
women's cause in their respective countries following the FWCW.
</P>
<P>
The FWCW, convoked in September 1995 in Beijing, passed the
Beijing Declaration and the Platform for Action in which strategic
goals for solving women's problems world wide were mapped out.
</P>
<P>
"The Fourth FWCW is the largest international meeting in the
history of the United Nations to date," said Chen. "It has become
an important milestone in striving for equality between men and
women and in promoting peace and development."
</P>
<P>
Secretary-general of the FWCW Gertrude I. Mongella extended her
thanks to all non-governmental organizations for their efforts in
promoting women's benefits.
</P>
<P>
Gu Xiulian, first secretary of the secretariat of All-China
Women's Federation, briefed the audience on Chinese government's
effort and goals in promoting women's employment, women's
education, and so on.
</P>
<P>
The delegates will discuss in panels in the next few days such
topics as women and poverty, women's education and training, and
objections to violence against women. 
</P>
</TEXT>
