<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bilharzia on L. Malawi Almost Under Control: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The prevalence of bilharzia along
the once highly infected western shores of Lake Malawi has
dropped by over 50 percent, and it is now almost under control, a
bilharzia control study has shown.
</P>
<P>
According to a Malawi News Agency report Thursday, the study
showed that the prevalence rate of the disease has dropped from
77 to 23.4 percent, reducing fears among tourists who love
lake-bathing of contracting the disease.
</P>
<P>
The two-year research was jointly conducted by the Department
of Community Health at the College of Medicine of the University
of Malawi, ministry of health, ministry of tourism, parks and
wildlife, some hotels and local communities in the area.
</P>
<P>
The study concerning Africa's third largest lake which has
about 400 fish species not found elsewhere showed that in every
10 children living around the western lake shore area tested,
only two have bilharzia.
</P>
<P>
"The third and most recent investigations carried out last
month yielded very encouraging results as they showed continued
decline of prevalence of bilharzia," Coordinator of the Lake
Malawi Bilharzia Program Chiwoza Bandawe was quoted as saying by
the weekly newspaper the Malawi News.
</P>
<P>
Bandawe said that the number of eggs found in a sample of
urine has also dropped drastically from 26 percent to three
percent.
</P>
<P>
He said: "The first investigations carried out in May 1997
revealed that 77 percent of the 3,622 children tested in three
schools within the area had bilharzia.
</P>
<P>
"But the second investigation revealed that the rate of the
disease in the schools had dropped from 77 percent to 32 percent
while the recently conducted third investigation has shown a
further downward trend to 23.4 percent."
</P>
<P>
He added that the decline is a result of the efforts by the
health clubs which have been started in some schools. The
children themselves are very active in spreading awareness about
bilharzia and the need to stop urinating in river water.
</P>
<P>
The coordinator also said that over catching of the type of
fish which eat bilharzia eggs contributed to the rise in
prevalence rate of bilharzia along the western shore of Lake
Malawi.
</P>
<P>
Fish from the lake provides over 70 percent of protein to the
people living along the lake shores.
</P>
<P>
The news of bilharzia prevalence in the area had badly
affected business for the resorts there, and in general, it had
also led to a drop in numbers of tourists visiting the lake area.
</P>
<P>
But with the efforts now being put in place to control the
disease, the situation is once again returning to normal.
</P>
<P>
"The fourth investigation will be carried out in October this
year," said Bandawe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
