<HEADLINE> Hun Sen Sets Condition for Khieu Samphan's Surrender </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Khmer Rouge's nominal political
leader Khieu Samphan would be treated leniently way if he captured
fellow leaders Ta Mok and Nuon Chea and handed them over to the
royal government, Cambodia's Second Prime Minister Hun Sen said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Cambodian Economy Institute, Hun Sen warned
that if Khieu Samphan did not do as requested and continued to
resist the government, he would be captured along with the other
two men.
</P>
<P>
Noun Chea, Ta Mok and Khieu Samphan are the only three Khmer
Rouge leaders other than Pol Pot, who are named by Cambodian
authorities as wanted for crimes against humanity.
</P>
<P>
Ta Mok is believed to be in his 70s and Khieu Samphan is 67
years old. Noun Chea's age is not known.
</P>
<P>
Unconfirmed reports said that Khieu Samphan is now in Pailin
near the Thai-Cambodian border.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen told his supporters Tuesday that the three staunch
Khmer Rouge leaders were incapacitated with a variety of health
problems.
</P>
<P>
Noun Chea is paralyzed down one side of his body. Ta Mok is
suffering a severe pain in the stump of an amputated leg and Khieu
Samphan has a lung trouble.
</P>
<P>
Last weekend, five senior officials of the so-called Khmer
Rouge government signed a statement, announcing they had split
from the Khmer Rouge's hard-liners Ta Mok and Noun Chea.
</P>
<P>
Khmer Rouge's nominal leader Khieu Samphan has for years served
as the more presentable public face of the Khmer Rouge guerrillas
in Cambodia. Some observers describe him as a somber, austere and
extremely disciplined man. 
</P>
</TEXT>
