<HEADLINE> S. Africa's TRC Postpones Chemical Weapons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 18 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's Truth and
Reconciliation Commission (TRC) Thursday postponed its hearings
on the apartheid government's biological and chemical weapons
program until next month.
</P>
<P>
The delay will give TRC staff time to study documentation
submitted by Niel Knobel, former surgeon-general of the former
South African Defense Force, and to ascertain whether Wouter
Basson, the alleged mastermind behind the program, will testify.
</P>
<P>
Basson plans to apply to the Cape High Court to stop the TRC
from forcing him to give evidence, which Basson says will
prejudice his upcoming criminal trial.
</P>
<P>
Basson is soon to go on trial for 10 charges, including
possession of mandrax and ecstasy.
</P>
<P>
The TRC hearings, which began on June 8, have been told that the
former apartheid government made biological and chemical weapons to
suppress the anti-apartheid movement at home and aboard.
</P>
<P>
The TRC has also been told that the former government had
plans to poison President Nelson Mandela after his release in
1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
