<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Opposes Upgrading Palestinian Status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu warned Thursday that the attempt to upgrade the
Palestinian status at the United Nations could lead to the
collapse of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu told reporters in Jerusalem that he has consulted
with U.S. officials and British Prime Minister Tonny Blair on this
matter. He added that he would also raise the issue with the
leaders of other European countries.
</P>
<P>
A communique issued by the Israeli government on Thursday said
that the U.N. observer status of the Palestine Liberation
Organization (PLO) should be determined only in the
Israeli-Palestinian permanent talks.
</P>
<P>
It charged that the PLO efforts to upgrade its U.N. status were
a violation of the signed agreements.
</P>
<P>
In response, Palestinian National Authority President Yasser
Arafat's senior advisor Nabil Abu Rudaineh said in Gaza that it
was the national right of the Palestinian people to upgrade their
status at the U.N..
</P>
<P>
He also demanded Israel respect the international legitimacy of
the signed Oslo peace accords by implementing them in earnest.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Nasser al-Kidwa, the PLO observer at the U.N.,
said that Arab states, led by Egypt, have asked the U.N. General
Assembly to reconsider an Arab resolution on upgrading the
Palestinian status. The General Assembly was asked to schedule a
debate on the proposal next week.
</P>
<P>
The draft resolution, which was first submitted by the Arab
states last December, called for conferring "upon Palestine the
same rights and privileges of participation as those conferred
upon member states, with the exception of voting and candidature"
in U.N. committees, such as the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
In 1974, the U.N. General Assembly granted the PLO the observer
status, which was upgraded in 1988 with the PLO designated as
Palestine.
</P>
<P>
Although the proposed resolution would make little difference
for the daily work of the current Palestinian mission at the U.N.,
it would affirm international support for the Palestinians in
their peace talks with Israel, which have been stalled for over 15
months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
