<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Encouraged to Develop Small Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The role of the small scale
enterprise sector in uplifting the living standards of
Zimbabweans is of crucial importance in difficult economic times,
a government minister said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Officially opening the small business expo in Harare, Minister
of State for Enterprises and Indigenization in the President's
Office Cephas Msipa said small business had become more
attractive than large companies.
</P>
<P>
He said they were absorbing a large number of youths churned
out of Zimbabwe's education system annually.
</P>
<P>
''Small businesses are also, to a large extent, providing a
safety net for the thousands being retrenched from the large
conglomerates as they down-size and focus only on their core
business, not only in Zimbabwe but also throughout the world,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
The government, he said, had incorporated small business
development as the cornerstone of its indigenization policy.
</P>
<P>
Measures, including the regularization of informal sector
activities, would be taken in due course to accelerate the entry
of those in the fringes of the country's economy into the
mainstream.
</P>
<P>
''it is also the government's considered view that the small
business sector should spearhead the country's industrialization
program. We have had to formulate and implement an
industrialization policy which is currently under
consideration,'' Msipa said.
</P>
<P>
''To this end we have witnessed the coming to fruition of
several funds earmarked for the small enterprise sector as well
as bilateral programs aimed at strengthening small businesses
through technology transfer and capital injection via joint
ventures,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
Msipa encouraged the exhibitors from the small enterprise
sector to look into the export market by investing more in
product, packaging and quality improvement.
</P>
<P>
The three-day expo was organized by the Confederation of
Zimbabwe Industries, Zimbabwe enterprise development program and
Zimbabwe trade promotion body. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
