<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Official: Hopeful Signs Seen in Iraqi life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 18 (Xinhua) -- A senior U.N official said
Thursday that hopeful signs can be seen in some aspects of Iraqi
life as a result of the implementation of the first three phases
of U.N. oil-for-food program.
</P>
<P>
"The gap between what is desirable and what is currently
available is beginning to narrow," said the U.N. humanitarian
coordinator in Iraq Dennis Halliday at a news conference Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said water contamination has been substantially lessened in
Baghdad after the use of water-pumping equipment and treatment
chemicals, adding that U.N. relief supplies, especially food and
medicines, have become more constant.
</P>
<P>
The availability of improved seeds, farm tools, pesticides,
tractors has boosted food production, and in some other cases, a
further deterioration is no longer witnessed, the coordinator said.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted that there is still much to be done: drinking
water quality still needs to be improved in many parts of the
country; averting chronic malnutrition needs long time and
requires a balance guide of basic food such as animal protein and
vitamins.
</P>
<P>
He warned the current delay by the member states of the U.N.
Security Council in approving the 300 million U.S. dollars used
for the purchase of spare arts and equipment for Iraqi oil
industry will affect the country's oil output and export in the
fourth phase of the deal starting June 3.
</P>
<P>
"This is expected to have serious consequences for the whole
oil-for-food program, in particular, the enhanced (fourth)
phase. There is a growing concern that we may not reach the
estimated growth target of 4.5 billion U.S. dollars," he said.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi government has said that due to the lack of spare parts,
Iraq can export no more than 4 billion dollars worth of oil in the
fourth phase.
</P>
<P>
Since the U.N. oil-for-food program started in December 1996,
Iraq had been allowed to sell 2 billion dollars worth of oil every
six months to buy food, medicines and humanitarian goods. The
value was raised to 5.2 billion dollars for the fourth phase.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
