<HEADLINE> S. African Policemen Always Armed: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 18 (Xinhua) -- South African off-duty
policemen will not be disarmed, Neels Steenkamp, commissioner of
Police Management, said in Pretoria Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Steenkamp said in a statement that it was evident that attacks
on police members were mainly aimed at seizing their firearms,
but disarming them would render them defless and make them
become easy targets for criminals.
</P>
<P>
For some time, there has been an argument in South African
mass media that off-duty policemen should be disarmed so as to
avoid their weapons being either robbed or stolen.
</P>
<P>
However, Steenkamp said that police members were expected to
come to the assistance of the community and enforce the law,
regardless of whether they were on or off duty.
</P>
<P>
"Services to the community and the self-defense of police
officials cannot be compromised as a result of the incopacty of
the police to perform or to defend themselves," Steenkamp said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Holbrooke to Visit Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 18 (Xinhua) -- U.S. presidential envoy on the
Cyprus problem Richard Holbrooke will visit Greece next Monday for
talks with Greek Foreign Ministry officials, Greek government
spokesman Dimitris Reppas announced here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press briefing, Reppas said that Holbrooke, who
will be accompanied by U.S. State Department Special coordinator
for Cyprus Thomas Miller, will deliver an address at a Greek
university and both he and Miller will have talks with the
political leadership of the Greek Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Recently, Holbrooke, in his capacity as U.S. presidential envoy
on the Cyprus issue, visited the divided island republic in an
effort to bring back the Greek and Turkish Cypriot communities to
the negotiating table, but his mission failed due to the two
sides' positions of not yielding to each other's demands.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops occupied
the northern third of the island in the wake of an abortive-coup
backed by Athens.
</P>
<P>
Greece, a firm supporter to the Cyprus Republic, and
neighboring Turkey have been at odds for decades over their
disputes on a series of issues including the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright is also expected to visit Greece at the end of July as
part of Washington's efforts to mediate the disputes between
Greece and Turkey.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
