<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malawian College's Means for Survival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The cash-strapped College of
Medicine of University of Malawi has started embalming dead
bodies to raise money for its laboratory teaching activities, the
Malawi News Agency MANA reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The assistant lecturer in anatomy of the college, Dr. Steve
Kamiza told the daily Nation Wednesday that embalming service
opened to the public two months ago "as part of fund raising in
view of the financial hardships."
</P>
<P>
He said surface perfusion, a process that preserves the body
for four weeks before it decomposes costs 2,500 Malawian Kwacha
(some 100 U.S. Dollars) while visceral perfusion that can keep
the body for "years costs 5,000 Kwacha (about 200 U.S. Dollars)
and vascular perfusion that maintains the body for up to five
years costs 10,000 Kwacha (about 400 U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
"Ours is a professional embalming... we have a professional
specialist from South Africa," said Kamiza.
</P>
<P>
He said that mourners are, however, not allowed within the
college premises during embalming process to avoid disturbing
classes.
</P>
<P>
"It should be emphasised that we do not allow people wailing
within the campus. We only do the embalming. We collect the
body from the hospital's (Queen Elizabeth Central Hospital)
mortuary and return it later.
</P>
<P>
"We don't keep bodies at our campus as it is strictly a
learning institution,"said Kamiza.
</P>
<P>
However, embalming service had been introduced to the college
for purposes of training anatomy trainee doctors.
</P>
<P>
Vice-chancellor of the University of Malawi Professor Brown
Chimphamba confirmed that the College of Medicine is at the
moment cash-strapped "and so is the whole University of Malawi.
</P>
<P>
"It is,therefore, not a surprise that the College of Medicine
has gone into such a fund raising venture," he said.
</P>
<P>
Chimphamba added, "the college is very young. It would,
therefore, not be a surprise that it is in such financial
constraints."
</P>
<P>
The College of Medicine which is less than 10 years old is one
of the five constituent colleges of the University of Malawi. The
others are Chancellor College, an arts college, Bunda College, an
agricultural college, the Polytechnic that offers technical and
engineering courses and Kamuzu College of Nursing offering
midwifery and nursing courses.
</P>
<P>
The University of Malawi just like other government subsidized
statutory corporations is facing financial hardships at the
moment mostly due to the structural adjustment program the
Malawian government has adopted under the influence from the
International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
Under the program, the Malawian government has instituted the
Cash Budget System under which departments and ministries have to
spend according to the amount of money allocated to them by
treasury -- which in most cases is inadequate -- and no extra
cash is given regardless of any eventuality. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> E. Africa Agrees on Further Military Coop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Defense leaders of Kenya, Tanzania
and Uganda Thursday adopted at the end of their meeting a
strategy for further military cooperation under the auspices of
East African Cooperation (EAC).
</P>
<P>
The strategy ranges from confidence building measures
including training and joint exercises, the integration of
military training facilities and systems, military research and
production measures, they said in a joint statement.
</P>
<P>
"The strategy is intended to culminate in the conclusion of a
Defense Pact" formed in the northern Tanzanian town of Arusha on
April 30, said Tanzanian Minister of Defense and National Service
Edgar Dionies Maokola-Majogo, who chaired the meeting.
</P>
<P>
"We are meeting and discussing security issues" with an eye to
maintaining peace in east Africa as "defense and security were a
necessary pre-requisite for the region's economic and social
development," Maokola-Majogo noted.
</P>
<P>
The military leaders agreed on the holding of regular meetings
with the next one being proposed for October in Kampala, Uganda's
capital.
</P>
<P>
They also signed an Addendum to the Memorandum of
Understanding on Cooperation in Defense and a Status of Forces
Agreement which regulate the legal status of members states'
defense forces while on visits in each other's territories.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Minister of State in the Office of the President in
Charge of Defense Giedon Ndambuki, Ugandan Minister of State for
Political Affairs Amama Mbabazi, as well as EAC Executive
Secretary Francis Muthaura attended the one-day meeting.
</P>
<P>
Also present were the three chiefs of defense forces --
General R.P. Mboma of Tanzania, General D.R. C. Tonje of Kenya
and Major General Jeje Odongo of Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The meeting came in the wake of the three countries' on-going
joint peace keeping military exercise, code-named Natural Fire
'98, in Lodwar, northwestern Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Maokola-Majogo said the three nations prefer to train their
military personnel with peace keeping skills so as to be able to
"convene this force when it is needed."
</P>
<P>
"This is the best approach," he claimed, saying the three
countries have no plans in the near future to set up a joint
regular peace-keeping force.
</P>
<P>
"Let's share the knowledge and take needs," he said.
</P>
<P>
The ministers will go to Lodwar Friday to view the exercise,
the first-ever of this kind in the east African region, according
to their joint statement.
</P>
<P>
About 2,000 soldiers from the three states, together with some
120 U.S. army trainers, now have entered the final stage of the
mock peace keeping operation which is set to end on June 27,
Kenya Defense Ministry's spokesman George Nyakundi told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The exercise, starting on June 2, aims to expose the soldiers
to future involvement in multi-national peace keeping operations
under the auspices of the Organization of African Unity and the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
It focuses on dealing with a hypothetical state called
Somanga, and the forces work to restore order, said Nyakundi.
</P>
<P>
Defense experts of the three states met in Arusha on June 1-6
to work out the modalities for implementing the defense
memorandum, signed on April 30, including the establishment of a
joint military liaison office at the EAC secretariat in Arusha.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0022 </DOCNO>
