<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1st Health Lab Opens in Mogadishu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Somalia's capital Mogadishu has
had a top class health laboratory for the first time since the
beginning of the civil war after toppling former President Siad
Barre in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The Public Health Central Laboratory which opened in Forlanini
Hospital Tuesday is a community project invested by the United
Nations World Health Organization (WHO).
</P>
<P>
The lab, co-sponsored by the Joint Health Authority of
Mogadishu, was designed for analyzing various germs, the HIV
virus, the parasites, as well as the cholera germ which are now
tightening its grip on the people in Mogadishu and elsewhere in
Somalia.
</P>
<P>
According to WHO, the lab cost of nearly 50,000 U.S. Dollars
includes equipment as well as the necessary reagents for making
the analysis of the deadly diseases when there's an outbreak of a
disease of one kind or another.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony Tuesday, the WHO country
representative in Mogadishu, Dr. Abdukarim Assayr Ali, said the
lab is open to all Somalis in an effort of minimizing the time
and risk of taking the samples abroad.
</P>
<P>
Cholera and other samples were taken to Nairobi, Kenya, or
Johannesburg, South Africa, for analyzing the existence of the
suspected diseases in the past.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Ali said WHO will keep maintaining the laboratory for the
next three months by supplying the reagents and paying a little
incentive to the nine local lab technicians in the facility.
</P>
<P>
During these three months, people will pay one-third of the
normal expenses for each sample to be tested, and will pay for
the full expenses after this period so as to enable the project
to become self-sustaining.
</P>
<P>
It has already tested 15 samples taken from patients in the
quarantines of Benadir and Forlanini hospitals, and seven out of
the eight tested samples from Benadir hospital have shown cholera
positive while another six out of the seven samples from
Forlanini quarantine have also shown cholera positive.
</P>
<P>
The laboratory is being safeguarded by well-armed militiamen
belonging to Forlanini Hospital to avoid the repetition of the
event in which the gangs recently ransacked the second largest
soccer stadium which is only about 300 meters away from the lab
in Mogadishu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Observes Day of African Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of African
Unity (OAU) organized a discussion with a theme of "Children and
the Education Decade" at Africa Hall here Thursday afternoon to
mark "the Day of African Children."
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the discussion, an OAU representative said that
education is a key for development and the education decade
provides all boys and girls with free and compulsory education.
</P>
<P>
United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF) also called on African
countries to carry out the programs of the education decade.
</P>
<P>
In July 1996, African leaders adopted in Yaounde, Cameroun, a
resolution on the launching of the Decade of Education in Africa
(1997-2006).
</P>
<P>
The resolution and the decade plan of action adopted by the
African education ministers later gave an excellent opportunity
for the OAU member states and their development partners to
achieve various goals in the field of education.
</P>
<P>
This includes programs emanating from the Jomtien Declaration
on Education for All, the Ouagadougou and Kampala declarations on
education of girls and women, the Segou Perspective, the Accra
Charter and declaration on the promotion of African languages in
education, and etc.
</P>
<P>
School children and panelists comprising ministers of
education, labor and social affairs, women's affairs, finance or
their representatives as well as officials from the OAU, the
United Nations Economic Commission for Africa (ECA), the World
Bank and some other U.N. agencies attended the workshop.
</P>
<P>
June 16 was designated by the 26th Session of the OAU Summit
in 1990 as "the Day of African Children" in remembrance of the
massacre perpetrated by the racist regime of then South Africa in
Soweto in which many innocent children lost their lives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kohl Repeats Demand for Big Cut in Germany's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 18 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl
Thursday repeated his demand for a big reduction in Germany's
payments to the European Union budget.
</P>
<P>
Noting that Germany now shouldered about 28 percent of the EU
budget, Kohl told the German parliament on Thursday that "We will
remain in the future a large contributor but we want a fair and
just share".
</P>
<P>
The EU should work out a fairer method of billing its members
by March 1999, Kohl said.
</P>
<P>
The demand first raised by Kohl at the recent EU summit in
Cardiff, Wales, has struck big controversies among the EU members.
</P>
<P>
While Kohl won predictable support with the Netherlands, Sweden
and Austria, which are the other big net payers into the EU
budget, he got a stiff rebuff from other nations including Spain
and France which are benefiting from the current EU budget scheme.
</P>
<P>
By adopting the tough new stance on the budget issue, Kohl
apparently wanted to score points with German voters with the
country's general elections just three months away.
</P>
<P>
Germany currently pays about 11 billion Ecus (12 billion U.S.
dollars) more than it gets back in farm and development subsidies
from the EU annually, nearly four times as much as Britain, the
next biggest net contributor.
</P>
<P>
Officials said that Germany wanted to slash its EU payments by
about seven billion German marks annually (four billion U.S.
dollars), a cut that would certainly be welcomed by German
taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
Observers, however, warned that the EU budget dispute would
carry the risk to undermine its enlargement process.
</P>
<P>
Germany's new tight-fisted stance would either mean a delay to
the EU enlargement, or less money for potential new members than
poorer EU nations have won in the past, they said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Russian Officials to Visit Yugoslavia, Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Two Russian deputy foreign
ministers will leave for Yugoslavia and Albania on Sunday to
promote settlement of the Kosovo conflict, according to the
Itar-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Foreign Minister Nikolai Afanasyevsky is to fly to
Yugoslavia to facilitate the settlement and elaborate on the joint
statement by the Russian and Yugoslav presidents, Foreign
Ministry's spokesman Vladimir Rakhmanin told a briefing on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Afanasyevsky will visit Belgrade and Pristina, the capital of
the autonomous Kosovo province, and meet with their leaders and
delegation members at the talks with Kosovo's Albanians, the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Another Deputy Foreign Minister Alexander Avdeyev will visit
Tirana and Skopje, the capitals of Albania and Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
Rakhmanin said that Moscow regards the results of the
negotiations between the Russian and Yugoslav presidents held on
Tuesday "as a big step towards preventing violence in Kosovo and
diverting the crisis into a peaceful channel."
</P>
<P>
Moscow believes that in settlement of the Kosovo conflict much
depends on how actively President Slobodan Milosevic will meet the
obligations he has assumed, the spokesman noted.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the readiness of Kosovo Albanians to return
to the negotiations assumes major significance, he said.
</P>
<P>
Rukhmanin emphasized that it is necessary to dispel separatist
illusions, to reiterate the position which unequivocally condemns
terror and violence used by the Kosovo Liberation Army and make a
statement in support of Yugoslavia's territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
An armed conflict occurred between the Yugoslav government and
ethnic Albanians, who are seeking for independence, in Kosovo in
February. Since then, more than 300 people have died in clashes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCarthy Saves South Africa from Elimination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOULOUSE, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Benedict McCarthy scored a
second-half equalizer against Danmark here on Thursday to keep South
Africa's hope for the last 16 alive in the soccer World Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
Three players were sent off in the Group C contest held between the
former European champion and the African upstart in Municipal Stadium
here.
</P>
<P>
After trailing Denmark 1-0, Ajax Amsterdam striker McCarthy slotted
the ball home from in the box seven minutes into the second half after
some dazzling short passes.
</P>
<P>
John Moshoeu tapped the ball toward striker Shaun Bartlett, who
chipped it to 21-year-old McCarthy to score.
</P>
<P>
Allen Nielsen gave Denmark a 1-0 lead by netting on a Brian Laudrup
pass from right in the 12th minute.
</P>
<P>
Denmark, who dominated the first half, almost made it 2-0 in the
40th minute had a blast from Ebbe Sand not hit the right-hand post.
</P>
<P>
The Bafana Bafana boys rallied strongly after break, melting the
Danish defence which had been impenetrable in the first half.
</P>
<P>
Referee John Toro Rendon flashed two red cards within three minutes
from 67th to 69th minutes, dispatching Denmark's Miklos Molnar first
and then South African Alfred Phiri.
</P>
<P>
The Danes were further reduced to 9 men after substitute Morten
Wieghorst was given the marching order in the 40th minute, only his
third minutes on pitch.
</P>
<P>
Quinton Fortune almost clinched a victory for South Africa in
injury time when his 30-meter shot hit the crossbar.
</P>
<P>
Besides the red cards, the seven yellow cards, four to South Africa
and three to Denmark, also made record in the competition so far, 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0028 </DOCNO>
