<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Meets George Bush </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin met
Thursday with former U.S. president George Bush in the Kremlin,
saying that the two laid the the foundation for ending the "Cold
War".
</P>
<P>
Bush is here on a private visit.
</P>
<P>
"We have become friends and began to resolve matters, using
exactly the same key," Yeltsin said. "The history of our relations
with George heralded an entirely new page in the history of
Russian diplomacy."
</P>
<P>
"The presidents of the two countries, former enemies who used
to grind knives against each other, have turned everything upside
down and went as far as reducing strategic weapons," Yeltsin said.
</P>
<P>
He said the two leaders had turned a new page in social,
cultural and human relations between the two countries and had
permanently removed an "iron curtain".
</P>
<P>
"There are no bans left between us -- this is what has been
achieved by the history of our presidency," Yeltsin added.
</P>
<P>
Bush, for his part, expressed the hope that Yeltsin would
continue the course of reforms he launched.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
