<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Diamond Sales Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 18 (Xinhua) -- South African diamond giant
De Beers' Central Selling Organization (CSO) Thursday reported a
41 percent drop to 1.7 billion U.S. Dollars in first half year's
rough gem diamond sales, the lowest since 1992.
</P>
<P>
The fall in sales followed the CSO attempts to curb
overstocking in the industry which has been hit by shrinking
retail diamond markets in Japan and southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
The 1.7-billion-U.S.-Dollar sales figure, sharply down on last
year's first half sales, is slightly better than the consensus
forecast of 1.55 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The daily Business Day Thursday quoted analyst Des Mayers as
saying that the CSO could probably sell more in the second half
year, but would have to watch developments in Asia carefully.
</P>
<P>
The danger is that growth could slow down in the United States
before Asia recovers, Mayers said.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts believed that there is no guarantee that, even
if Asia recovered, its consumers would start buying diamonds.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and the southeast Asian region normally are major
consumers of diamond in the the world.
</P>
<P>
The U.S., which used to account for about 28 percent of the
world's retail diamond market, now accounts for more than 35
percent as other important markets have declined.
</P>
<P>
At their peak in 1996, the Japanese and southeast Asian
markets together accounted for about 40 percent of the market.
</P>
<P>
De Beers reported strong growth this year in retail sales of
diamond jewellery in the U.S., Canada, India and Europe. Sales
in the Gulf states and China continued at reasonable levels but
the markets in Japan, Korea, Thailand and Indonesia declined
further.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
