<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt, Iran Gear Up Efforts to Mend Rift: Moussa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa
said Thursday that Egypt and Iran are stepping up efforts to mend
the rift in their long-strained relationship.
</P>
<P>
Moussa made the statement to reporters here when asked to
comment on the progress Iran has made in its efforts to end
decades of hostilities with the United States, Saudi Arabia and
other countries.
</P>
<P>
Iran's new, moderate President Mohammad Khatami proposed early
this year people-to-people exchanges with the U.S. as a way to
start a new friendship, which makes a thaw in those relations
possible.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said that the new development was in fact preceded by
progress in Cairo-Tehran ties last winter when then Iranian
Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati paid a crucial visit to Cairo
to kick off the process of fence-mending.
</P>
<P>
As a sign of entent between Cairo and Tehran, Moussa said, he
received this week a large Iranian economic delegation here and
witnessed the signing of a protocol for boosting bilateral
cooperation in industry, investment and trade.
</P>
<P>
The visit was the first of its kind in nearly 20 years. "There
is movement in Egyptian-Iranian relations at the present time,"
Moussa said, and voiced hope that the relations will take a
positive turn as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Moussa added that contacts between the two countries are now
continuing at the foreign ministerial level within the framework
of the Organization of the Islamic Conference, of which both are
members.
</P>
<P>
Iran disrupted diplomatic and political ties with Egypt after
late Egyptian President Anwar el-Sadat visited Israel to launch
his peace initiative in 1979, the year of Iran's Islamic
Revolution. They became even more hostile to each other after
Cairo accused Tehran of backing Egyptian Muslim militants fighting
to overthrow the secular government.
</P>
<P>
The ice in Egyptian-Iranian ties began to thaw in recent years,
and bilateral trade started to picks up. In 1997 alone their trade
volume reached 75 million U.S. dollars, and Iran is investing 220
million Egyptian pounds (some 64.7 million dollars) in seven
projects of weaving, carpets, ready-made garments and banks in
Egypt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
