<HEADLINE> Egypt to Join Regional Common Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Egypt is to join the Common Market
of East and South Africa (COMESA) later this month in a bid to
strengthen its economic and trade links with other African states.
</P>
<P>
The official signing of the agreement on Egypt's membership of
COMESA will take place on June 29 at the opening session of the
group's summit in Kinshasa, capital of the Democratic Republic of
the Congo.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Amr Moussa will lead an Egyptian delegation to
the 5th COMESA ministerial meeting due to be held in Kinshasa on
June 25-27.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian cabinet on Tuesday endorsed the Egyptian
membership of COMESA, believing this will promote Egypt's trade
and investment relations with the 19 COMESA members, Assistant to
the Foreign Minister on African Affairs Mohamed Shaaban told
reporters Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Trade and investment activities among the COMESA states will be
carried out through a free trade zone of 350 million inhabitants
with exports worth 17 billion U.S. dollars and imports of 25
billion dollars, he said.
</P>
<P>
The volume of trade between Egypt and the COMESA members
currently stands at 2.5 billion dollars, and is expected to rise
to 4 billion dollars, Shaaban added.
</P>
<P>
"Joining COMESA will open the door to an increase of Egypt's
exports to the group's members as well as a tax exemption of up to
90 percent by October, and 100 percent by the turn of the
century," he said.
</P>
<P>
Shaaban is to leave here Friday for Kinshasa to attend the
COMESA governmental committee meetings.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Transport Metwalli Soliman will also lead Egypt's
delegation at the first special meeting of the COMESA Ministers of
Communications on June 24 in Kinshasa, Shaaban said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
