<HEADLINE> Cyprus Condemns Turkish Violations of Airspace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government on Thursday
condemned the new violations of Cyprus airspace by Turkish
military aircraft.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement, government spokesman Christos
Stylianides said that Cyprus "is taking the necessary diplomatic
action" concerning the Turkish "provocative violation."
</P>
<P>
"The government is calmly monitoring Turkish attempts to
create artificial tension," Stylianides said.
</P>
<P>
He also reiterated the government's insistence on the
implementation of international law and its proposal for
demilitarization of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Six Turkish F-16 fighters flew low over both the Greek and
Turkish Cypriot sectors of the divided capital, Nicosia, around
12:00 local time (0900 GMT) Thursday and then landed at the
Lefkoniko airport in the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north.
</P>
<P>
According to Turkish officials, the warplanes were sent in
retaliation for the landing of six Greek warplanes at the Paphos
military air base in the Greek Cypriot-dominated southern part of
the island earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Cyprus had protested the visit by five Turkish
navy warships to the ports of Kyrenia and Famagusta in northern
part of the island.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot-controlled
south and the Turkish Cypriot-dominated north since 1974 when
Turkey landed troops and occupied the northern third in the wake
of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
Tension has been heightened on the island since January of
last year when Cyprus ordered S-300 anti-aircraft missiles from
Russia, whose delivery is scheduled for later this year.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has threatened to take all necessary measures to
prevent the deployment of these Russian-made missiles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
