<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zanzibar Short of External Hotel Experts: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Zanzibar is short of
external hotel experts although tourism is the leading industry
in the isles, a senior government official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Idi Pandu Hassan, the Minister of State who is responsible for
constitutional and legal affairs, said at the House of
Representatives that non-islanders constitute a mere 14 percent
of all workers in the leading privately owned hotels.
</P>
<P>
Hassan said 11 people from Kenya and 225 from the mainland of
Tanzania have been employed in 10 leading privately owned hotels
in the isles.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, he said a total of 1,400 people in the hotels are
Zanzibaris, according to a report reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The minister was responding to a question of Haji Mkema Haji,
a member of parliament from Koani, who wanted to know the number
of workers from the outside who are employed in Zanzibar hotels.
</P>
<P>
The isles investment regulations spell out that Zanzibaris
should be given priority in employment opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Zanzibar President Salmin Amour in late April said the
government has been striving to make tourism the principal
foreign exchange earner to replace cloves exports after the
prices of the cash crop plunged in the world market in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
Amour called on Zanzibar residents to give full support to
foreign investors in developing the tourism industry so as to
tide over the isle's economic hardships.
</P>
<P>
Zanzibar, part of Tanzania, is separated from the African
continent by a 21-mile corridor at its narrowest point. It
comprises the twin islands of Unguja and Pemba and more than 20
smaller islands in the Indian Ocean.  
</P>
</TEXT>
