<HEADLINE> OAU Delegation Works for Peaceful Solution of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The delegation of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) Thursday met with Ethiopian
Prime Minister Meles Zenawi on the peaceful resolution of the
dispute between Ethiopia and Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
The OAU delegation, appointed by the 34th OAU summit meeting
in Ouagadougou, Burkina Faso, earlier this month, comprises
Blaise Compaore, president of Burkina Faso, who is the current
chairman of the OAU, Robert Mugabe, Zimbabwean president and
outgoing OAU chairman, Pasteur Bezimungou, Rwandan president,
and Mohamed Mousa Shehim, Djibouti Foreign Minister who is
current chairman of the Inter-Governmental Authority on
Development (IGAD), as well as OAU Secretary-General Salim Ahmed
Salim.
</P>
<P>
"We have had very good discussion with the prime minister,"
said Salim.
</P>
<P>
According to the OAU chief, the delegation represents Africa's
collective concern on the situation and its desire to contribute
in every way possible to put an end to the current conflict.
</P>
<P>
African leaders, Salim said, have characterized the crisis as
a conflict that affects not only the two countries but also
countries in the region and Africa as a whole.
</P>
<P>
"We have come here on the basis of the urging of the heads of
states in Ouagadougou for a cessation of hostilities and for the
implementation of the efforts which are made by the
facilitators," Salim said.
</P>
<P>
He said the OAU delegation will look into what the problem
areas are and what can be done to ensure that the peace process
is on course.
</P>
<P>
The OAU delegation left here Thursday afternoon for Asmara on
a similar mission and is expected to return here this evening.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the spokesperson of the Ethiopian government
announced Thursday that the Ethiopian government is currently
holding 140 Eritrean national conscripts at a center in the town
of Fiche, about 100 km from Addis Ababa.
</P>
<P>
"Journalists, the International Committee of the Red Cross
(ICRC) and other organizations are allowed free access to these
detainees who are being held purely for reasons of national
security," the spokesperson said.
</P>
<P>
"Eritrea has detained more than 530 Ethiopian civilians and
has refused access to them by the ICRC and journalists," the
spokesman added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
