<HEADLINE> Turkey Condemns Greece's Landing Warplanes in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Deputy Prime Minister
Bulent Ecevit Thursday accused Greece of escalating tension in
Cyprus by landing its warplanes on the divided island.
</P>
<P>
The military movements displayed the Greek government's
"expansionist plan" concerning the eastern Mediterranean country,
Anatolia News Agency quoted Ecevit as saying in Istanbul, the
largest city of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The criticism came as four F-16 fighters and two C-130
transport planes belonging to the Greek Air Force touched down at
an air base near the western town of Paphos in the Greek
Cypriot-dominated part of Cyprus on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit, who ordered a military intervention in 1974 when he
was the then prime minister, said that Turkey would use its air
force to "maintain tranquility in Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
Also on Thursday, Turkey's six F-16 fighters landed at the
Gecitkale Air Base in northern Cyprus in response to Greece's
military movements on the island.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem stated that
Turkey would take all necessary steps to protect the security of
Turkish Cypriots and Turkey itself.
</P>
<P>
There were reports that Turkish Foreign Ministry had
instructed its embassies in member states of the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization to brief these countries on "the latest
provocations by Greece."
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Greece and Cyprus have condemned the
landing of the Turkish fighters in northern Cyprus, describing it
as "an illegal move."
</P>
<P>
Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros Pangalos said in Athens that
those countries selling arms to Turkey should also be held
responsible for the current tension in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into Greek Cypriot-dominated south and
Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkish troops
landed and took over the northern third of the small island in the
wake of an abortive coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
At present, some 35,000 to 50,000 Turkish troops are stationed
in the northern part of Cyprus with a claimed aim to protect
Turkish Cypriots who unilaterally declared "Turkish Republic of
Northern Cyprus" now only recognized by Ankara. 
</P>
</TEXT>
