<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Urges Ethiopia, Eritrea to Stop Fighting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Foreign Minister Jawad
Anani urged here Thursday Ethiopia and Eritrea to cease their border
clashes "for the sake of regional stability."
</P>
<P>
"Any conflict in the Horn of Africa implies a far-reaching
security impact that would affect the entire region," Anani told
reporters after meeting the Ethiopian envoy and Minister of
Industry and Trade Ali Sayyed Abdallah, who arrived here Wednesday
for a two-day visit.
</P>
<P>
"The Red Sea is an Arab sea as many countries overlooking
it are Arab countries, and therefore we are concerned about its
security," said Anani.
</P>
<P>
For Jordan, its Red Sea port of Aqaba is the only sea outlet
that links it with the outside world. Amman is therefore
especially concerned about the Red Sea security, Anani added.
</P>
<P>
The Red Sea is surrounded by Egypt, Jordan, Saudi Arabia,
Yemen, Ethiopia, Eritrea and Sudan. The Ethiopian-Eritrean border
conflict broke out in early May, and has claimed hundreds of
lives.
</P>
<P>
Anani called for both parties to exercise restraint and wisdom
to end their armed conflict.
</P>
<P>
Asked if Jordan will join Egypt's effort to cease the conflict,
Anani said that "if there is a need for such a mediation, then it
could be made in coordination with our brothers in Egypt and we
are ready for this."
</P>
<P>
African leaders have already started mediation between Ethiopia
and Eritrea to end the bloodshed. On Thursday, a delegation of the
Organization of African Unity met with Ethiopian Prime Minister
Meles Zenawi in Addis Ababa to to discuss ways to end the fighting.
</P>
<P>
Under the U.S. and Italian pressure, Ethiopia and Eritrea agreed
on Sunday to halt air bombings, and the ground fighting has also
subsided since one week ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
