<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Philippine Gov't Sees Budget Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government's
swelling budget deficit is seen as the biggest challenge the new
administration of President-elect Joseph Estrada who will take
office on June 30.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a briefing on Estrada's economic agenda on Friday,
incoming Finance Secretary Edgardo Espiritu told reporters that
the deficit could get worse to hit 30 billion pesos (750 million
U.S. dollars) by the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The current government, which targeted a 5 billion pesos (125
million dollars) budget surplus, said earlier the deficit surged
to 15.4 billion pesos (385 million dollars) for the first five
months of the year due to revenue shortfalls.
</P>
<P>
The government has posted a budget surplus annually during the
past three years, at 39 million dollars in 1997, 156 million
dollars in 1996 and 275 million dollars in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Espiritu also predicted a continued rise in the country's
average of commodity prices or inflation which hit a two-year high
of 9.2 percent in May with 1988 as the base year.
</P>
<P>
Espiritu said the impact of the Asian financial crisis on
commodity prices has not yet fully displayed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
