others has gone against us, but we can compensate with our speed," he
added.
</P>
<P>
"This match is of ocurse very important for Japanese football in
view of the next World Cup but it is especially so fi we are to
qualify for the second round," Okada said.
</P>
<P>
Remarks from captain Masami Ihara echoed Okada's views.
</P>
<P>
"It's an important match as far as qualification goes and we're
prepared to take some risks. We also have to keep an eye on the
refereeing; after what happened yesterday this has become something to
take into consideration," Ihara said.
</P>
<P>
A total of five players were sent off in two games on Thursday,
including the record-making three substitutes ousted in the clash
between South Africa and Denmark.
</P>
<P>
Ihara said his team would put on a more offensive face against
Croatia but what worried him most was the opponents' strong midfield.
</P>
<P>
Brazilian-born striker Wagner Lopes said Japan still had chance to
win although teammate Hidetoshi Nakata thought the chance was low.
</P>
<P>
