<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Geneva to Host Eighth Annual Internet Society Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Swiss city of Geneva will host
the eighth annual Internet Society Conference scheduled on July
21-24, the organizers announced here Friday.
</P>
<P>
One of the major issues at the so-called Internet Summit will
be the future of the Internet's domain naming system.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from more than 120 countries are expected to
discuss the next major steps needed to assist in the definition
and development of a non-profit corporation, Internet Assigned
Names Authority (IANA).
</P>
<P>
The organizers expect that about 3,000 stakeholders, policy
makers and Internet leaders around the world will be attending the
conference.
</P>
<P>
To help promote the Internet in the developing countries, a
special symposium will be held on the matter during the meeting.
</P>
<P>
"Hands-on" training will be given to professionals who will
play a vital role in establishing the Internet's presence in their
countries or facilitating the efforts of schools, government
agencies, businesses, and residents to learn about and exploit
Internet services.
</P>
<P>
As the conference is not a purely technical one, 11 tutorials
will be set up to help visitors understand the Internet.
</P>
<P>
The Internet Society is a U.S.-based non-profitable
international organization. Since 1992, it has served as the
international organization for global coordination and cooperation
on the Internet, promoting and maintaining a broad spectrum of
activities focused on the Internet's development, availability and
associated technologies.
</P>
<P>
The first Internet Society Conference was held in 1991, when an
estimated four million people had access to the Internet.  
</P>
</TEXT>
