<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netherlands Launches WTO Program for Developing Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Netherlands has launched a new
training program for developing countries, announced the World
Trade Organization (WTO) here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, trainees from developing countries will
learn more about trade and development-related matters and improve
their knowledge of trade policy.
</P>
<P>
"Effective integration of developing countries in the
international trading system is crucial, not only for their
development, but also for the credibility of the WTO as a world
trade organization," said Dutch Permanent Representative Eveline
Herfkens.
</P>
<P>
"This requires the institutional capacity in these countries to
deal with WTO matters," he said. "Through this initiative, we hope
to make a modest contribution to this effect."
</P>
<P>
Initially, there will be up to three trainees per year, whose
selection and recruitment shall be made by the WTO secretariat.
</P>
<P>
Trainees will be considered as WTO staff members during their
assignment and will receive a normal salary, but will not take up
regular staff posts.
</P>
<P>
While working for the WTO, they will receive training for a
maximum of two years and then go back and contribute to the
strengthening of their countries' institutional capacity.
</P>
<P>
The content and duration of the assignment vary for each
candidate, depending on their circumstances.
</P>
<P>
The Netherlands will meet all costs involved with the trainees.
</P>
<P>
In coming weeks, the WTO secretariat will finalize arrangements
for selection and recruitment, the development of tailor-made
programs and the supervision of trainees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
