<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Duma Sets Up Impeachment Commission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Russian State Duma, the lower
house of parliament, on Friday adopted a decision to form a
special commission for the impeachment of President Boris Yeltsin,
the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The decision was taken by 331 votes in favor and five against,
no abstention.
</P>
<P>
The special commission consists of 15 representatives of all
parliamentary groups and is headed by Vadim Filimonov, communist.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Duma also approved the impeachment commission
regulations.
</P>
<P>
It was said that the initiative of forming the commission came
from the faction of Communists.
</P>
<P>
Under the Russian constitution the president may be impeached
by the Federation Council "only on the grounds of Duma charges of
high treason or committing some other grave crime." The charges
should be confirmed by a Supreme Court ruling.
</P>
<P>
According to another report, the Yabloko party said on Friday
that the nation was increasingly discontented with the
government's policy and that this meant Yeltsin would soon leave
office.
</P>
<P>
Yabloko in its statement circulated in the Duma noted that "A
serious wave of discontent is giving rise to increasingly loud
calls for the dismissal of the Russian president."
</P>
<P>
At the same day coal miners who have for nine days been
striking outside Russian government headquarters in Moscow urged
parliament to back a proposal for impeachment of the president.
</P>
<P>
However, Chairman of the State Duma Gennady Seleznyov said on
Friday that a motion for impeaching the president was unlikely to
drum up enough support in the lower house in fall this year.
</P>
<P>
Such a motion would hardly muster 300 votes in the State Duma,
the minimum it would need to be carried, Seleznyov told a news
conference.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
