<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 14:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Protests Turkey's Violations of Airspace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus has lodged a strong
protest to the U.N. General Secretariat against recent violations
of its airspace by Turkish warplanes.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the U.N. dated on Friday, Cyprus' Permanent
Representative to the U.N. Sotos Zackheos said that "it should
be stressed to the Turkish side that these actions are in
violation of international law and Turkey should act according to
the principles and norms of this law."
</P>
<P>
He was referring to the violations of Cyprus' airspace by six
Turkish F-16 fighters which flew low over both the Greek and
Turkish Cypriot sectors of the divided capital, Nicosia, around
12:00 local time (0900 GMT) Thursday and then landed at the
Lefkoniko airport in the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north.
</P>
<P>
According to Turkish officials, the Turkish warplanes were
sent in retaliation for the landing of six Greek warplanes at the
Paphos military air base in the Greek Cypriot-dominated southern
part of the island earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
Cypriot government spokesman Christos Stylianides Thursday
accused Turkey of creating an "artificial tension" by sending
warplanes over its airspace.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Cyprus also protested the visit by five Turkish
navy warships to the ports of Kyrenia and Famagusta in northern
part of the island.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot-controlled
south and the Turkish Cypriot-dominated north since 1974 when
Turkey landed its troops and occupied the northern third in the
wake of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
Tension has been heightened on this Eastern Mediterranean
island since January last year when Cyprus ordered S-300
anti-aircraft missiles from Russia, whose delivery is scheduled
for later this year.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, which has kept 35,000 troops in northern Cyprus, has
threatened to take all necessary measures to prevent the
deployment of these Russian-made missiles on the island.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
