<HEADLINE> Zambia: Over 700 Arrested for Drug-Related </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- More than 700 people have been
arrested in Zambia for suspected drug-related charges in the last
five months, according to the Drug Enforcement Commission (DEC).
</P>
<P>
DEC spokesman Mukutulu Sinyani said Thursday that among the
711 arrested, 264 people have been convicted and were serving
various jail sentences, the Zambia Daily Mail newspaper reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Sinyani as saying that of the arrested, 675
were Zambians, 11 Tanzanians, six South Africans, four each from
Malawi and Zimbabwe, three Somalis, two Congolese, one each from
India, Lebanon, Sweden, Canada, Britain and Ghana, bringing the
number of foreigners to 36 arrested on drug charges.
</P>
<P>
He added that DEC has seized five kg of opium, 48 kg of khat
(also known as miraa) and 2.7 tons of marijuana during the past
five months.
</P>
<P>
In the past years, Zambia has become an international transit
point for drug traffickers and about 20 percent of the drugs are
consumed locally, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
