<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Legislators Plan To Improve Rural Democracy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The coming third meeting of the
Ninth Standing Committee of China's National People's Congress
will discuss revising the Village Committee Organization Law to
urge greater clarity in village management.
</P>
<P>
This will affect more than 900,000 villages in China and 900
million people. A draft specifies the system of democratic
election for village heads and provides for tighter supervision,
according to Zhang Mingliang, director of the Civil Affairs
Ministry's Grassroots Power Building Department.
</P>
<P>
China passed the Law in November 1987, putting an end to the
practice of picking village heads at the government level.
</P>
<P>
It says that all members of the village committee, the formal
village leadership, are to be directly elected by the village, and
in the past decade, most Chinese villages have held three direct
elections, greatly increasing democracy in China, Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
"The law protects the democratic rights and basic interests of
all Chinese villagers," he explains.
</P>
<P>
It also stipulates that village committees make public a list
of the village's assets, incomes, expenditures, land leases, and
building permits. And, this open management of village affairs
effectively keeps dishonest village heads from benefiting
personally by using their power, Zhang says.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
