<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia's Inflation to Rise by 20 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's inflation might ascend
above 20 percent while the Kwacha is expected to hit 2,200 for
one U.S. Dollar depreciation in the second half of the year,
Zambia Daily Mail reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted the latest Business Trends published by
Standard Chartered Bank Zambia as saying that the nine percent
target for the year-end is no longer meaningful and that with the
current situation, inflation is likely to push upward, already
its averaging in the 20 percent range.
</P>
<P>
In the second half, inflation can be expected to accelerate,
partly for statistical reasons, but also as the knock-on effects
of currency devaluation and wage push inflation starts to bite,
said the publication.
</P>
<P>
However, over the whole year, inflation is expected to fall
modestly below last year's 24.8 percent. An average of 22 percent
to 23 is being forecast.
</P>
<P>
The bank said that the decline in the country's copper
earnings and low disbursement of donor money are some of the
factors that have caused a foreign exchange drought, causing a
steep fall in the Kwacha from 1300 last December to 1970 against
one Dollar at present.
</P>
<P>
The Kwacha depreciation might have impact on the consumer
prices in the second half of the year leading to wage increases
which would in effect generate a degree of wage-push inflation,
predicted the bank document.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to control inflation and protect the Kwacha, the
Bank of Zambia, the country's central bank, said monetary policy
would be tightened to curb demand for foreign exchange, pointing
to lower monetary growth and higher interest rates for the rest
of the year.
</P>
<P>
The year is expected to end on a bad financial base, and "the
extremely ambitious 1999 inflation target of four percent now
also looks unrealistic and it is questionable whether in fact, so
low an inflation rate is consistent with the government growth
rate," said the publication. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
