<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Not to Seek Third Term </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin on
Friday said he would not seek a third term in office in 2000 when
the next presidential elections are held.
</P>
<P>
On a short visit to Kostroma region northeast of Moscow,
Yeltsin told students of the Kostroma Agricultural Academy that he
would not run for a third term.
</P>
<P>
"No, that is not allowed by the constitution," he added.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin, who is serving his second term, has repeatedly fudged
on the issue over the last few months, sometimes leaving doubts on
whether he would run, then ruling out a third term.
</P>
<P>
The president also advised the faculty on higher education
reform, and promised to increase students' grants at the end of
this year.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin is expected to meet the leadership of Kostroma city and
return to Moscow later Friday. 
