<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Trade Surplus Shrinks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Canada's trade surplus in April
fell by 600 million Canadian dollars (408 million U.S. dollars) as
Asia's financial crisis kept the nation's export growth in check.
</P>
<P>
April's trade surplus was 1.2 billion Canadian Dollars (816
million dollars), down from March's 1.8 billion dollars (1.2
billion dollars) and the lowest since last October, Statistics
Canada said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The decrease was blamed on the financial crisis in southeast
Asia with many countries suffering sudden and sharp devaluation of
their currencies followed by set-back in their economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The currency depreciation prompted Asian nations to curb demand
for Canadian goods, which have grown relatively more expensive.
</P>
<P>
The sinking demand has, in turn, dragged down world prices for
Canadian mainstays such as wood, minerals, oil and gas, thus
bringing about the reduced value of Canadian exports.
</P>
<P>
Exports barely budged in April, rising 0.1 percent from March
to 26 billion Canadian dollars (17.7 billion dollars). Higher
exports of aircraft, communications equipment and other consumer
goods were offset by lower exports of cars, wood pulp, precious
metals and ores.
</P>
<P>
Imports, however, rose 2.6 percent to 24.8 billion dollars
(16.9 billion dollars). Aircraft and steel product imports were
mainly responsible for the rise, offset slightly by a drop in
imports of auto parts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
