<HEADLINE> Philippine Airlines' Ground Crew Union to Join </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Flight attendants and ground
personnel of Philippine Airlines (PAL) threatened Friday to join a
crippling two-week-long pilots' strike which has already
aggravated the debt-ridden airlines' financial situation.
</P>
<P>
The ground workers' union filed a strike notice with the
Department of Labor and Employment accusing PAL of union busting
and harassment.
</P>
<P>
The flight attendants' union expressed support for the pilots'
strike and said it may follow their suit.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the striking Airline Pilots Association of the
Philippines (ALPAP), said that PAL unions and other trade unions
have agreed to rally in front of the presidential palace on July
1, the first day for the next administration.
</P>
<P>
Vice President and President-Elect Joseph Estrada, who has
openly supported PAL management's decision to downsize, will take
his oath of office on June 30 to succeed outgoing President Fidel
Ramos.
</P>
<P>
Also Friday, PAL filed a petition to the Philippine Securities
and Exchange Commission seeking approval for its rehabilitation
plan which will lead to the sacking of 5,000 employees, or 37
percent of its more than 13,000 workforce.
</P>
<P>
The airlines said it is unable to meet payments on its loans,
estimated at 2 billion U.S. dollars, because of drastically
reduced cash flow as a result of the devastating pilots' walkout.
</P>
<P>
The strike has cost the company more than 2 billion pesos (50
million dollars) in lost revenue, PAl said.
</P>
<P>
The airline said it also plans to dispose of 40 of its 54 jet
planes, suspend more than two-thirds of its routes and sell some
subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
The company said Thursday it will decide in three months
whether it will shut down after seeing the results of the
rehabilitation plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
