<HEADLINE> Jamaican PM Says World Cup Brings Nation Together </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 19 (Xinhua) -- P.J. Patterson, Prime Minister of the
Caribbean island nation Jamaica, said on Friday that the team's debut
at the World Cup finals had brought his nation together.
</P>
<P>
"Jamaicans are fanatical about the World Cup: each time the Reggae
Boyz play, everybody is in front of their TV set," said the prime
minister at the team's training camp at Chaumont, 300 kilometers east
of Paris.
</P>
<P>
"In my country, sport is a way of bringing people together, in a
spirit of peace and faternity," Petterson added.
</P>
<P>
He said Jamaica, the first English-speaking nation which qualifies
for the finals, was very proud of being part of the top-level soccer
tournament although it was not the first time his country
distinguished itself in a high profile event.
</P>
<P>
"I would like everybody to remember that Jamaica qualified for the
Winter Olympic Games, although snow never falls on my country. We
rejoice all the more because until now our national football team has
never distinguished itself."
</P>
<P>
Jamaica, which lost to Croatia in their Group H opener, will face
former world champion Argentina at Parcs des Princes in Paris on
Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
