<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea to Pay Cost of U.S. Troops in Won </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 19 (Xinhua) -- South Korea is to pay most of the
cost of maintaining U.S. troops in Korea in South Korean currency
this year, saving the Seoul government 130 billion won (92.8
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The payment agreement with Washington was announced Friday by
Kim In-jong, South Korean defense policy adviser, and Richard
Christenson, counsellor of the U.S. Embassy in Seoul.
</P>
<P>
Early last year, Seoul promised to pay 399 million U.S.
dollars this year as its share of the cost of keeping some 37,000
U.S. troops in the country.
</P>
<P>
However, with the former 11th largest economy in the world
suffering under the Asian financial crisis, Washington agreed to
accept most of the payment in won at a pre-crisis exchange rate of
907.6 won against the greenback.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement, the two nations said that the agreement
will reduce Seoul's burden without imposing any further financial
burden on the United States.
</P>
<P>
"In consideration of South Korea's need to lessen the potential
demand for foreign currency, Korea's payment will be made in won,"
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The agreement will mostly effect South Korean employees working
for the U.S. military. The original portion set aside for their
salaries was 299 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The remaining 100 million U.S. dollars will be offered to the
U.S. Forces in South Korea in the form of the construction of
various facilities and support in kind.
</P>
<P>
In response to the U.S. effort to reduce its financial burden,
South Korea will provide an additional 2.6 million U.S. dollars in
logistics supplies to the U.S. troops.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen said in January that
Washington would not seek to profit from a weakening won.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean currency, which had been in the 900 level last
October, just before the November financial crisis, is now
hovering around 1,400 against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
It was trading at 1,392 to the dollar Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
