<HEADLINE> Malaysia Applying for Additional Loan From World Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad confirmed Friday that Malaysia is applying for an
additional 700-million-U.S.-dollar loan from the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
He said this loan and the 300-million-U.S.dollar loan approved
by the World Bank Friday would be used solely for social programs
like housing, and not for economic reform.
</P>
<P>
The government was in the process of applying for the
700-million -U.S.-dollar loan, he told reporters at the United
Malays National Organization( Umno) general assembly here.
</P>
<P>
A Malaysian National News Agency report from Washington
Thursday quoted a World Bank official as saying that Malaysia was
expected to request for the loan before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the 7.03 billion ringgit (about 1.793 billion U.S.
dollars) supplementary budget to spur economic activity announced
Thursday by Deputy Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim, Mahathir said it
would compound the country's present budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said with the government's shrinking revenue due to a
fall in company profits following the economic slowdown, the
government was expecting a deficit for this year.
</P>
<P>
Originally, the government forecast a budget surplus of 3.934
billion ringgit (about 1.004 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
"We may have to borrow more money, like through the issue of
bonds. We are working on this," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
