<HEADLINE> Illegal Aliens Commit Crimes in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Police statistics has
indicated that 14 percent of crimes committed in South Africa
were by foreigners, local daily the Citizen reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
This figure was high if the proportion of foreigners in
relation to the population was considered, Albert Makoena,
director-general of the Home Affairs Department, was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Crimes illegal aliens were involved in included money
laundering, drugs, motorcar theft, weapons smuggling,
prostitution and fraud.
</P>
<P>
A large number of South Africans were involved with foreign
criminals whose activities extended beyond the country's borders,
police said.
</P>
<P>
There were increasing reports of people using illegally
acquired South African passports being caught all over the world
for crimes like drug smuggling and forge visas.
</P>
<P>
"Very soon travel restrictions will be imposed on South
Africans because of this," Makoena said, adding that there was a
strong linkage between the increase in some types of corruption
and the activities of foreigners.
</P>
<P>
Referring to a protocol on the Facilitation of the Movement of
People discussed by the members states of the Southern African
Development Community (SADC), Makoena said South Africa welcome
the protocol.
</P>
<P>
"We welcome this move which further reinforces the development
of the region, but we also recognize that it will pose major
challenges to all of us, because SADC citizen will now travel
visa-free in the region," Makoena said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
