<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Grants Funds for Overseas Vocational Training </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission on Friday
announced a grant of 29.7 million ECU (32.67 million U.S.
dollars) for overseas vocational training for young people in 22
countries.
</P>
<P>
As many as 17,600 young people will benefit from the training
program known as the Leonardo da Vinci scheme that is implemented
in the 15 European Union (EU) member states, Iceland, Liechtenstein,
Norway, Hungary, the Czech Republic, Romania and Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Poland and Slovakia are expected to join and benefit from the
program soon.
</P>
<P>
The training program is aimed at organizing international job
placement and exchange programs for young job seekers and trainers
as well.
</P>
<P>
The EU funding will be used to co-finance the linguistic and
cultural preparation of the trainees, travel expenses, insurance
costs and subsistence expenses.
</P>
<P>
Each participating country is eligible for the financial
assistance on the basis of the size of its population, its gross
domestic product (GDP) and its geographical location.
</P>
<P>
European Commissioner Edith Cresson, who is responsible for
education, training and youth, said, "These measures make it
possible to broaden one's horizons and will reinforce young
people's capacity to learn and help prepare them for the labor
market." 
</P>
</TEXT>
