<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 12:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syrian President to Pay First Visit to Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Syrian President Hafez al-Assad is
to pay his first visit in more than 20 years to Lebanon this fall,
notably to climax Damascus' official recognition of Lebanon's
statehood and independence.
</P>
<P>
The Orient radio Friday quoted Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik
Hariri, who is visiting the United States, as saying Assad "will
visit us at the invitation of President Elias Hrawi before
October."
</P>
<P>
Hrawi last month expressed hope that Assad would visit Lebanon
"to see me before my term is up. I have extended longstanding
invitations to him."
</P>
<P>
The remark has sparked media speculation on whether Assad's
visit would be a formal farewell to Hrawi, whose term will expire
in October, or a prelude to another extension of his tenure.
</P>
<P>
Hrawi was elected president with strong Syrian backing in
1989, two days after the assassination of his predecessor, Rene
Mouawad, in a massive car bomb blast in Beirut.
</P>
<P>
Hrawi's constitutional term expired in 1995, but the parliament
voted a one-time constitutional amendment that year, allowing him
to stay on for an extra 3-year term.
</P>
<P>
The conservative newspaper An Nahar here said Assad's coming
visit, the first since he came to power in 1971, will further
stress Syria's official recognition of Lebanon's independence, an
issue at the center of broad suspicion.
</P>
<P>
This was a reference to Syria's longstanding contention that
Lebanon is part of Syria that was torn off by victorious British
and French allies after the first World War.
</P>
<P>
Syria withheld its recognition to Lebanon after it declared
independence in 1943, but has kept a special relationship with
it. Syria now has some 40,000 troops in Lebanon, deployed since
1976, after Lebanon's 15-year civil war broke out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boating Offers on the Qinghai Plateau </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, June 19 (Xinhua) -- A new tourism program enables
tourists visiting the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau in Qinghai Province
not only enjoy vast grasslands, scenic snow-capped mountains and
expansive deserts, but also boating on clear blue lakes.
</P>
<P>
Qinghai Lake, the largest saltwater lake of China, is the prime
Qinghai area for boating and the summer nesting grounds for over
100,000 migratory birds. The three hour ride along the ribbon-like
Qinghai-Tibet Highway from Xining, the provincial capital, to the
lake offers an opportunity to view strikingly beautiful scenery.
</P>
<P>
The Yellow River, which meanders over 1,900 km through Qinghai,
is another favorite boating destination.
</P>
<P>
The reservoir at the Longyang Gorge Hydropower Plant introduced
boating on the river.
</P>
<P>
The Lijiaxia Hydropower Plant has also emerged as popular
destination due to its close proximity to the Kanbula National
Forest Park. Some 30,000 tourists have visited the reservoir over
the past three years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ROK Firms In Shandong Province Report Rising Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The exports by ROK-funded companies
in east China's Shandong Province were valued at 891 million US
dollars in the first five months of this year, up 6.5 percent on
the previous year's period.
</P>
<P>
Shandong is home to 2,525 firms funded by the Republic of Korea
(ROK), or half of the national total.
</P>
<P>
Customs officials attributed the rise in exports by ROK-funded
firms to their minimal presence in the Asian market. As a result,
the firms have not been affected by the Asian financial
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Half of their products were exported to the European and
American markets, and only 24 percent of their products sold in
other Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government's firm support for ROK firms in the
form of new policies and reduced taxes has also contributed to
their good performance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
