<HEADLINE> Hong Kong to Attend APEC Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 19 (Xinhua) -- A Hong Kong government
delegation, led by Secretary for Trade and Industry Chau Tak Hay,
will attend the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) meeting
for trade ministers, to be held in Malaysia next week, a
government spokesman said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Trade ministers from 18 member economies will gather in
Kuching, Sarawak of Malaysia on June 22 and 23, reviewing the
progress of an APEC initiative on early voluntary sectoral
liberalization in respect of 15 sectors selected by APEC ministers
in Vancouver, Canada, in November 1997.
</P>
<P>
"The objective of Hong Kong, China, is for trade ministers to
endorse the work completed on this initiative and give clear
instructions to senior officials to further develop the proposals
on the 15 sectors in order to arrive at a credible, balanced and
mutually beneficial package by November this year," the spokesman
from the Hong Kong Trade and Industry Bureau said here.
</P>
<P>
The trade ministers will also discuss, among other major
issues, the follow-up work that may be undertaken within APEC on
the decisions taken at the Second Ministerial Conference of the
World Trade Organization (WTO) held in Geneva from May 18 to 20
this year, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The APEC at present comprises 18 member economies including
Australia; Brunei Darussalam; Canada; Chile; China; Hong Kong,
China; Indonesia; Japan; South Korea; Malaysia; Mexico; New
Zealand; Papua New Guinea, the Philippines, Singapore, Chinese
Taipei; Thailand and the United States. Peru, Russia and Vietnam,
which currently take part in APEC activities as members-designate,
will be formally admitted to APEC in November this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
