<HEADLINE> Motorola Opens Center In Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Motorola opened a new office
building in eastern Beijing today that will serve as a management
and coordinating center for China, Japan, and Korea.
</P>
<P>
The "North Asia Center" represents a change in Motorola's
geographic focus, according to Gary Tooker, chairman of the board.
</P>
<P>
At an annual business meeting, P.Y. Lai, president of Motorola
(China) Electronics Ltd., said that Motorola has 8 manufacturing
facilities in the northern Chinese port city of Tianjin and 7 in
other parts of the country, worth 1 billion U.S. dollars of
investment, making Motorola the biggest U.S. investor in China.
</P>
<P>
China's State Economic and Trade Commission says that Motorola
(China) was the largest exporter in China, with 900 million
dollars worth last year.
</P>
<P>
According to Lai, his company plans to build Suzhou, in Jiangsu
Province, into its second production base in China following
Tianjin, which is its Asian production center.
</P>
<P>
The company is expected to put 100 million dollars into the
initial phase of the project and to increase its investment in
China to 2.5 billion dollars by the year 2000.  
</P>
