<HEADLINE> HK Manufacturers' Orders-on-Hand Decline in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong manufacturers'
orders-on-hand dropped by 8 percent in April 1998 from a year
earlier, the government announced here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Census and Statistics Department Friday released a monthly
survey, which shows that orders for electrical, plastic,
electronic, wearing apparel, printing and publishing products
shrank between 6 and 26 percent in value in April.
</P>
<P>
But orders for textiles and fabricated metal products rose by 4
and 2 percent respectively, according to the survey.
</P>
<P>
A government spokesman said here Friday that orders-on-hand for
the manufacturing sector as a whole recorded slower year-on-year
declines in April 1998.
</P>
<P>
He added that Hong Kong continued to receive orders for
textiles and wearing apparel industries from overseas, but the
unsettled situation in some Asian economies was still affecting
their export production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
