<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Ministers Warn of Renewed Fires in Southeast Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 19 (Xinhua) -- ASEAN environment ministers
warned Friday against a renewed threat of fires in the months
ahead as the region is entering into the dry season.
</P>
<P>
The warning was contained in a statement issued by Singapore
Minister for the Environment and Health Yeo Cheow Tong at a press
conference held at the end of the one-day 4th Ministerial Meeting
of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) on Haze.
</P>
<P>
The statement said though heavy rains had helped put out the
fires in Kalimantan and the El Nino was at its final stages, new
fires were already spotted in some parts of the region,
particularly in Sumatra, Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The ministers noted that firm measures should be taken
immediately to put out these fires before they go out of control.
</P>
<P>
The ministers agreed to speed up the implementation of the
Regional Haze Action Plan which was launched to beef up preventive
measures, and to establish regional monitoring mechanisms to
enhance fire-fighting capabilities.
</P>
<P>
The ministers said that the plans must be complemented by
public education efforts and strict enforcement against open
burning, and they particularly urged ASEAN countries to include in
their national laws regulations to discourage open burning
activities by land owners.
</P>
<P>
The ministers agreed to strengthen fire-fighting cooperative
mechanisms for fire-fighting in Sumatra, which involve Indonesia,
Malaysia and Singapore. They also set an objective to prevent
fires and not to allow the scales of any fires to deteriorate into
a disaster level.
</P>
<P>
On fire-fighting in Kalimantan, Brunei, Indonesia and Malaysia
will join efforts to prevent and contain any fires there within
the framework of a working group led by Brunei.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia and Singapore agreed to assist Indonesia in aerial
surveillance by providing training and communication equipment
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also called on the international community to
provide the necessary assistance.
</P>
<P>
A representative of the United Nations Environment Program
(UNEP) said at the press conference that the Global Environment
Facility has adopted a project of 750,000 U.S. dollars to support
the efforts to deal with fires and haze, and the UNEP will
actively follow up with potential donors on an ASEAN plan to
establish a 10-million-U.S.-dollar fund for fire-fighting and
other related measures.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the United States has promised to offer an
aid of 4 million dollars to help ASEAN deal with the regional haze
problem and an additional 2 million dollars to assist Indonesia in
fire-fighting operations.
</P>
<P>
In his opening speech Friday morning, Yeo Cheow Tong said the
1997 fires and haze cost ASEAN 4.5 billion dollars and a repeat of
this disaster will surely aggravate the already bad regional
economic situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Communist Youth League Growing Steadily </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The world's largest youth
organization, the Communist Youth League of China (CYLC), has been
growing steadily over the past five years, said a senior leader of
the CYLC.
</P>
<P>
The total number of members of the CYLC stands at 68.5 million,
up 10.5 million from 1993. And 3.92 million members of the CYLC
joined the Communist Party of China (CPC), the ruling party of the
country, over the past five years.
</P>
<P>
On behalf of the 13th CYLC Central Committee, Zhou Qiang,
executive member of the Secretariat of the 13th Central Committee
of the CYLC, delivered a speech at the opening ceremony of the
14th National Congress of the CYLC here today.
</P>
<P>
He said that during the five years after the convocation of the
13th National Congress of the CYLC, 230 million Chinese young
people, some one-fourth of the country's total population, have
made tremendous contributions to China's modernization drive.
</P>
<P>
He said the past five years have shown that the present
generation of Chinese youth is a reliable and promising
generation, and has been growing steadily under the correct
guidance of the CPC.
</P>
<P>
Since it was founded in 1922, the CYLC has all along stuck to
the principle of CPC leadership, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhou, the CYLC has given priority to the education
of the young generation and sticks to the principle of using Deng
Xiaoping Theory to equip them as a spiritual pillar.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that over the past five years, more than 50
million members of the CYLC have attended professional training
courses, and more than 1,000 small- and medium-size enterprises
have begun to reduce losses or turn a profit because of the CYLC.
</P>
<P>
He said that the young volunteers program, launched by the CYLC
in 1993, has promoted the building of social ethics, and the
movement now boasts more than 1.3 million youth volunteer groups,
comprising 70 million young people.
</P>
<P>
The Hope Project, also launched by the CYLC, has so far
received more than 1.3 billion yuan in donations from home and
abroad, which has helped more than 1.8 million dropouts to return
to school and funded the building of more than 5,000 Project Hope
primary schools.
</P>
<P>
Zhou stressed that the work of the CYLC should be
conscientiously subject to the work of the whole Party and the
whole country, and the CYLC should stick to the leadership of the
CPC and be consistent with the CPC Central Committee, with Jiang
Zemin at the core, politically and ideologically. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
