<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Rand Hits New Low Against Western </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The rand fell to its worst
levels ever against the U.S. Dollar and the British Pound
Thursday, The Star paper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Rand stood at 8.98 Rand to the Pound at the end of the
market after breaking through the nine Rand barrier earlier in
the day. Against the Dollar, it ended at 5.39 Rand, coming back
slightly from a low of 5.41 rand.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the weakened Rand would reduce overseas travels
by South Africans, increase the price of imports and contribute
to inflation.
</P>
<P>
The surprise slump came in the afternoon after the Rand
rallied to 5.27 Rand to the Dollar in the morning, up 6 cents
from Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Traders, who expected a further Rand recovery following news
that the United States would support Japan's ailing Yen, said
they could not account for the surge of the Dollar.
</P>
<P>
There were reports that the Rand selling came from speculators
in London and New York and there was also talk of a very large
corporate Dollar order.
</P>
<P>
A Rand trader in New York said the volatility in the day
indicated that the market was unsure at what level the Rand
should be trading in current conditions.
</P>
<P>
The Reserve Bank has been absent from the market, allowing
traders free rein to push and pull currencies.
</P>
<P>
Reserve Bank governor Chris Stals Thursday dismissed criticism
of the bank's performance, saying South Africa's economic
fundamentals remained sound.
</P>
<P>
He said South Africa was a victim of a wider attack on
emerging markets.
</P>
<P>
"As stability returns to the international financial markets,
our economy will be well-placed to resume a new upward phase of
the business cycle," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Banking System Still Healthy: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine banking system is
still healthy despite the closure of five thrift banks in the past
year, Central Bank Governor Gabriel Singson said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here, Singson said the closure
of the five thrift banks will not affect the health of the
country's banking system as their combined resources amount to
only 561 million pesos (about 14 million U.S. dollars), or 0.02
percent of the entire banking industry.
</P>
<P>
He said the central bank closed the five banks after they
failed to raise capital to the required level.
</P>
<P>
Since the financial crisis started in Southeast Asia last July,
the Philippine Central Bank has closed Eastern Visayas Development
Bank, Aklan Development Bank, Commonwealth Savings and Loan Bank,
Community Savings and Loan Association and Fortune Savings and
Loan Association.
</P>
<P>
One commercial bank, Orient Bank, is still in limbo after
declaring a bank holiday on February 14.
</P>
<P>
The central bank is set to discuss with the Philippine Deposit
Insurance Corporation (PDIC) the possibility of bailing out Orient
Bank, which is suffering from non-performing debts, according to
Singson.
</P>
<P>
"It is up to the PDIC if it wants to take out some of Orient's
bad assets. If it agrees to do so then it will be all right," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the banking systems of other Southeast Asian
countries, the Philippines' remains relatively healthy although
the five small banks were closed, economists also said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
