<HEADLINE> "We Have to Play to Win," Prohaska </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BORDEAUX, June 19 (Xinhua) -- After scoring a last-gasp equaliser
in each of their first two group matches, the lucky Austrian team will
now take on the strongest team in Group B--Italy.
</P>
<P>
Before moving to Saint-Denis for the decisive match on June 23,
Austrian coach Herbert Prohaska shouted out his determination:"We
will have to play to win without fearing the Italians."
</P>
<P>
"I saw the first half of the Italian game against Cameroon. To
beat the Italians we will have to take risks except in the
organisation of our game," said Prohaska, "It will be a hard-fought
match, it will be all or nothing."
</P>
<P>
The Austrians have played two matches in the World Cup finals,
but many of them haven't loosened up.
</P>
<P>
Prohaska admitted that his players were still tense and nervous,
"But we can't hold that against them. They've all been giving one
hundred percent in training. By the time we play Italy, I will have
spoken to the players to make them relaxed."
</P>
<P>
Prohaska, who played for Italian club Inter Milan for three seasons
during his career, said:"I am still very fond of Italy, but I feel
Austrian first and foremost. I know Austria is not one of the great
footballing nations, but we will do our very best to win." 
</P>
</TEXT>
