<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Residents to Receive Better Drinking Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The second-phase construction to
provide drinking water from the upper reaches of the Huangpu River
to Shanghai has been completed.
</P>
<P>
The four-year-long effort cost 3 billion yuan to set up
facilities capable of daily transporting 5 million cubic meters of
upstream Huangpu river water through a 41-kilometer pipeline.
</P>
<P>
The water will be treated in eight water plants in Shanghai
before being delivered to eight million Shanghai people.
</P>
<P>
Prior to this, Suzhouhe River and the lower reaches of the
Huangpu River that runs through Shanghai had been the city's two
major drinking-water resources. However, due to an excessive
amount of industrial and residential sewage discharge, the water
had become seriously polluted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 11:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNA Criticizes Israel's Jerusalem Expansion Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) Friday criticized Israel's plan for Jerusalem expansion and
called on the international community to pressure Israel to halt
such a unilateral plan.
</P>
<P>
PNA Cabinet Secretary Ahmed Abdel Rahman said in Gaza that the
expansion plan is aiming at causing a demographic change in the
Holy City for the interest of Israelis to preempt final status
negotiations, according to East Jerusalem-based Palestinian news
service JMCC.
</P>
<P>
He said the expansion plan, which has been endorsed by Israeli
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, is nothing but a "colonial
intention" and that "could not change the fact that Jerusalem is
the capital of Palestine."
</P>
<P>
A 12-point plan designed to strengthen Jerusalem, including
annexing land west of Jerusalem, building a tunnel under Mount
Scopus to connect with the settlement of Ma'ale Adumim east of
Jerusalem, and creating a silicon valley in Jerusalem, was formally
endorsed by Netanyahu on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The plan has been the focus of much debate over the past three
months, especially by residents in communities west of Jerusalem,
who have objected to the creation of a Greater Jerusalem via an
umbrella municipality that will wield administrative powers over
these nearby towns.
</P>
<P>
"I think this is a basic change in Jerusalem's status which
will be remembered as a turning point," Netanyahu said after
receiving the plan submitted to him Thursday by a special
committee comprising representatives from the Prime Minister's
Office, Jerusalem Municipality, the Interior Ministry and
Jerusalem Development Authority.
</P>
<P>
The plan, to be funded under the 1999 state budget, will be
presented to the cabinet on Sunday with Netanyahu's firm
endorsement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
