<HEADLINE> World Bank Study Outlines New Global Rural Development Strategy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese version of a World
Bank report on global rural economies was published here today,
which called for a new approach to rural development in the 21st
century to solve the pressing problems of poverty, food security
and natural resource management.
</P>
<P>
The publication, titled "Rural Development: From Vision to
Action," reviews the importance of rural development in the global
economy and identifies a series of urgent actions that the World
Bank and its partners must take to improve the welfare of the 800
million people in the world who are going hungry.
</P>
<P>
The new rural development strategy focuses on six key elements
that involve government policies, international trade,
agricultural technology, information, rural infrastructure and
education.
</P>
<P>
Geoffrey Fox, rural development manager of East Asia at the
World Bank, said: "China has been a world leader in promoting
rural development and we hope that the report will provide new
ideas and initiatives to help spur environmentally sustainable
growth in the poor, remote inland areas of China."
</P>
<P>
Sources from the World Bank's Resident Mission in China said
that the World Bank is preparing a report on rural development
strategy issues, and is expanding its investment program in the
rural sector.
</P>
<P>
During the past year, the World Bank approved 1 billion U.S.
dollars in financing for investments in China's rural sector,
including agriculture and irrigation, forestry, coastal
management, state farm commercialization, rural health services
and environmental management. 
</P>
</TEXT>
