<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Education Exchanges Dynamic Between China, U.S. (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 19 (Xinhua) -- One hundred and twentysix years
ago, noted Chinese educator Rong Hong led 30 teenagers across the
then vast and mysterious Pacific Ocean to a newfound world,
ushering in the first chapter of Sino-U.S. education exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Some of the students, such as the first Chinese railway
engineer, Zhan Tianyou, made pioneering contributions to their
homeland after returning from the United States.
</P>
<P>
Such contacts have witnessed ups and downs in the ensuing one
and a quarter centuries amid volatile state-to-state relations.
</P>
<P>
China's opening-up policy initiated in the late 1970s reopened
the gates of China, starting from a narrow crack to the now
two-way channels accessible to hundreds of thousands of people
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"The past two decades can be considered a period with gradually
recovered exchanges, wide-ranging cooperative fields, and more
tangible results," said Chen Zhili, China's education minister, in
a recent exclusive interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics from the ministry, in the past 20 years
a total of 163,000 scholars and students went to the United States
to study in almost all academic fields in more than 1,000
institutions of higher learning.
</P>
<P>
"With the majority engaging in the study of natural sciences,
the figure accounted for 56 percent of the total studying abroad
in the period," Chen said, adding that 43,300 of them have
finished study and returned to China.
</P>
<P>
"It is also noteworthy that more and more students from the
United States are coming to study in China," she said. In 1997
alone, 3,135 U.S. students enrolled in Chinese colleges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ten Cities Report Excellent Air Quality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Ten cities reported excellent air
quality in the previous week, according to information released by
the China Environment Monitoring Center (CEMC) today.
</P>
<P>
The inland cities of Nanchang and Nanning joined the group of
cities with excellent air quality, an honor normally reserved for
coastal cities.
</P>
<P>
The other eight cities reporting excellent air quality were
Fuzhou, Ningbo, Shenzhen, Zhuhai, Haikou, Beihai, Zhanjiang and
Xiamen.
</P>
<P>
The CEMC's report gives the air quality atmospheric pollution
index (API) of sulfur dioxide (SO2), nitrogen oxide (NOX) and
total suspended particles (TSP).
</P>
<P>
Air quality is listed on five levels by the State Environmental
Protection Administration. An API from 0 to 50 is level I, meaning
excellent air quality; 51 to 100 is level II, or good quality; 101
to 200 is level III, or slight pollution; 201 to 300 is level IV,
or medium pollution; and above 300 is level V, or heavy pollution.
</P>
<P>
No cities reported heavy air pollution in the June 12-18
period, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Taiyuan, the capital of north China's Shanxi Province, was the
only city with medium air pollution. Its major problem was TSP.
</P>
<P>
Seven cities including Beijing, Lanzhou and Tianjin had slight
air pollution in the period, all with TSP as the major problem.
</P>
<P>
The air quality of the remaining 26 cities including Shanghai,
Suzhou and Guilin was good, the report said.
</P>
<P>
To date, China has 44 cities releasing weekly air quality
reports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
