<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Intensify Post-flood Disease Control Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Fearing serious floods and
droughts this summer, China's health departments are taking
measures to control a possible outbreak of infectious diseases.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Health (MOH) has informed local health
departments and agencies responsible for preventing epidemics to
be ready for disease control after flooding, according to
a MOH official.
</P>
<P>
Floods or droughts are often followed by intestinal illnesses
as a result of water pollution, said Li Jianguo, an official with
the MOH's Department of Disease Control.
</P>
<P>
Although he did not provide national statistics on epidemics in
the first half of this year, the official admitted that the
current situation has become more serious than previous years and
"may worsen if preventive measures are not taken immediately."
</P>
<P>
Natural disasters will also increase the danger of plague and
malaria across the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has asked to intensify supervision of the quality
of food and drinking water, as well as protection of water sources
to avoid food poisoning and prevent infectious diseases, Li said.
</P>
<P>
The authorities will keep a close eye on migrant people,
schools and large construction sites.
</P>
<P>
A special telephone line will be opened by the ministry for
local authorities to report the epidemic at any time.
</P>
<P>
Experts with the Ministry of Water Resources and flood-control
agencies have warned of a possible serious flood on the Yangtze
River, China's longest, which has not occurred in 44 years.
</P>
<P>
The Yellow River, the nation's second longest, also is expected
to experience flooding this summer.
</P>
<P>
Floods have already hit the provinces of Jiangxi, Hunan, Fujian
and Guangdong in southern China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
