<HEADLINE> China Gets Largest Oil Contract on Iraq Food-for-Oil Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 19 (Xinhua) -- China National Chemicals Import
and Export Corp (CNCIEC) has signed an oil contract to buy 18
million barrels of crude from Iraq in the fourth-round agreement
of the United Nations Oil-for-Food program.
</P>
<P>
"It is the largest oil deal so far under the Oil-for-Food plan,
exceeding the amount contracted by the French TOTAL and ELF oil
companies and the Russian Oil Corp.," said a senior CNCIEC
official.
</P>
<P>
In the previous two rounds of agreements, China got 2 million
and 7.4 million barrels of crude, much less than the present deal
which starts on June 11 and expires on November 25.
</P>
<P>
The China National Chemicals Import and Export Corp. is
directly under the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation, which ranked first among the country's 500 largest
import and export companies for eight years.
</P>
<P>
In addition, it has been listed among the top 30 out of the
world's largest 500 enterprises for eight consecutive years by
Fortune since 1989, and ranked 14th in 1996. It's listed by the
U.N. Trade Conference as the sixth largest transnational company
from developing countries.
</P>
<P>
The CNCIEC has undertaken oil import and export businesses for
many years and has high status in the international oil trade
circles. 
</P>
