<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Recovers $41m From Bank Frauds in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria banks were saved a loss of
3.526 billion Naira (about 41 million U.S. Dollars) from 478
fraud cases in 1997, through the work of the Failed Banks
Tribunals.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed by the Nigeria Deposit Insurance
Corporation in its 1997 annual report released recently in Lagos.
</P>
<P>
The report said bank staff and their collaborators made
attempt to defraud the banks of a total sum of 3.777 billion
Naira (about 44 million dollars) in 1997, but they succeeded with
only 251.54 million Naira (about 2.96 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
In 1997, 566 bank staff were dismissed for involvement in
fraudulent activities, down from 1995's 625 but up from 552 in
1996, the report said.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the commonest type of frauds are
presentation of forged cheques, granting of unauthorized loans,
unauthorized overdraft, posting of fictitious credits,
suppression of cheques, abuse of medical scheme and fraudulent
transfer and withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
To combat the rising cases of banking frauds, the Nigerian
government promulgated the Failed Banks (recovery of debt) and
Financial Malpractices in Banks Decree 18, 1994.
</P>
<P>
Under the decree, failed banks tribunals have been set up in
several cities. The prosecution and delivery of judgement in such
tribunals are made easier and much faster than what would have
been in ordinary courts.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the efforts, the total number of fraud cases dropped
from 1996's 606 to 487 in 1997, while the actual loss declined
from 375.2 million Naira to 251.54 Naira, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Accordingly, the report said, both the magnitude of distress
as measured by the number of distressed banks and the depth of
distress as measured by various financial ratios declined in
1997.
</P>
<P>
For example, it said, the ratio of loans and lease of
distressed banks to the industry's total loans and leases fell
from 23.7 percent in 1996 to 21.2 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The ratio of total assets of distressed banks to the
industry's total assets which stood at 19.8 percent in 1995 fell
to 11 percent in 1996 and 7.6 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Compared with 1996, the aggregate assets of banks rose by 25
percent to reach 739.3 billion Naira (about 8.70 billion
dollars), while the industry's total deposits rose by 26 percent
to reach 591.2 billion Naira (6.96 million dollars), the report
added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
