<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan Government to Curb Fuel Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan government has
announced measures including sealing every gas station in the
country to curb increasingly rampant fuel smuggling.
</P>
<P>
Emmanuel Tumusiime-Mutebile, Permanent Secretary in the
Ministry of Finance, Planning and Economic Development, made the
remarks during a public discussion on the new budget here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He was quoted by Friday's Monitor daily as saying that the
measure will soon cover the whole country and that the bulk of
smuggling will be reduced.
</P>
<P>
"All petrol stations in Kampala and Entebbe will be sealed
with customs seals so that we can know how much fuel is sold and
how much money is earned," the permanent secretary said.
</P>
<P>
Any station that cannot be sealed by the end of the month
along the east-south corridor will be closed down, he added.
</P>
<P>
Fuel smuggling is one of the illicit practices that many have
attributed to an improper taxation policy. This prompts fuel to
be smuggled into Uganda from neighboring Kenya where the tax
rates on fuel are much lower.
</P>
<P>
The official, however, said fuel smuggling is not caused by
high taxes but by the fact that the smuggled fuel remains untaxed
because it had been intended for Rwanda or the Democratic
Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to fight fuel smuggling, the new budget, which was
announced on June 11, aimed at narrowing the gap between fuel tax
rates in Uganda and Kenya. It reduces taxes on petrol, kerosene
by 30 Uganda shillings per liter and that on diesel by 60
Shillings per liter (one U.S. Dollar equals 1200 Uganda
Shillings). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
