<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Above 61 U.S. Cents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar meandered
around the 61-U.S.-cent mark Friday, buoyed by a firmer Japanese
yen but warily awaiting the outcome of crisis talks in Japan this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
The local currency ended slightly higher after a tumultuous
week during which it dipped to a new 12-year low of 58 U.S. cents
and rose above the 60 U.S.-cent level for the first time in two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
Market consensus is that the combined U.S. Federal Reserve and
Bank of Japan rescue package for the Japanese yen needs to be
followed up by swift reform by the Japanese government.
</P>
<P>
All eyes are now firmly focused on the G-7 meeting this weekend
in Tokyo involving deputy finance ministers and central bank
officials.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the week in Sydney, the Australian dollar was
trading at 61.27 U.S. cents, little changed from 61.21 U.S. cents
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Much will depend on this weekend's meetings of U.S., Japanese
and G-7 officials," the Commonwealth Bank of Australia's Michael
Blythe said.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar was also buying 83.47 Japanese yen from
83.77 yen and 1.0981 German marks from 1.0936 previously. 
</P>
</TEXT>
