<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Sinks to 134 Yen Level in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar fell below 135 yen in
Tokyo Friday for the first time in a month on expectations of
yen-supportive news from an international meeting to be held here
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The dollar was quoted at 134.97-135.00 yen at 5 p.m. (local time),
down from 137.30-33 yen at 9 a.m., and 137.80-90 yen late Thursday in
New York.
</P>
<P>
During the day, the U.S. currency rose to a high of 137.80 yen
before the late afternoon entrance of players from Europe, who pushed
it to a low of 134.50 yen, a level last seen in Tokyo on May 15.
</P>
<P>
For most of the day, yen-dollar exchanges were lackluster ahead of
Saturday's international gathering in Tokyo, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
The one-day meeting involve the Group of Seven (G-7) finance
ministers' deputies and representatives from the 11 Asian economies
included in the Manila Framework.
</P>
<P>
News that Japan is discussing further measures to stimulate its
economy lifted sentiment on the yen, dealers said. 
</P>
