<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Education Exchanges Dynamic Between China, U.S. (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Within the framework of the Sino-U.S. Science and Technology
Cooperation Agreement and the Sino-U.S. Education Exchange and
Cooperation Protocol, "both official and unofficial exchanges saw
marked progress," Chen said.
</P>
<P>
Take the inter-governmental Fulbright program for
instance. About 500 Chinese scholars and graduates and 300
U.S. experts carried out projects in the two countries in more
than 20 academic fields, including economics, law, history,
literature and politics in the past 19 years, according to Chen.
</P>
<P>
"Inter-university exchanges are also active," she said. Through
cooperation in such forms as joint college operations,
international conferences and textbook exchanges, the two sides
carried out studies on wide-ranging fields from natural sciences
to liberal arts.
</P>
<P>
"Most recently, U.S.-based multinational corporations showed
strong interest in education exchanges by clinching joint research
labs in Chinese universities," she added.
</P>
<P>
On the perspective of the cooperation, Chen said that Chinese
President Jiang Zemin's state visit to the United States last fall
is a milestone in the Sino-U.S. diplomacy and has brought about an
opportunity for the two sides to further their education
exchanges.
</P>
<P>
"The education circles in the two countries should advance
along the development wave and reconsider the importance of such
development at a new height," she said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese and U.S. universities should be encouraged to form
durable and mutually beneficial ties and focus more efforts on the
insightful studies on development trends in education in the
coming century, she added.
</P>
<P>
The two sides are also urged to put more efforts on joint
science and technology projects. "These substantial exchanges can
push forward the cultivation of talents, and then play a positive
role in each other's economic development and social progress,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
"The longtime education exchange, a dynamic part in the
bilateral ties, is a cause with far-reaching impact for the two
countries," she said.
</P>
<P>
With efforts made by the two sides, Chen said she believes the
cooperation will have "richer contents and more accessible
channels" so that a mutual respect and comprehensive education
relationship will be brought well into the 21st century."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
