<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> MOFTEC Official Discusses Sino-U.S. Trade (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 19 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton's
upcoming China visit will vigorously advance Sino-U.S. economic
cooperation and the healthy growth of two-way trade, according to
Sun Zhenyu, Chinese vice-minister of foreign trade and economic
cooperation (MOFTEC).
</P>
<P>
During an exclusive interview today with Xinhua, Sun said that
the scale of bilateral trade does not cater to the demands of the
economic growth of both countries, and the two sides should
earnestly analyze and properly handle the problems in economic
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Sun cited Sino-U.S. trade as the most active and important
part, as well as the major stabilizing factor and driving force of
bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the bilateral trade volume between the
two countries reached 49 billion U.S. dollars last year, 20 times
that of 1979 when China and the United States resumed their
diplomatic relations.
</P>
<P>
Mutual investments have continued to expand. By the end of
1997, the United States had invested in 24,366 projects in China
with contractual and paid-in U.S. investment reaching 40.06
billion and 17.5 billion U.S. dollars, respectively.
</P>
<P>
China's investment in the United States has also constantly
increased in wider ranges.
</P>
<P>
Since Chinese President Jiang Zemin made a successful visit to
the United States last fall, Sun noted, the establishment of the
midterm negotiation mechanism of the Sino-U.S. Joint Commission of
Commerce and Trade and the convening of the Sino-U.S. Joint
Commission of Economy further improved exchange mechanism of the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
The implementation of the Sino-U.S. agreement on the peaceful
use of nuclear power and the advancement of cooperation in the
fields of environmental protection and energy constituted new
areas of growth for bilateral economic cooperation, he added.
</P>
<P>
Touching upon differences in the two-way trade, Sun said that
the annual evaluation of U.S. Congress on the most-favored-nation
trading status to China is incompatible with the times because
this approach makes the business community of the two countries
worry about the the future of their cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The business societies of both countries have made unremitting
efforts to solve the problem, Sun said, adding that "only the
elimination of this practice for the interest of the two countries
can stablize the foundation of bilateral economic cooperation."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mahathir Urges People to Ensure Political Stability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad Friday urged his people especially United Malays
National Organization (UMNO) members to be united to ensure
political stability to overcome the attack on the country's
economy.
</P>
<P>
He also asked them to fully understand the powers behind the
attack on the local currency and the stock market, saying the
attackers intend not only to suppress the national economy and
finances but also to determine the leadership of the country.
</P>
<P>
"In countries where they are able to exert great pressure their
power is not confined to the economic and financial areas alone.
They intend to control politics too and to determine who should
lead that country," he said in his policy speech at the 52nd UMNO
General Assembly here Friday.
</P>
<P>
"An attempt to change leaders in Malaysia had taken place
before when leaders were alleged to be anti-Jews," said Mahathir,
who is UMNO president, referring to allegations that he had made
statements against the Jews at a rally in Terengganu last year.
</P>
<P>
He said they then alleged that current leaders were obstacles
to efforts at economic revival and that present leaders were
ignorant of the intricacies of world financial systems.
</P>
<P>
"The objective is to cause political instability because their
allegations will in turn create misunderstanding among leaders,"
he said in his speech focused on the country's economic and
financial problems.
</P>
<P>
He said that under such circumstances, the economic and
financial problems could not be overcome and the economic
situation would worsen and finally the problems would become worse
with leaders unable to work together.
</P>
<P>
"When this happens, the economy will be open for foreign funds
to acquire major local companies. At that time they will revive
the economy and the value of our currency," he said.
</P>
<P>
Declaring that Malaysia's independence is still not assured, he
called on the Malaysian people to get united and work together to
save the nation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> MOFTEC Official Discusses Sino-U.S. Trade (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
On China's entry into the World Trade Organization (WTO), Sun
said, the United States made a commitment six years ago to firmly
support China's access to the multilateral trade organization. Sun
expressed the hope that the United States can keep its commitment
so as to avoid any impact on the sound development of bilateral
economic and trade relations.
</P>
<P>
China's position and active measures taken after the financial
crisis in east Asia occurred last year fully demonstrates its
responsible attitude toward the region and the international
community and were welcomed by the international community, said
Sun.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that keeping China outside the WTO for a long
time will not be conducive to the stability and prosperity of the
world economy, adding his belief that the United States can draw a
correct conclusion on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Touching upon the bilateral trade imbalance, Sun attributed it
to statistics and technical factors, as well as U.S. government
restrictions on technology exports to China and its insufficient
export promotions which reduced U.S. exports to China and expanded
the gap between statistics for the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Trade statistics also did not include profits by U.S. companies
from product sales in the Chinese market, the vice-minister said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the Chinese government attaches great
importance to the development of Sino-U.S. trade, and has made
unremitting efforts to solve the trade imbalance.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese side will, as always, continue its efforts to
expand bilateral trade, especially its imports from the United
States, said Sun, while asking the U.S. side to lift its export
restrictions and increase credit support for its companies.
</P>
<P>
Sun called it "unfair" since the United States still treats
China as a non-market-economy country and resorts to a surrogate
in dealing with anti-dumping cases with China.
</P>
<P>
Sun said he hopes the United States can, just as the European
Union has done, face the fact that China is developing a market
economy, and treat China's export companies in a fair manner to
create a fair and healthy condition for bilateral economic and
trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"We are looking forward to President Clinton's state visit to
China", said Sun, adding that both sides can promote the steady
and sound growth of bilateral relations and economic and trade
cooperation in the spirit of enhancing mutual understanding,
expanding common ground, developing cooperation and jointly
pioneering the future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Follow New York, Asian Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
closed weaker Friday, forfeiting some of the strong gains of the
previous session as profit-takers moved in.
</P>
<P>
A lower Wall Street overnight and negative Asian markets had
kept a lid on trade, as did the ongoing caution surrounding the
fortunes of both the Japanese yen and Australian dollar against
the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark All Ordinaries Index finished down 19.4 points at
2,588.8, off an intra-day low of 2,582.3, wiping out 0.7 percent
of the market's 2-percent surge Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The All Industrials Index lost 20.6 points to 4,523.2 while the
resources sector tumbled 1.95 percent or 20.5 points to 1,031.2.
</P>
<P>
Media giant News Corp. managed to defy the trend, adding 8
cents to 11.3 Australian dollars while its preferred scrip gained
11 to 9.73 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Resources giant BHP ended 19 cents lower at 13.21 Australian
dollars and global miner Rio Tinto eased 15 cents to 19.4
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index also deteriorated after its rally of Thursday,
dropping 37.4 points or 3.36 percent to 1,074.2 as the precious
metal traded 40 U.S. cents weaker at 293.1 U.S. dollars an ounce
in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
Commonwealth Bank of Australia was the only member of the big
four banks to improve Friday, climbing 4 cents to 18.08 Australian
dollars. National Australia Bank eased 6.4 cents to 21.836
Australian dollars, Westpac bank was off 8 cents to 9.77
Australian dollars and ANZ bank finished 8 cents down to 10.85
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the top of the turnover table was telecommunications giant
Telstra, which slipped 1 cent to 3.85 Australian dollars. More
than 20.43 million installment receipts changed hands worth 47.61
million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
National volume was a modest 292.3 million shares valued at
585.67 million U.S. dollars, with falls outpacing rises 598 to 469
and 440 stocks remaining steady. 
</P>
</TEXT>
