<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suspects over Tanzanian Pilot Murder Netted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 19 (Xinhua) - Seven suspects including a
policeman in connection with killing a senior Tanzanian pilot
driving in downtown Dar es Salaam early June have been arrested
by police.
</P>
<P>
The Dar es Salaam Regional Police Commander Alfred Gewe said
Thursday that the suspects were found in possession of three
pistols, dozens of rounds of ammunition and a cellular phone
handset belonging to the slain pilot of the Air Tanzania
Cooperation (ATC), media here reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
"They are expected to appear in court soon," Gewe said,
appealing to city residents to volunteer more information on the
killing of Elizeus Rugeyemba Rutazaha, a 45-year-old First
Officer of the ATC Boeing Fleet, by two bandits armed with a
sub-machine gun and a pistol at about 11:00 in the morning on
June 8 while his saloon car stopped at a traffic light.
</P>
<P>
Police have not yet established the exact amount of money
which the gunmen took from the Rutazaha's vehicle after killing
him who reportedly left home with one million Tanzanian shillings
(1 U.S. dollar equals to 670 Tanzanian shillings at present) for
shopping in downtown.
</P>
<P>
The only passenger in the car, Alex Kapama, a retired army
officer, was queried by police but later released.
</P>
<P>
The police commander also alleged that the suspects were
hard-core criminals implicated in a number of offenses such as
armed robbery with some of their cases still pending in court.
</P>
<P>
Immediately after the incident, Kapama told the police that
the two strangers smashed the car windows and shot Rutazaha in
the stomach.
</P>
<P>
"They then grabbed out two briefcases and disappeared," said
Kapama, who was treated for minor bruises on the hands in the
Muhimbili Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
Innocent Mungy, the Public Relations Manager of the ATC, has
said Rutazaha, who had joined the state-owned ATC for 15 years
with 5,000 flying hours, was off-duty following a flight on June
7. The pilot is survived by a wife and three children.  
</P>
</TEXT>
