<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Treatments Save Giant Pandas from Normally Fatal Disease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Chinese veterinarians have managed
to cure chronic gastroenteritis, a major disease that normally
causes the death of giant pandas, through a combination of
traditional Chinese and Western medical treatments.
</P>
<P>
The treatments, regarded as a breakthrough in medical care for
giant pandas, passed the experts' assessment today in Chengdu,
capital of Sichuan Province and known as the hometown of giant
pandas.
</P>
<P>
Since 1993, 10 giant pandas suffering chronic gastroenteritis
have received this medical treatment in the Chengdu Giant Panda
Breeding Research Base.
</P>
<P>
Five of them have recovered and the condition of the others has
been improved.
</P>
<P>
A female giant panda called Yaya gave birth to a female cub
after recovering from one year of treatment. Her daughter, who is
also in good health, weighs 30 kilograms now.
</P>
<P>
Chronic gastroenteritis is the top killer of giant pandas in
childhood. Statistics show that 56 percent of giant pandas raised
in captivity suffer digestive diseases, and 80 percent die of
intestinal and stomach diseases and malnutrition.
</P>
<P>
The giant panda is one of the rarest animals in the world and
on the verge of extinction. There are about 1,000 living in
China's western provinces of Sichuan, Gansu and Shaanxi.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
