<HEADLINE> Russian Officials to Mediate in Georgian-Abkhaz Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Under President Boris Yeltsin's
instruction, two senior Russian officials left Friday for Abkhazia
to mediate between the conflicting parties.
</P>
<P>
First Deputy Foreign Minister Boris Pastukhov and Commonwealth
of Independent States (CIS) Executive Secretary Boris Berezovsky
are to attend a new round of Georgian-Abkhaz talks, which is being
held in Sukhumi, the capital of Abkhazia, between Abkhaz leader
Vladislav Ardzinba and Vazha Lordkipanidze, a special envoy of the
Georgian president.
</P>
<P>
The talks are expected to pave the way to a personal meeting
and certain agreements between Ardzinba and Georgian President
Eduard Shevardnadze, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Before departure at the airport, Pastukhov said that Yeltsin,
who chairs the Council of the Heads of the Commonwealth of
Independent States (CIS), believed that it was necessary to
facilitate the process of a peaceful settlement of the
Georgian-Abkhaz conflict.
</P>
<P>
The main objective of the current negotiations, Pastukhov said,
is to help eliminate the aftermaths of the latest aggravation of
the situation in the conflict region and solve the issues of
repatriating refugees, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Berezovsky stated on Thursday that the CIS Executive Board and
the Russian Foreign Ministry have formed a single consolidating
center for making decisions on the settlement of the Georgian-
Abkhaz problem.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the prospects for the settlement of the conflict,
the CIS executive secretary said that at this stage there are no
talks on exerting a pressure by force on Abkhazia.
</P>
<P>
He noted that although neither Tbilisi nor Sukhumi was pleased
with the efforts of the peacemakers, until now these peacekeeping
forces are an element of stability in the most complicated region.
</P>
<P>
The Georgian-Abkhaz conflict broke out when Abkhazia, a
northwestern autonomous republic of Georgia, proclaimed
independence in July 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
