<HEADLINE> Southwest China Province Seeking Investment in Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Song Baorui, governor of
southwest China's Sichuan Province, said recently that overseas
investors are welcome to the province's tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that Sichuan will offer a series of
preferential policies to ensure a high return for these investors.
</P>
<P>
The province considers toruism one of its six pillar industries
since it possesses the world famous natural relics at Jiuzhaigou and
Huanglong, the cultural relics of Leshan Buddha and Ermei
Mountain, the world's oldest water conservation project of
Dujiangyan, and more than 80 percent of China's pandas.
</P>
<P>
Song said that investment in tourism will focus on
infrastructure construction, which includes the construction of
the Jiuzhaigou Airport, the expansion work at the Shuangliu
International Airport, the opening of air routes to Singapore,
Thailand, Japan and the Republic of Korea, and accelerating
construction of some high-rate highways and special highways for
tourism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
