<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Nazi Officer Extradited on War Crime Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, June 18 (Xinhua) -- A former Nazi officer in charge a
concentration camp during the World War II was extradited to
Croatia Friday after more than half a century in exile in
Argentina.
</P>
<P>
Dino Sakic, under the escort of Croatian police, arrived at the
Zagreb Airport at 19:20 local time and was transported to a Zagreb
prison.
</P>
<P>
As the commander of Jasenovac concentration camp, known as the
"Auschwitz of the Balkans", Sakic, 76, is suspected of being
responsible for the deaths of several tens of thousands of Jews
and Serbians between 1941 and 1945.
</P>
<P>
After the fall of Nazi Germany in 1945, Sakic fled to Argentina
and lived an unnoticed life until last April 6 when he appeared in
a televised interview, defending his role in the concentration
camp.
</P>
<P>
After an urgent appeal by the Croatian government, Argentina
sanctioned Sakic's extradition back to his homeland.
</P>
<P>
Trial proceedings will begin from tomorrow. Sakic's lawyer
however claimed that any legal procedures should wait until after
the criminal investigation, which meant the official trial would
be six months away. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 07:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon's Independence Father Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon has lost the last of its
independence pillars with the death of veteran statesman Adel
Osseiran, local newspaper Daily Star reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Osseiran, who had been suffering from Parkinson's disease for
the past 15 years, died at midday Thursday on the way to hospital
in his native city of Sidon, his family said. He was 93.
</P>
<P>
During the 1943 struggle for independence from France,
Osseiran, then minister of supply and trade, was rounded up by
French forces, together with then President Beshara Khoury, Prime
Minister Riad Solh and two other ministers. They were later
released.
</P>
<P>
Pressures from local rebels, demonstrators and international
powers keen to undermine France's presense in the Middle East
prompted Paris to grant Lebanon its independence that year.
</P>
<P>
After the release of the leaders, Osseiran went on to become
one of Lebanon's prominent politicians, a career which spanned the
next five decades.
</P>
<P>
He took part in the parliamentary deliberations in Taif, Saudi
Arabia, which gave birth to the national accord document that put
an end to the 15-year civil war from 1975-1990.
</P>
<P>
He served as parliament speaker between 1953 and 1958 and also
held cabinet portfolios of defense, interior, justice, public
works, economy and education.
</P>
<P>
Osseiran was hailed as "belonging to a school of national
thought" and "an example of a generation of politicians who
entered the arena through the gates of knowledge, competency and
hard work in favor of Lebanon's unity and independence." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
