<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Independent Judiciary Maintained in HK: Chief Justice (by Tao Wenge) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 19 (Xinhua) -- As the first chief justice of
the Court of Final Appeal in the history of Hong Kong, Andrew Li
Kwok-nang said that he and his colleagues will try their best to
build their court into one with international reputation.
</P>
<P>
Sitting in his office, Li told Xinhua that he has almost given
up all his hobbies since he was appointed chief justice of the
Court of Final Appeal of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (SAR).
</P>
<P>
"We should try our best because Hong Kong citizens have a very
high expectation to the Court of Final Appeal of the HKSAR, the
first in the history of Hong Kong," Li said.
</P>
<P>
Nearly one year after Hong Kong returned to China on July 1,
1997, the principles of independent judiciary and rule of law have
been successfully maintained in the SAR, Li said in an exclusive
interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The independence of the judiciary means that everybody is equal
in face of the law no matter who he or she is and that the courts
exercise their judicial power independently, free from any
interference, Li elaborated.
</P>
<P>
He said that he felt no interference at all with his work
either from the mainland or from the SAR government.
</P>
<P>
The independence of the judiciary has been guaranteed by the
Basic Law in many areas, Li said.
</P>
<P>
The Basic Law prescribes that judges of the courts of the SAR
shall be appointed by the chief executive on the recommendation of
an independent commission composed of local judges, persons from
the legal profession and eminent persons from other sectors.
</P>
<P>
What's more, the Basic Law stipulates that the judges of the
Court of Final Appeal can hold their position life-long unless
they are no longer able to discharge their duties or conduct any
misbehavior, Li added.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of the Court of Final Appeal in the SAR
demonstrates that the Hong Kong people enjoy a high degree of
autonomy and it also demonstrates the implementation of the "one
country, two systems" principle in Hong Kong, Li said.
</P>
<P>
The SAR practices a judicial system different from that of the
Chinese mainland. With the exception that the power of final
adjudication was transmitted from the British Privy Council to the
Court of Final Appeal of the SAR, the current judicial system in
Hong Kong almost sees no change compared with the previous one, Li
said.
</P>
<P>
The Court of Final Appeal comprises not only local judges but
also judges invited from Britain, Australia and New Zealand where
the common law is practiced, Li said.
</P>
<P>
Li said that the number of appeals to his court has increased
compared with that to the British Privy Council because it costs
much less to settle the dispute in Hong Kong rather than sending
the cases to Britain as before.
</P>
<P>
"The most important thing is to have a just and fair verdict
and make the parties to the lawsuit respect our verdict," Li said.
</P>
<P>
Wearing a pair of glasses, the gray-haired chief justice looks
like a scholar rather than a judge.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that just like the other courts in Hong Kong,
the trial in the Court of Final Appeal is open to members of the
public. all the members of the public can come to listen and the
verdict is also open. "People can read our verdict on the Internet
now," Li said.
</P>
<P>
Turning to the building of his court, Li said that the training
of judges is very important.
</P>
<P>
"We have intensified the work of training in three areas: the
latest development of laws, particularly the laws in the common
law area, the Chinese language and the new technology," Li said.
</P>
<P>
Although Hong Kong is a Chinese dominated society, all the
trials were conducted in English before.
</P>
<P>
"That was unfair for those Chinese people who don't understand
English although interpreters were provided," Li said.
</P>
<P>
English is used in all the common law practiced areas but the
Chinese language is also very important because trials should be
understood by the ordinary citizens, Li said. "So, the Chinese
judges should learn their Chinese well," the chief justice noted.
</P>
<P>
"We invited famous judges from overseas to give us lectures and
introduce their experiences. We have established contacts with
courts in other common law practiced areas. In addition, we have
positively participated in international conferences," Li said.
</P>
<P>
Pointing to the piles of files in his office, the chief justice
said that all his time has been occupied by his work and learning
Putonghua (standard spoken Chinese) every Saturday afternoon has
become one of his hobbies now.
</P>
<P>
On the wall of his office, there is a piece of Chinese
calligraphy which reads being upright and avoiding flattery. Li
said that is his motto as a justice. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
