<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Close Lower in Tokyo on Profit-Taking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices fell in Tokyo Friday, led
by profit-taking activity after Thursday's substantial gains.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange slipped 93.56 points, or 0.61
percent, from Thursday's close to finish at 15,267.98.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, fell 11.57 points or 0.97 percent to 1,187.27.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section decreased to an estimated 480 million
shares from Thursday's 701 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan (LTCB) was the day's most heavily
traded issue.
</P>
<P>
The key Nikkei index stayed in negative territory throughout the
day, with market players skimming profits after the previous day's
increase of 650 points for the index, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Market sentiment was dampened as LTCB sank to a low of 95 yen
around 9:45 a.m. (local time), drifting below the 100 yen line for
most of the morning.
</P>
<P>
But an afternoon news report that the Japanese government is
considering a possible merger between the ailing LTCB and Nippon
Credit Bank (NCB) helped the Nikkei index recoup some early losses.
</P>
<P>
Market participants welcomed the news as it would likely accelerate
disposal of nonperforming loans at banks and prompt the Japan's
finance sector to reorganize, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,334 issues listed on the First Section, losers outpaced
gainers 679 to 419, with 170 issues remaining unchanged.
</P>
</TEXT>
