<HEADLINE> Ramos Returns Home After Receiving UNESCO Prize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
returned home Friday after a four-day trip to receive the U.N.
Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO) 1997
Felix Houphouet-Boigny Peace Prize in Senegal.
</P>
<P>
Ramos shared the prize with Governor Nur Misuari of the
Autonomous Region in Muslim Mindanao in Mindanao, the southern
Philippines, for their peace efforts.
</P>
<P>
Misuari, head of the former largest rebel group, the Moro
National Liberation Front, singed a final peace agreement with the
Ramos administration in September 1996 after 24 years of bloody
civil war.
</P>
<P>
Upon arrival at the Ninoy Aquino International Airport in
Manila, Ramos said the prize was an international recognition of
the efforts of the Philippines to achieve peace in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
"Such international recognition of our collective efforts to
build a just and lasting peace, coupled with a focused development
agenda in Mindanao, is of high significance to those whose
countries still suffer from bloody strife," he said.
</P>
<P>
During the trip to Senegal via France, Ramos also assured
French and African businessmen that there will be a continuity of
social and economic reforms under the next administration in the
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Philippine President-Elect Joseph Estrada would assume office
when Ramos' term expires on June 30 this year. 
</P>
