<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First Local Regulation to Ban Teenage Drinking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The south China city of Shenzhen
recently adopted an amended regulation totally banning sales of
alcohol to youngsters under 18 years of age.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen became the first Chinese city to adopt a local
rule prohibiting sales of alcohol to minors. The regulation
also bans advertising for spirits.
</P>
<P>
The amended regulation -- The Shenzhen Special Economic Zone
regulation on the Administration of Alcohol -- was adopted during
the executive meeting of the Second Shenzhen City People's
Congress.
</P>
<P>
The regulation also bans the use of lethal ethyl alcohol, raw
materials and additives in the production of spirits. Units and
individuals are prohibited from making and marketing unapproved
tonic alcohol.
</P>
<P>
The amended regulation also stipulates that alcohol producers
are not titled to tax reductions or exemptions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 07:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tensions over Cyprus Send Turkey's Stocks Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Tensions over Cyprus have
suppressed Turkey's stock market and worries are growing about
future plummeting if confrontation escalates, the Daily News
reported here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The near crisis wiped out gains in the morning session
resulting from the U.S. support of the Japanese yen, and sent the
Istanbul Stock Exchange into a deep slide Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The National-100 index closed at 3.965.51, down 81.6 points,
or 2 percent, from Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Brokers were worried that similar fluctuations might be
expected as long as the confrontation between Greece and Turkey
continues.
</P>
<P>
"The positive atmosphere in the foreign markets created by
U.S. support of the Japanese yen was also reflected in our
morning session," Murat Zelet, general director of the Boomerang
Investment Partnership, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"But in the afternoon, when news of Turkish fighter jets
landing in Cyprus and subsequent tension reached the market, we
witnessed a dive," he added.
</P>
<P>
Turkey sent six F-16 fighters to the Gecitkale Air Base in
northern Cyprus Thursday morning in response to Greek Air Force's
military movements on the southern part of the island state.
</P>
<P>
A Foreign Ministry statement earlier said Greece's four F-16
jets and two C-130 cargo planes had touched down in Cyprus,
constituting a threat to the security of Turkish Cypriots and
Turkey itself.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into Greek Cypriot-dominated south and
Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkish troops
intervened and took over the northern third of the island
following an abortive coup seeking union with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
