<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Severe Flooding Hits Southern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Flooding along various
tributaries of the Yangtze River in South China resulting from heavy
rains since June 11 have damaged crops and destroyed houses,
according to today's report issued by the State Flood Control and
Drought Relief Headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The report said torrential rain in the central and northern
sections of South China have led to serious flooding in Jiangxi,
Hunan and Fujian provinces.
</P>
<P>
Water levels along the Xinjiang River, a Yangtze tributary, has
remained at a record 29 meters above the warning level for four
consecutive days. The flood peak at 08:00 Thursday morning stood
at 29.73 meters, a level exceeding the previous record by 0.37
meters. However, the water level fell to 29.13 meters by 07:00
this morning.
</P>
<P>
The water level for the Zishui tributary hit 43.98 meters at
17:00 on June 14, some 2.98 meters above the warning level, with
the latest reports indicating the flooding continues to reside.
</P>
<P>
The Minjiang River, a regional river in east China's Fujian
Province, reached a flood peak of 12.82 meters at 14:00 on
June 18 some 1.82 meters above the warning level.
</P>
<P>
The report indicated that the water level for the main channel
of the Yangtze is now below the warning level.
</P>
<P>
The report, the first for this year, said that members of the
People's Liberation Army, China's armed forces, and local
residents were engaged in an all-out effort to combat flooding and
carry out rescue operations.
</P>
<P>
China has witnessed higher than normal rainfall since last
winter.
</P>
<P>
The report indicated that the flood season arrived one month
earlier than normal.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
