<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal's Economy Called Satisfactory in 10 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The performance of Nepal's most
macroeconomic indicators is satisfactory during the first 10
months of the current fiscal year which ends in mid-July, The
Rising Nepal daily said Friday, quoting the country's central
bank.
</P>
<P>
A substantial growth of 20 percent in exports plus a decline of
6.7 percent in imports has resulted in lower trade deficit and a
significant surplus of 7.925 billion rupees (122 million U.S.
dollars) in balance of payments, which in turn has contributed to
a substantial rise in foreign exchange reserves, the newspaper
quoted the Nepal Rastra Bank as saying.
</P>
<P>
According to the bank, by mid-May, the foreign exchange holding
of the banking system rose by 21.4 percent to 60.497 billion
rupees (930 million dollars), sufficient to cover average
merchandise imports for a period of more than eight months.
</P>
<P>
It said a decline in gold imports is one of the major causes
for the slowdown in the overall imports, and accordingly, the
total foreign trade of the country witnessed a fall of 1.6 percent
to 96.185 billion rupees (1.5 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Net foreign assets of the banking system increased by 19.7
percent during the first 10 months of the current fiscal year
compared with a rise of 13.2 percent last year, the bank noted in
a press release.
</P>
<P>
The net domestic assets, which grew by 8.9 percent last year,
went up by 6.3 percent during this period.
</P>
<P>
Domestic credit during the review period rose by 7.5 percent
while credit to the government decreased by 1.7 percent, the bank
said, adding that 69.9 percent of the total domestic credit went
to the private sector.
</P>
<P>
Total foreign cash assistance (grants and loans) during the
period soared to 6.631 billion rupees (102 million dollars) as
against 3.126 billion rupees (48 million dollars) last year, the
bank said.
</P>
<P>
On the price front, the national urban consumer price index
(base year 1983/84=100), on a point-to-point basis, rose by 6.6
percent during the period as against 5.3 percent for the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the country in the period saw a 3.4-percent growth
in total resources.
</P>
<P>
Development expenditure rose by 9.6 percent compared with zero
growth last year while the regular expenditure went up by 13.3
percent, the bank said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
