<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmers Welcome Management Transparency Over Their Affairs (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
According to a sociologist from the Chinese Academy of Social
Sciences, village affairs such as financial management, land
distribution for building housing and contracts for economic
programs which used to be closed to public opinion formed the major
cause of disputes in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
The lack of transparency and supervision over the actions of
village officials also led to corruption, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Central Committee of the Communist Party of China and the
State Council have jointly issued a circular urging the country's
nearly one million villages to adopt a system based on the "open
management of village affairs".
</P>
<P>
The circular stresses that introduction of the system is the
major task for work in rural areas and will in turn have an
important bearing on rural reform, development and stability.
</P>
<P>
The Organic Law on Village Committees in the People's Republic
of China passed in 1987 requires the direct election of all
village officials formerly appointed by governments at higher
levels.
</P>
<P>
Sixteen provinces across China have introduced regulations
governing implementation of the law. Most Chinese villages have
held three direct elections of village officials over the past
decade.
</P>
<P>
Information provided by the Ministry of Civil Affairs shows
that more than 60 percent of the country's villages have adopted
the system of "self-government by villagers". For example, over 90
percent of villages in Anhui Province have adopted the system
since 1992.
</P>
<P>
Xin Qiushui, an agricultural expert and researcher with the
Anhui Provincial Academy of Social Sciences, said the system of
"self-government by villagers" adapts to the need for farmers to
participate in the management of village affairs.
</P>
<P>
Xin noted that rural reform and implementation of contract
responsibility system provide more decision-making powers which
enable Chinese farmers to manage their own businesses. He said
farmers are exhibiting greater concern about their overall
interests, village affairs and the actions of local officials.
</P>
<P>
Wuhe County, for example, has established a leading group
responsible for promoting implementation of the system of "
self-government by villagers". As a result, more than 85 percent
of local farmers participated in village elections held in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmers Welcome Management Transparency Over Their Affairs (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Years ago farmers from Qutai Village
had to appeal to governments at higher levels for help when
dissatisfied with the improper management of local financial
affairs.
</P>
<P>
However, the situation has fundamentally changed since Wuhe
County in east China's Anhui Province where the village belongs to
introduced democratic elections for the village leader in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Local farmer Sun Baoting, the leader of the aforementioned
appeal effort, has since been elected to lead the village group
responsible for supervising the management of village affairs.
</P>
<P>
Sun noted that local villagers are satisfied with the current
management of village affairs since the adoption of system of
"self-government by villagers" which allows all villagers to voice
their opinions on their own affairs.
</P>
<P>
The village has also elected 21 representatives to soliciting
opinions on all major affairs which have an important bearing on
the interests of local villagers. Village leaders fully consider
all opinions before making final decisions.
</P>
<P>
The village also published a quarterly financial report and
various other village affairs.
</P>
<P>
According to a local villager, the "self-government by
villagers" means "four democracies" -- democratic elections of
village officials, democratic decision-making in village
management, democratic management of village affairs and
democratic supervision by villagers over village leadership.
</P>
<P>
"Self-government by villagers has enabled farmers to be the
masters of their own affairs which guarantees their democratic
rights and promotes stability, economic growth and social
development in rural areas," said Hui Liangyu, governor of Anhui
Province.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
