<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Builds System to Monitor National Marine Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, June 19 (Xinhua) -- China has built networks to monitor
the marine environment in all of its territorial waters after 20
years of effort.
</P>
<P>
Built by the National Oceanographic Bureau, the networks are
expected to provide essential data for drafting policies on
sustainable national marine development.
</P>
<P>
Covering a nationwide network and three regional networks, the
monitoring system can launch 1,300 surveys of water quality in all
the river mouths, ports and offshore areas in the country.
</P>
<P>
The system could launch more than 50 kinds of investigative
items including monitoring radiation materials, red tide,
petroleum spills and waste dumps.
</P>
<P>
Wang Shuguang, deputy director of the National Oceanographic
Bureau, said that the whole system has more than 1,300
technicians, 22 vessels, two planes and some 600 monitoring
devices as well as advanced location equipment and data processing
facilities.
</P>
<P>
Wang is currently on an inspection tour of the marine
environment protection system arranged by the Standing Committee
of the National People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
In the first 10 years of the next century, Wang noted, the
networks will focus on monitoring marine resources and the
biological effects of environmental pollution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
