<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Airlines Seeks Rehabilitation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Airlines (PAL) filed to
the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) here Friday a
rehabilitation plan intended to bring PAL back to financial
health.
</P>
<P>
Some 85 billion pesos (2 billion U.S. dollars) in debts will
have to be restructured to give PAL time to improve its cash flow
and enable it to service its loan payments, PAL said in a press
release.
</P>
<P>
PAL said it is current in all its loan obligations as of
Friday, but it is not in a position to project its cash flow in
the coming months because of the adverse effects of the pilots'
strike and the Asian currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
"Precisely we are seeking SEC assistance in implementing a
rehabilitation plan for PAL to avoid defaulting on our loans and
breaking up company assets that may arise from creditors' action,"
PAL President Jose Antonio Garcia said.
</P>
<P>
He assured PAL creditors that current assets of the company are
more than enough to cover its maturing obligations and that they
are in no danger of not being paid in case of closure. He added
that the company has over 90 billion pesos (2.2 billion dollars)
in assets.
</P>
<P>
Under the rehabilitation plan, PAL will reduce fleet size, lay
off personnel, dispose of excess assets and inventories,
restructure route network, give up routes and frequencies to
strategic alliances and obtain the support of creditors,
financiers and unions.
</P>
<P>
Over the last 12 years, PAL has suffered aggregate losses of 21
billion pesos (512 million dollars). Last fiscal year, it
registered a loss of 8 billion pesos (195 million dollars), the
largest in its history. The recent strike by pilots aggravated the
financial woes.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, PAL has decided to lay off 5,000 workers and fire all
the 620 pilots on strike.
</P>
<P>
PAL said rebuilding the airline will be long and difficult and
will entail a lot of sacrifices from all sectors concerned. It
appealed for cooperation and understanding as it strives to render
continued service to the riding public and the nation as a whole.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, commercial bank creditors and PAL reached an
agreement, recognizing the need to reschedule PAL's obligations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
