<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Search for Missing Peking Man Fossils (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 19 (Xinhua) -- China's leading scientists are
planning an ever-larger search for six skullcaps of Peking Man
which disappeared more than 50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The country's most authoritative paleoanthroplogists and
archeologist have solicited clues related to the missing
skullcaps, said Dong Junshe, a research fellow with the Institute
of Vertebrate Paleontology and Paleoanthropology of the Chinese
Academy of Sciences (CAS).
</P>
<P>
The find of Peking Man fossils, dating back about 500,000
years, around Zhoukoudian in suburban Beijing stunned the whole
world. However, the treasured six intact skullcaps disappeared
without a trace during World War II.
</P>
<P>
"We plan to publicize through the nationwide media a letter
which was co-signed by scores of CAS academicians to get support
from all over the country," said Dong here today in an exclusive
interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Jia Lanpo, a leading Chinese paleoanthropologist, said: "These
skullcaps are most likely buried somewhere in China. But the
search might be extremely difficult."
</P>
<P>
Jia, 89, has poured more than six decades into studying Peking
Man fossils. "We must find the skullcaps as early as possible,"
said Jia, who obtained worldwide fame largely because of his
excavating skullcaps of Peking Man.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Search for Missing Peking Man Fossils (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"We aim to arouse the conscience of the human being, enhancing
the development of science and world peace," Dong said.
</P>
<P>
"Potential clues might be lost forever," he said, because
almost all discoverers of the Peking Man fossils and other key
insiders are dead.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese people enthusiastically responded to the research
endeavor initiated by the CAS institute, he said. Some individuals
have offered to finance the work.
</P>
<P>
"Once the CAS and the State Bureau of Cultural Relics approve
the project, we will kick it off immediately," Dong said.
</P>
<P>
He also suggested that the authorities should better preserve
the Zhoukoudian ruins, where later excavations yielded mandibles,
facial bones, limb bones, teeth, animal fossils and 100,000-odd
stone tools.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with scientific reports, Peking Man has an
average cranial capacity of 1,075 cubic centimeters. Some skulls
are even characterized by 1,300 cubic centimeters of capacity,
equal to modern man.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, Chinese scientists and their global counterparts
have to rely on a broken Peking Man skull, which is now preserved
in the CAS institute.
</P>
<P>
Late Chinese archaeologist Pei Wenzhong stumbled upon the first
complete skull of Peking Man in a cave at Chou-k'ou-tien on
December 2, 1929.
</P>
<P>
In 1941, some attempts were made to send the six skullcaps
and other precious fossils to the United States when the Japanese
troops invaded China.
</P>
<P>
But the bones disappeared and have never been recovered after
leaving the Peking Union Medical College, the last place for
preserving them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Nicaragua Keep Unbeaten in World Cup qualifier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The United States and hosts
Nicaragua kept undefeated at 2-0 with victories on Thursday, the
second day of a baseball World Cup qualifying tournament.
</P>
<P>
The United States edged The Dominican Republic 4-3 while
Nicaragua ousted Colombia 9-6.
</P>
<P>
Canada, Mexico and Venezuela had their first win of the series.
</P>
<P>
Canada beat Panama 6-5 in 12 innings. But Venezuela eliminated
Argentina 15-5 in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
In the day's other match, Mexico overwhelmed Honduras 11-0 in
seven innings.
</P>
<P>
Ten teams from the Americas are competing for five berths at
the July 18-August 12 World Cup in Italy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
