<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Sets Fresh Target for Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has set a
new target of hosting two million tourists by 2002 despite a
recession in the country's top foreign exchange earner since
middle last year.
</P>
<P>
"After the target is realized, the tourism industry will be
expected to contribute about 20 percent to the gross domestic
product (GDP)," said Minister for Tourism Herry Kosgey.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government is planning to take serious measures to
revamp the tourism industry from the current slump, he was quoted
by Friday's Daily Nation newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
"An aggressive marketing drive will be stepped up in the
coming financial year to ensure Kenya recaptures its lost
leadership position in the world of tourism," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kosgey said Kenya has the potential of hosting the targeted
visitors since the existing hotel accommodation of more than
73,000 hotel beds, international airports, an expanded Tourist
Police Unit and other infrastructure are revitalizing.
</P>
<P>
The east African country had seen more than one million
visitors by the end of 1994, according to data from the Central
Bureau of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
There are a total of 59 national parks, game reserves and
marine parks in Kenya, one of the leading tourist destination in
Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
