<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cooperation Increases Between Shanghai, Boston </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's largest
metropolis, and Boston, one of the most technologically developed
cities in the United States, are stepping up efforts to promote
trade and economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"Shanghai's economic growth means great business opportunities
to Boston, and my mission here is to spur this momentum of
cooperation," said Robert J. Wolfgang, head of the Office of
International Trade and Business Development under the Office of
the Mayor of Boston.
</P>
<P>
Dramatic changes have taken place in Shanghai since he first
visited the city seven years ago, Wolfgang said Wednesday. He is
heading a 14-member trade delegation to Shanghai. The Chinese city
is maintaining its stable and healthy growth pattern after a
period of high-speed economic increases, he added.
</P>
<P>
Boston is home to many institutions of higher learning, such as
Harvard University, he said, and will make the most of its
scientific and technological advantages to cooperate with
Shanghai, which boasts science and technology, personnel
resources, and abundant capital.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. city is planning cooperative projects with Shanghai in
telecommunications, environmental protection technologies,
software development, biochemical research, tourism, financial
services, and education.
</P>
<P>
Boston officials are talking with Shanghai University to open a
program for business training and exchanges of teachers and
students. Later this year, Boston plans to organize 150 to 200 of
its businesses to do on-the-spot investigations in Shanghai,
Wolfgang said.
</P>
<P>
Members of the delegation include senior managers of
Boston-based multinationals and some MBA students at Bently
College. 
</P>
</TEXT>
