<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mahathir Rejects Market Forces as Way for Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad said Friday that his country could not rely on
market forces to combat the current economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Claims that these market forces are apparently aimed at forming
transparent governments, free from corruption and nepotism and any
form of crime by the leadership are mere excuses to gain control
or to re-colonize a country, he said.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the 52nd United Malays National Organization (UMNO)
General Assembly here, Mahathir said, "This is mere fairy tale.
Market forces are not meant to improve governments, financial
management and practices of the countries under attack."
</P>
<P>
On the contrary, what they do is actually allowing traders and
speculators to extract as much profits as possible from the
country.
</P>
<P>
"Hoping for market forces to create a stable currency exchange,
economy and stable politics is the same as not doing anything and
leaving everything to fate," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said market forces profit from economic and financial
instability caused by the attack on the currencies.
</P>
<P>
"Why should they stabilize the conditions at the expense of
their profits?" he asked.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, it is illogical that to resuscitate our economy and
currency, we should submit to the demands of market forces," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said these forces would continue attacking the
financial and economic systems until a democratically elected
leader bows to the outside powers.
</P>
<P>
"When this happens, the economy will be opened to foreign
companies and funds to enter and take over local big companies,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
However, Mahathir said Malaysia could still defend the local
companies from being acquired by foreigners who could only own 30
percent stake in companies and banks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
