<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tougher Anti-Smoking Laws Urged in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Health and Child Welfare
Ministry of Zimbabwe Thursday said tough anti-smoking measures
need to be taken through introduction of legislation which bans
smoking in tobacco free zones, to promote public health, the
Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Addressing guests at a ceremony to mark World Non-Tobacco Day
in Harare, deputy minister David Parirenyatwa said the
legislation should include, among other things, the banning of
all sponsorship of sporting activities by tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
It should also map out strategies that provide economic
alternatives to tobacco farmers and agricultural workers.
</P>
<P>
Places which could be declared tobacco-free zones include
public transport, health institutions, schools and other
education institutions, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Zimbabwe generates a lot of financial benefits from tobacco
growing and tobacco sales and exports," he said.
</P>
<P>
"My ministry's main concern is in protecting the health of all
the people in Zimbabwe from the ill effects of tobacco smoking,
both passive and active," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said tobacco kills up to 50 percent of smokers who start
smoking in their adolescence and continue throughout their lives.
</P>
<P>
He blamed adult influence and the easy accessibility of
tobacco to youths in the country as the main reasons why a big
number of youths smoked.
</P>
<P>
Tobacco alone is believed to be killing about 3.5 million
people every year worldwide through chronic illnesses such as
pulmonary diseases and cancer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
