<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Cambodian Parties Threaten to Boycott Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Two Cambodian opposition
parties, the Sam Rainsy and Son Sann Party, Friday threatened to
boycott the forthcoming elections if the electoral process is not
improved by the government and the National Election Committee
(NEC).
</P>
<P>
Sam Rainsy, president of the Sam Rainsy Party, and Son Soubert,
president of the Son Sann Party made the announcement in a joint
statement addressed to the Friends of Cambodia, an informal group
consisting of mostly donor countries to Cambodia, such as the
United States and Japan.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders stated that none of the requirements for fair
elections set out by the United Nations Secretary-General Kofi
Annan has been met. They believed that their hope for minimum
fairness in the elections has nearly vanished.
</P>
<P>
The statement said killings and intimidations continue; legal
institutions such as the Constitutional Council have been created
illegally and packed with ruling party supporters; hundreds of
thousands of citizens are denied the right to register; media
access is doled out in token amounts; and the ruling party has a
free reign.
</P>
<P>
Unless there is a commitment by the government and the NEC to
improving the electoral process, the two parties will declare on
July 5, three weeks before the scheduled polling, that they will
not take part in the July 26 election, the two leaders announced.
</P>
<P>
But they emphasized their commitment to participating in
reasonably fair elections which they believed could bring true,
long-term stability to Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
Sam Rainsy is one of Hun Sen's harshest critics and his Sam
Rainsy Party is a member of the National United Front (NUF), the
other three being Funcinpec, the Son Sann Party and Khmer Neutral
Party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
