<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0630 GMT, June 19 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI -- Vietnam earned 730 million U.S. dollars from exports
to the European Union (EU) in the first five months of this year,
Vietnam News Agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Garment and textiles led Vietnam's export items to the EU,
fetching 180 million dollars or 40 percent of the country's export
turnover in the past five months. The EU market has also opened
for processed aquatic products from 28 Vietnamese processing
enterprises which earned a combined turnover of 40 million dollars
or 13 percent of the sector's total export turnover.
(Vietnam-EU-Exports)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
COLOMBO -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB) is to help Sri
Lanka improve its water resources management, the ADB sources here
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
It will provide a technical assistance grant of 1.5 million
U.S. dollars to prepare a project aimed at improving water
resources management of five river basins surrounding Colombo, the
sources said. (Sri Lanka-ADB-Assistance)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- The Indonesian government has signed an agreement
with the Export-Import Bank of Japan that will provide a loan of
one billion U.S. dollars aimed at helping Indonesian exporters,
press reports said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The yen-denominated loan will be used for guaranteeing letters
of credits issued by banks in Indonesia, which have thus far been
rejected by most banks overseas, Finance Minister Bambang Subianto
told reporters after the signing ceremony here Thursday.
(Indonesia-Japan-Loan)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The World Bank Thursday approved two loans
totaling 600 million U.S. dollars for two projects in China.
</P>
<P>
The first loan of 300 million dollars will be used to help the
Hunan power development project. This project will alleviate power
shortages in Hunan province by providing efficient, reliable and
environmentally sound power supply. (WB-Loans-China) 
