<HEADLINE> Japan Pledges Efforts to Stablize Financial System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Japan will do its best to stablize
its financial system by resolving bad-loan problems appropriately,
Foreign Minister Keizo Obuchi said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi made the remark while meeting visiting U.S. Deputy
Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers, the Kyodo News Service
reported.
</P>
<P>
Summers, who arrived here on Thursday, met Obuchi and Japanese
Finance Minister Hikaru Matsunaga to exchange views on the world's
economy, the yen-dollar exchange rate and Japan's economic slump.
</P>
<P>
Both sides expressed satisfaction with the success of recent
joint intervention by the two countries' monetary authorities to
prop up the yen against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
Summers told reporters after the talks that Washington and
Tokyo "share strong interest" in maintaining Asian economies on a
course of sustainable growth.
</P>
<P>
In a separate meeting, Governor of Bank of Japan Masaru Hayami
and Summers discussed Japan's plan to solve its bad-loan problem.
</P>
<P>
The governor said Japan was aware of the necessity to
accelerate the bad-loan disposal. Summers showed his understanding
toward the Japanese stance.
</P>
<P>
Summers is scheduled to meet leaders of the ruling Liberal
Democratic Party (LDP) later Friday.
</P>
<P>
He is also expected to attend Saturday's emergency meeting of
finance ministers' deputies and central bank governors from the
Group of Seven major industrialized nations and Asia-Pacific
countries. 
