<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet Improves Health Care for Women, Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Women and children in the Tibet
Autonomous Region enjoy good health care thanks to the extensive
efforts of local governments and the support of the central
government.
</P>
<P>
The region has established a health care network covering all
urban and rural areas, with related centers and stations for women
and children available in 48 prefecture and counties.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 hospitals at or above the county level have
established gynecology and obstetrics departments, and 110
townships, or more than 60 percent of the total, have opened
health care centers for women and children.
</P>
<P>
Constantly improving health care for women and children over
the past four decades has reduced the region's infant mortality
rate from 430 per thousand the only 37 per thousand. In addition,
the mortality rate for pregnant women has dropped from 50 per
thousand to only three per thousand.
</P>
<P>
The average life expectancy of local women has grown from
36 years to 65 years.
</P>
<P>
The region also has cooperated extensively with international
organizations such as the the United Nations Children's Fund and
the World Health Organization in developing health care programs
for women and children.
</P>
<P>
Tibet has trained over 4,000 health care professionals for
rural areas in recent years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hughes Saves Stranded Satellite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Hughes Global Services Inc.
announced Thursday it had successfully used the moon's gravity to
slingshot a stranded communication satellite into useful orbit
around the Earth.
</P>
<P>
The 3.8-ton wayward satellite had been stuck in a useless orbit
since it was launched last December for Asia Satellite
Telecommunications Co. Ltd. of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
It now orbits at the desired 22,300 miles above the Pacific
Ocean, said the company.
</P>
<P>
The salvage mission by Hughes Global Services Inc., a
subsidiary of Hughes Space and Communications Co., marked the
first time that a private company has sent a spacecraft to the
moon for a commercial purpose.
</P>
<P>
Only NASA has used the slingshot technique for interplanetary
exploration before.
</P>
<P>
Hughes officials believe that using gravity as a fuel-saving
device will make launches cheaper or allow companies to put
heavier satellites into place. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0220 </DOCNO>
