<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Armey: House to Complete Finance Legislation by August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Dick Armey, Majority Leader of
the U.S. House of Representatives, promised on Thursday that the
house would complete work on campaign finance legislation by
August. Democrats however accused the Republican leadership of
delaying tactics aimed at ensuring that no bill will survive.
</P>
<P>
Armey said he had told republicans supporting campaign funding
measures that "they should be assured that proceedings on this
bill in this house will be completed in their entirety by the
August recess."
</P>
<P>
In turn, Representative Christopher Shays, a republican and
co-sponsor of one of the leading campaign finance proposals, and
other republicans agreed to back a leadership initiative that
could allow a stream of amendments to be offered.
</P>
<P>
Democrats railed at the procedural rule, approved by a mostly
party-line 221-189 vote, that would allow lawmakers to offer 258
unrelated amendments to the various campaign funding bills on the
agenda.
</P>
<P>
Representative David Bonior, a democrat, said the republicans
aimed to delay action and to "divide, derail and destroy any
possibility of substantive bipartisan reform."
</P>
<P>
Representative Martin Frost, a democrat, said that even if work
was finished by August it would be too late for the senate to
act.
</P>
<P>
The senate abandoned campaign finance legislation after making
little headway earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
Republicans, however, argued that democrats were trying to stop
open debate.
</P>
<P>
After the procedural vote, the house began debate on what could
be the most popular of 12 proposals to revamp campaign funding
practices the house will debate in coming weeks. The proposal
that wins the most votes will become the final House version.
</P>
<P>
The bipartisan proposal of Shays and Representative Marty
Meehan, a democrat, would ban so-called "soft money" --
unregulated donations to national and state political parties from
corporations, labor unions and individuals. It would also regulate
issue advertising by third parties and expand disclosure
requirements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
