<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Maldivian President Awarded WHO Gold Medal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Maldivian President Maumoon Abdul
Gayoom has been awarded the prestigious Health For All Gold Medal
by the World Health Organization (WHO), according to WHO sources
here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The award was handed over Sunday to Gayoom by WHO Director
General Hiroshi Nakajima in Male, capital of the Maldives.
</P>
<P>
According to the citation which accompanied the award, the
medal was given in recognition of President Gayoom's outstanding
contribution to the attainment of a social goal of health for all
in his country.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that over the past two decades, the Maldives
has made remarkable progress in the area of public health due to
the vision, initiative and dedication of Gayoom.
</P>
<P>
The Maldives had eradicated many communicable diseases,
decreased infant mortality rate from 120 to 27 per 1000 live
births and increased life expectancy from 48 to 71 years.
</P>
<P>
Since 1993, the UNDP's Human Development Index had ranked the
Maldives far ahead of many developing nations as a country of
medium level achievement and social development.
</P>
<P>
In 1978, the Maldives had only one small hospital and one
physician per 20,700 people.
</P>
<P>
Today, hospital bed capacity has increased about ten-fold, and
a ratio of 1,300 persons per physician has been achieved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
