<HEADLINE> Myanmar's Transportation Improves in 1997-98 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar's transport sector
increased 6.6 percent in value in 1997-98 fiscal year ending
March over the previous year, according to the latest official
statistics.
</P>
<P>
Measures were taken in the year for the development of the
sector by joint operation with local and foreign companies in the
road, rail and air transportation and construction of container
terminal wharves, said a  report on the country's financial,
economic and social conditions.
</P>
<P>
During the year, in addition to the increase of various means
of transport, 1,553 kilometers of highways were also built,
extending to 29,844 km, and 307 km of railroads were expanded,
adding up to 5,750 km.
</P>
<P>
The capacity of road, rail and water transport also increased
over the previous year, it said.
</P>
<P>
In air transport, the state-run Myanmar Airways and other joint
venture airlines were operating the internal flights, transporting
a total of 900,000 passengers on the domestic routes in the year,
while 250,000 international passengers were transported by the
Myanmar Airways International and 11 foreign airlines, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
The country's transport sector shared 4.3 percent of its gross
domestic product in 1997-98 which grew by 4.6 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
