<HEADLINE> Partial Cut in Ukraine Conscription </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Ukranian President Leonid Kuchma has
ordered a partial suspension of this year's conscription, the
Information Office of the Ukranian Defense Ministry disclosed
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma, also the commander-in-chief of the Ukranian army,
issued the order Wednesday, calling on the Ukranian Armed Forces,
the National Guard, the Security Service and the Communication
Troops to stop conscription.
</P>
<P>
However, the Interior Force, the Border Guard Troops and the
Civil Defense Forces could continue their recruiting.
</P>
<P>
The Ukranian army, which conscripts 100,000 people annually,
has absorbed 70,000 so far this year. The number of servicemen
will be reduced by 30,000 this year because of retirements.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine, which has a 350,000 strong regular army, planned this
year to reduce it by 17,000 servicemen.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here linked Kuchma's order with the government's
anticipation of considerably cutting down financial expenditure
and reducing the budget deficit to 2.5 percent of the gross
domestic product. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
