<HEADLINE> Turkmenistan Able to Meet Food Needs by 2000, Says President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Turkmenistan will be able to fully
satisfy its domestic food needs by the year 2000, President
Saparmurad Niyazov said in the capital city of Ashabad Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Itar-Tass news agency reported that Niyazov had set for its
agro-industrial complex a two-million-ton target in both grain and
unginned cotton output by 2000.
</P>
<P>
The president said the grain production goal for this year was
1.2 million tonnes. So far, the country has already purchased more
than 550,000 tonnes of summer grain from the farmers.
</P>
<P>
The current grain producing capacity for the state of Lebap
alone is 20,000 tonnes, which the president has raised to 26
tonnes for the next year.
</P>
<P>
Farmers in the state were optimistic about the target, saying
that the task would be fulfilled by turning waste land into arable
ones.
</P>
<P>
Turkmenistan, the country with 80 percent of its territory
being desert, used to give top priorities to cotton growing and
sheep husbandry.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to a rapid grain production rise in recent years, food
supply in the country has witnessed steady improvement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
