<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Host Int'l Conference on Chittagong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- A two-day international conference
will begin here Saturday to garner support for the development of
the country's southeastern Chittagong Hill Tracts (CHT), press
reports here said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, jointly organized by the Economic Relations
Division under the Ministry of Finance and the United Nations
Development Program, is also aimed at disseminating information
about the prospects of development projects in the hill districts
following the singing of the CHT peace accord between the
government and the tribals last December.
</P>
<P>
The conference, titled "peace and Chittagong Hill Tracts" and
scheduled to be inaugurated by Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina, would
focus on the prospects of development in the CHT, Finance Minister
Shah A.M.S. Kibria said. "We must now consolidate the gains of the
peace treaty. We must involve everyone and take up development
schemes," he added.
</P>
<P>
"We hope to generate greater awareness in the international
community about the prospects of investment and development in the
CHT. We want to sensitize the international community,
particularly donors, so that they are encouraged to take up
participatory programs," Economic Relations Division Secretary
Mashiur Rahman was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The three major objectives of the conference were to learn
about the experiences of ethnic conflicts in other countries, to
find out what sort of institutional measures could be taken up for
development and to list the economic potentials that could be
tapped, he said.
</P>
<P>
Canada, Australia, and the Netherlands have made commitment to
extending assistance for development activities in the CHT, and
the World Bank and the Asian Development Bank have also shown
interest in taking up projects in the region, according to Rahman.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the embassies and the leading donor agencies
would participate in the conference, and some members of the
British parliament and representatives of some leading
governmental and non-governmental organizations and think-tanks
might also be present at the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
