<HEADLINE> Ukraine Expedites Economic Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma
issued a package of decrees on economic reform with an aim to
reduce taxes and stimulate economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The decrees order a cut in the value-added tax, unification of
the agriculture tax, and the simplification of procedures for tax
payments by small and middle-sized enterprises.
</P>
<P>
In his address to the nation, Kuchma explained that the
newly-elected Supreme Rada (parliament) has been paralyzed with
inactivity for more than a month, due to the fact that it has not
been able to elect a speaker. As a result, it has not been able to
review the 42 economic proposals submitted by the Ukraine cabinet.
</P>
<P>
In this situation, the president said, he was compelled to
issue these decrees.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma said that although a long-sustained production drop is
already under control, budget revenues and the overall economic
situation has not yet taken a turn for the better.
</P>
<P>
The president said his greatest concern is that the financial
crisis would effect the stability of the Ukrainian currency hryvna
drastically, which could lead to inflation and another decline in
production.
</P>
<P>
The hryvna-U.S. dollar rate dropped from 1.8:1 to 2.05:1 this
year.
</P>
<P>
To stablize the economy, the government has no other way but
to borrow at home and abroad, the president said.
</P>
<P>
So far, Ukraine's total debt has surpassed 17 billion dollars
which includes domestic debts equivelent to 7 billion dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moldova Crippled by Energy Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Power shortages in Moldova have
crippled government institutions, hospitals, banks,
telecommunication services and public transportation.
</P>
<P>
The Moldovan Basa Press reported on Thursday that during the
most serious energy crisis in recent years, the capital city of
Chisinau has been hit by an ongoing series of power black-outs
with the presidential palace the only survivor of the energy
shortfall.
</P>
<P>
The power predicament is the result of a June 8 decision by
Russia's gas monopoly Gazprom, Moldova's major source of energy,
to cut its gas supply in half in a bid to press for an immediate
payment of the 200-million-dollar gas dues.
</P>
<P>
Gazprom's move has affected the operation of the leading power
plant in Moldova, which provides eighty percent of the country's
electricity.
</P>
<P>
The Moldovan government, which is unable to pay the debt, has
to make daily power cuts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
