<HEADLINE> 52nd UMNO General Assembly Opens in Kuala Lumpur </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The three-day 1998 United
Malays National Organization (UMNO) general assembly, the party's
52nd, began here Friday attended by more than 1,900 delegates.
</P>
<P>
The opening ceremony started with Prime Minister and UMNO
President Mahathir Mohamad inspecting a guard-of-honor mounted by
a brigade of the party's youth and women's wings followed by a
flag-raising ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir then delivered the presidential address formally
opening the general assembly.
</P>
<P>
He said that UMNO members and leaders at all levels must not
allow envy, hatred and vengeance to control them in facing the
economic crisis, and instead they must ensure that their thinking
should curtail their desires at the very least.
</P>
<P>
"Let others be dominated by the feeling of vengeance, hatred
and envy, etc. Whatever we do, it should be based on our thoughts
and judgments consistent with the needs of an advanced
civilization," he said in addressing the 1,907 delegates.
</P>
<P>
In his speech entitled "The Challenges of Turmoil", Mahathir
spoke at length of factors that had caused the economic problems
which hit the country nearly a year ago.
</P>
<P>
"We should understand all this. We should understand because
whether we are successful or not in our effort to overcome the
financial and economic crisis will depend on how much we all
understand the problems we are facing," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Not understanding what exactly attacked us is equivalent to
being blind and not knowing exactly the source of the attack.
People who do not know what exactly attacked them will create
enmities with the other people, the innocent. Thus the attackers
will have a big laugh," he said.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the National Front component parties, local and
foreign observers were among the party's guests at the opening
along with 14 representatives of political parties from other
countries, including China.
</P>
<P>
Eighteen representatives and six observers from UMNO clubs
overseas are also attending the assembly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
