<HEADLINE> Thai Government Urged to Issue Bonds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government must speed up
the issuing of global bonds to address the liquidity crunch faced
by Thai businesses, leading businessmen told Prime Minister Chuan
Leekpai Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
The parliament had passed four executive decrees earlier this
month, allowing the government to issue 5 billion U.S. dollar
global bonds.
</P>
<P>
The Nation reported Friday that the prime minister held a
working dinner with 15 top businessmen Thursday night to discuss
the economic problems and listen to their opinions on how to
tackle the current economic woes.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister Supachai Panitchpakdi and Finance
Minister Tarrin Nimmanhaeminda also joined the dinner.
</P>
<P>
The businessmen, including Thai Bankers Association President
Banthoon Lamsam, Thai Chamber of Commerce President Vichien
Tejapaibul and Federation of Thai Industries President Thawee
Butrsunthorn, said liquidity and debt restructuring are essential
to revive the Thai economy.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted government spokesman Akrapol Sorasuchat as
saying the business leaders agreed that liquidity is a more
important issue than the efforts to control interest rates. They
said better liquidity will eventually cause rates to decline.
</P>
<P>
For debt restructuring, the business leaders proposed that the
government set up a neutral body to coordinate the work by holding
negotiations between creditors and debtors.
</P>
<P>
The government was also urged to help the export sector, which
is facing tight liquidity, and to promote tourism and related
businesses by strictly enforcing laws to punish those who cheat
foreign tourists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
