<HEADLINE> ADB Helps Sri Lanka Improve Water Resources Management </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
is to help Sri Lanka improve its water resources management, the
ADB sources here said Friday.
</P>
<P>
It will provide a technical assistance grant of 1.5 million
U.S. dollars to prepare a project aimed at improving water
resources management of five river basins surrounding Colombo, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
Water quality has been deteriorating due to industrial and
urban pollution and increasing salinity. Several densely populated
wetland ecosystems are under severe pressure from pollution and
floods are problems in some of the basins.
</P>
<P>
The ADB project is expected to promote efficient investment in
priority sub-projects for water supply management, flood control
and watershed management. It will also restore economically
important wetland and lake ecosystems, the sources pointed out.
</P>
<P>
With a large number of Sri Lanka's industries concentrated in
the project area, it accounts for a high and increasing share of
the country's gross domestic product, the sources added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
