<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico to Become U.S. Second Trade Partner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Mexico is to replace Japan as
the second U.S. trade partner, it was announced here thursday.
</P>
<P>
Reports from the U.S. Department of Commerce published here say
that Mexico imported in the first four months this year U.S. goods
worth 26.12 billion U.S. dollars, 31.1 percent more than the
19.92 billion dollars accumulated by Japan in the same period.
</P>
<P>
the total trade between Mexico and the United States in that
period amounted to 56.25 billion dollars, only 4.4 million dollars
less than the U.S.-Japan trade.
</P>
<P>
In comparison, said the announcement, the difference was 14.358
billion dollars in the same period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The figures showed that trade between the United States and
Mexico grew by 16.78 percent in the last 12 months and went from
48.168 billion dollars in the first four months of 1997 to 56.25
billion dollars in the same period of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Mexico's trade surplus with the United States dropped from
5.38 billion dollars in the first four months of 1997 to 4.01
billion dollars in the same period of 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
