<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Boost Farmers' Income </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka has adopted a series of
measures to boost farmers' income by revitalizing the agricultural
sector, President Chandrika Kumaratunga said Thursday, according
to press reports.
</P>
<P>
Inaugurating a scheme for a development center at Sooriyawewa
in North Central province, the president said her government was
committed to boosting farmers' income.
</P>
<P>
The center will be built at a cost of 26.2 million U.S. dollars
to promote economic, social and cultural activities and a post
harvest technology training center will be set up.
</P>
<P>
She said a three year irrigation program envisages the
improvement of irrigation facilities initially for 2,900 hectares
now under cultivation and then the area under irrigation will
expand by another 1,100 hectares as well as allocation of
agricultural plots to farmers.
</P>
<P>
Another project encompasses the development of 5,340 hectares
which will provide settlement for 5,300 farming families at a cost
of 84.62 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The president said that the government is conscious of creating
an environment conducive to the country's farming community which
constitutes 52 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
At present yields in paddy and other crops are comparatively
low. Measures are being taken to improve this situation by
providing high yielding paddy seeds to farmers.
</P>
<P>
She stated the country is able to spend only 20 percent of its
earnings on development with 25 percent going to public servants,
another 25 percent for pensions and 30 percent on the war.
</P>
<P>
However, the president added that the government plans to set
up a large number of farms and vocation training centers in
different districts to uplift the lives of the farmers. 
</P>
