<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tourist Arrivals in Thailand Up in 1st 4 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BANGKOK, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Tourist arrivals in Thailand
during the first four months of this year increased by 3.2 percent
to about 1.9 million compared with the same period last year, but
lower than the 5.4 percent target set by the Tourism Authority of
Thailand (TAT).
</P>
<P>
The Bangkok Post Friday quoted TAT as saying that the
disappointing result should be mainly attributed to the big drop
in arrivals from some major Asian markets.
</P>
<P>
The regional economic crisis pushed overall arrivals from east
Asia down by 7.08 percent to 973,829. The biggest drop came from
South Korea, down by 79.55 percent, followed by Indonesia, down by
67.39 percent.
</P>
<P>
Arrivals from Japan, the biggest single market for Thailand at
the moment, also fell by 9.81 percent to 291,615, and the weak yen
is expected to further discourage overseas travel, TAT said.
</P>
<P>
However, a positive trend has emerged among Asian countries
and regions less affected by the crisis. Arrivals from Hong Kong
rose by 40.14 percent, while the numbers of Singapore and Taiwan
tourists increased by 37.73 percent and 16.97 percent, TAT figures
showed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, more tourists from European countries preferred to
spend their holidays in Thailand, with overall arrivals rising by
15.19 percent to 608,076. Russia and eastern Europe emerged as the
rapidly growing markets.
</P>
<P>
Realizing that the Amazing Thailand 1998-99 campaign has not
been achieving its goal, the TAT is scheduled to hold a meeting in
Bangkok early next month with directors of all its overseas
offices.
</P>
<P>
The Thailand Tourism Society, which groups several
private-sector organizations, is also preparing a marketing plan.
</P>
<P>
The society will also seek a meeting with Prime Minister Chuan
Leekpai on ways to promote tourism and bring in more foreign
exchange. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
