<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO, Russia Seek Political Solution for Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, June 18 (Xinhua) -- NATO and Russia will continue
their efforts to seek diplomatic solutions to the Kosovo Crisis,
NATO Secretary General Javier Solana said here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Solana said it does not make
sense to impose a deadline on the resumption of negotiations
between the Yugoslav government and ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
However, NATO will continue to support any effort to resume
dialogue between the conflicting sides in Kosovo, added Solana,
who arrived here on Thursday for a two-day visit.
</P>
<P>
He said NATO will help implement the agreement Russian
President Boris Yeltsin and Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
reached on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Milosevic promised to resume dialogue with
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo and end repressive action against
civilians there.
</P>
<P>
But Milosevic refused to withdraw Yugoslav troops immediately
from the troubled province -- the key demand of the six-nation
Contact Group, which includes Britain, France, Germany, Italy,
Russia and the United States.
</P>
<P>
It is important to take a sensible attitude toward the Kosovo
crisis, Solana said. But if Milosevic cannot keep to his promise,
NATO would consider solving the crisis through military action.
</P>
<P>
More than 300 people have been killed since tensions escalated
in Kosovo in early March. About 65,000 of the 1.8 million
population have fled their homes in the province, where ethnic
Albanians account for 90 percent of the population. Ethnic
Albanian separatists have been seeking independence from
Yugoslavia since 1981.
</P>
<P>
In a sign to show Finland's support for international efforts
in the Balkans, Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari said at the
meeting with Solana that Helsinki will enhance its peacekeeping
forces in Bosnia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
