<HEADLINE> Endangered Plants at Three Gorges Area Relocated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, June 19 (Xinhua) -- More than 30 rare species of
endangered plants, such as dove trees, which were moved from the
Three Gorges reservoir area are doing well, botanists said.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the world's largest water conservation project
at the Three Gorges of the Yangtze River will raise the water
level and inundate some plants.
</P>
<P>
The removal of rare species began in 1995, and botanists at
Wuhan Plant Research Institute, Hubei Province, chose a favorable
location in the Jiugong Mountains where the same species of plants
were found growing well under similar climatic and soil conditions.
</P>
<P>
Botanists have set up a four-hectare protection base for the
endangered plants in the mountainous areas with elevations ranging
from 700-to-4,000 meters.
</P>
<P>
Research for the relocation was started in the 1980s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
