<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Steel Production Strengthened to Promote China's Auto Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 19 (Xinhua) -- China will accelerate the
automotive steel manufacturing of its key steel producers, and
turn Baoshan Iron and Steel Group (Baogang) into a reliable supply
base for various types of auto steel by the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the development plan for auto steel, Zhao Kun,
assistant general manager of Baogang, said the Chinese iron and
steel giant is now undergoing its third-phase construction which
involves 700 million U.S. dollars in investment.
</P>
<P>
The two cold rolling mills in the third-phase project aim to
manufacture all types of steel for the modern auto industry,
according to Zhao.
</P>
<P>
The auto industry is one of the focuses of Baogang. Statistics
show Baogang holds 60.2 percent of the cold rolled sheet supply
and 46.2 percent of the hot rolled sheet supply for China's eight
major automobile producers.
</P>
<P>
By 2010 when the group completes its technology upgrading and
new projects, 2 million tons of auto sheet production capacity
will be added, said Zhao.
</P>
<P>
By then, 1 million tons of auto sheet steel should be added to
the existing production capacity of both Wuhan and Anshan iron and
steel groups.
</P>
<P>
A new capacity of 350,000 tons of cold rolled sheet will be
created in Panzhihua Iron and Steel Group, and that for Benxi
Group is designed to be 300,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
Among steel sheets, automotive sheet steel is the most
technologically demanding, said Wang Xiaoqi, deputy director of
the Development Planning of China's State Administration of the
Metallurgical Industry.
</P>
<P>
The equipment and technology involved in the production of
automotive sheet steel is of great significance to the development
of the auto industry, he said.
</P>
<P>
China will produce 6 million automobiles in 2010. The auto
industry will consume 1.37 million tons of hot rolled sheets and
2.75 million tons of cold rolled sheets then.
</P>
<P>
Baogang merely produces one-fourth of the projected cold rolled
sheet consumption in 2010.
</P>
<P>
China's auto industry is crying for a larger supply of
domestically made sheets that "have stable quality and low price"
to substitute for imported ones, Zhao said.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that automakers in China, including joint
ventures, work on a closer relationship with steel suppliers in
such areas as joint development of new automobile models and
materials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
