<HEADLINE> Indonesian Govt Pledges Safety for Foreign Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Government has pledged
full security to foreign investors seeking to invest in the
country's trade and industry, press reports said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The government's guarantee was made by Coordinating Minister
for Political and Security Affairs Feisal Tanjung and Armed Forces
(ABRI) Commander General Wiranto after a meeting with President
B.J. Habibie at the Presidential office here Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, Tanjung said: "Foreign investors are asked
not to hesitate when they come to investing capital in the country
as there is a full security guarantee from the government."
</P>
<P>
The government is determined to meet all its commitments as
agreed upon with the international community, he said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia is now in the grip of a series of deep financial and
economic crisis in which inflation and prices have soared. Many
companies and factories have also been forced to close down,
resulting in a record unemployment high of 15 million.
</P>
<P>
Tanjung said the government had already set in motion various
measures to implement reforms in the political, economic and legal
sectors.
</P>
<P>
"But it must be understood that reforms essentially need time
and due process," he added.
</P>
<P>
Tanjung said some people had misinterpreted the meaning of
reform, and had used reform as a tool to force their will upon
others, or even to flaunt the law and public interests.
</P>
<P>
In a press statement, Wiranto urged the nation to immediately
cease all "emotional expressions" which would only make it
difficult for the government and the nation to revive the
development drive.
</P>
<P>
He warned of attempts by certain forces to destroy people's
confidence in the government, including the military, which, if
not stopped, could lead to national disintegration.
</P>
<P>
Rumors circulating that former leaders of the previous
administration are to stage a comeback, or interrupt the flow of
reforms are misleading and unfounded, Wiranto said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
