<HEADLINE> Shandong Develops Marine Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, June 19 (Xinhua) -- East China's Shandong Province is
drafting an ambitious plan to expand its marine economy.
</P>
<P>
The plan calls for the marine industry to contribute 10 percent
to the province's gross domestic product by 2010.
</P>
<P>
Shandong's 1997 GDP hit 665 billion yuan, with the industrial
output for the marine industry reaching 35 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Shandong borders on both the Bohai Sea and Yellow Sea and is
home to approximately a sixth of the nation's coastline. The
province's 50-plus bays and beaches covering some three million
hectares provide favorable conditions for developing sea
aquaculture and deepwater ports.
</P>
<P>
Shandong initiated extensive development of coastal areas in
early 1991 and has since led the nation in sea
aquaculture, chemical salt production and offshore petroleum
development.
</P>
<P>
Related industries have emerged as the backbone of the
provincial economy.
</P>
<P>
The province plans to develop its marine manufacturing sector
while significantly expanding the service industry.
</P>
<P>
The aquaculture and sea fishing industries contributes 59
percent of the province's total marine economy, with an additional
20 percent coming from aquatic product processing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
