<HEADLINE> Indonesia Receives 1b Dollars Trade Loan From Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government has
signed an agreement with the Export-Import Bank of Japan that will
provide a loan of one billion U.S. dollars aimed at helping
Indonesian exporters, press reports said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The yen-denominated loan will be used for guaranteeing letters
of credits issued by banks in Indonesia, which have thus far been
rejected by most banks overseas, Finance Minister Bambang Subianto
told reporters after the signing ceremony here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The five-year loan has a three-year grace period and is
separate from Japan's commitment to the International Monetary
Fund's 43 billion U.S. dollars bailout package.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the loan will help the economy by helping
exporters buy imported raw materials and parts to manufacture
exports.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the United States Agency for International
Development (USAID) announced Thursday it would give an additional
50 million U.S. dollars in aid in the form of food and loan
guarantees.
</P>
<P>
USAID administrator Brian Atwood told a public forum here
Thursday the agency would spend 25 million dollars, in addition to
25 million dollars pledged earlier, to provide Indonesia with
50,000 tons of American rice.
</P>
<P>
The agency will also provide an additional 25 million dollars
in loan guarantees to support the construction of urban
environmental infrastructure, such as drinking water services and
drainage canals.
</P>
<P>
So far, USAID has allocated over 100 million dollars in
humanitarian assistance to Indonesia. It has also provided 25
million dollars in concessional loans to buy rice and other food,
and 26 million dollars in technical expertise for the Indonesian
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
