<HEADLINE> Bicycles Rapidly Disappear In South China City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Bicycles, once a major means of
transportation for Chinese, are rapidly disappearing in Guangzhou,
capital of Guangdong Province and one of the most prosperous
citiesin China.
</P>
<P>
Nearly three million of the city's total population of 3.9
million people are using modern modes of transportation such as
buses, cars and motorcycles thanks to the past 20-odd
years of reform and opening to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
Individuals own some 90 percent of the city's over 600,000
motor vehicles. About two households own one car or motor bike,
according to a recent issue of China Economic Herald.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper reported that the city leads the nations with 13
public buses per 10,000 people.
</P>
<P>
The city's transportation department plans to further improve
public transportation to ensure all residents have access to a
public bus stop within a five minutes walk.
</P>
<P>
The city's sustained economic development has supported the
strong growth of public transportation and private vehicles,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou's per capita GDP has soared to 3,000 US dollars, one
of the highest levels for a Chinese province.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
