<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gingrich Says House to Unveil Slimmed-Down Tobacco Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 18 (Xinhua) -- One day after tobacco
legislation perished in the U.S. Senate, Speaker Newt Gingrich
said Thursday Republicans in the House of Representatives will
soon unveil a separate, slimmed-down bill to curtail teen smoking.
</P>
<P>
Gingrich predicted that President Bill Clinton "is going to
sign."
</P>
<P>
But the White House and its allies in Congress dismissed the
effort in advance.
</P>
<P>
In the House, officials said Republicans were discussing an
approach that would fund an ad campaign discouraging teen smoking
and grant the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) authority over
the manufacture of cigarettes, but not necessarily over nicotine.
They are also seeking to impose constitutionally permissible
restrictions on industry advertising clearly directed at minors.
</P>
<P>
The Associated Press quoted unidentified officials as saying
Republicans were discussing imposing limits on the placement of
vending machines to make it harder for teen-agers to buy
cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
Also under review is a plan for financial incentives to states
that take steps on their own to crack down on youth smoking.
</P>
<P>
The emerging House bill is not expected to seek higher
cigarette prices -- a centerpiece of the Senate bill killed
Wednesday and a key demand of public health groups supporting its
passage.
</P>
<P>
The house bill is not expected to touch directly on numerous
state lawsuits and the settlement the industry reached with
attorneys-general a year ago, an event that gave impetus to
attempts to enact legislation in Congress.
</P>
<P>
Pollsters reportedly have told Republicans they are viewed by
the public as too closely allied with the tobacco industry but
don't need to pass a broad bill like the Senate measure to remedy
the damage. They fare just as well, in this view, by passing a
smaller bill.
</P>
<P>
"There's absolutely no reason we should be a party to
protecting an industry that is so despicable and so dishonest,"
added Representative Deborah Pryce, a Republican and head of a
task force to produce legislation.
</P>
<P>
Republicans said they had come to no decision yet on how to
finance the proposed ad campaign.
</P>
<P>
The measure that died in the Senate would have raised the price
of cigarettes by 1.10 dollar a pack, and raised an estimated 561
billion dollar or more over 25 years.
</P>
<P>
Republicans attacked it as a "tax and spend" measure that was
far bigger than anything needed to deal with teen smoking, and
Gingrich said House Republicans don't "want to go into the same
kind of swamp."
</P>
<P>
As for Clinton, Gingrich said, "I don't think he's going to
veto an anti-smoking bill. I think he's going to sign it.
Particularly if it's part of an anti-drug bill."
</P>
<P>
But White House spokesman Mike McCurry told reporters there is
"no such thing as a slimmed-down bill that protects kids from
tobacco smoking....
</P>
<P>
"In short, you need to have that per pack price increase of at
least 1.10 dollar," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
