<HEADLINE> First Brazilian Astronaut Prepares for Space </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Air Force Captain Marcos
Cesar Pontes will be the first Brazilian to travel in space.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian Space Agency (AEB) commission selected Captain
Pontes as the astronaut from among five candidates to join the
crew of a space tour by the United States National Administration
of Space and Aeronautics (NASA).
</P>
<P>
Pontes, 35, from the city of Bauru in Sao Paulo state, is an
engineer who graduated from the Aeronautics Technological
Institute.
</P>
<P>
He was a fighter pilot until 1988 and has a rich experience in
the piloting of military planes including U.S. F-15s, F-16s, and
F-18s, as well as the Russian MIG-29.
</P>
<P>
Pontes was very happy when he was informed that he would be the
first Brazilian astronaut to go into the space, and said
travelling in space was his old dream.
</P>
<P>
Brazil takes part, as a member country, in the International
Project of Space Station led by the United States Space Agency.
</P>
</TEXT>
