<HEADLINE> Romania to Continue Peacekeeping Mission in Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The Romanian parliament Thursday
approved a bill submitted by President Emil Constantinescu to
further extend the commitment of troops to Bosnia for peacekeeping
operations.
</P>
<P>
The bill provides for a contingent of 200 soldiers and officers
to participate in peacekeeping operations in Bosnia for the period
between June 21, 1998 and June 30, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The Romanian contingent will consist of an engineering
battalion, a transportation unit and a platoon of armed police
supported by two C-130 transport planes.
</P>
<P>
Romania's Mediafax news agency said the troop contribution
will cost about 55 billion leus (6.47 million U.S dollars).
</P>
<P>
Romania sent the first batch of peacekeepers to Bosnia in 1996
after the signing of the Dayton Peace Accord, which brought the
Bosnian civil war to an end.
</P>
<P>
Romanian soldiers have also joined U.N. peacekeeping operations
in Somalia and Albania. 
</P>
