<HEADLINE> Wimbledon Shuns Direct Advertising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 18 (Xinhua) -- There are no blimps hovering
overhead, no inflated mascots tethered to Center Court, and
billboards are banned in the forthcoming Wimbledon Open tennis
tournament.
</P>
<P>
Wimbledon is one of sport's last advertising-free zones.
</P>
<P>
According to reports form Wimbledon, Profits have grown by 10
percent the last five years, with a record 51 million U.S. dollars
generated in 1997 from the two-week tournament.
</P>
<P>
Wimbledon Marketing Director Robert McCowen said: "We could
make more money in the next two or three years by selling
billboards and advertising out there. But we think in the
long-term we'd make less because television would turn around and
say we're now like any other sports event in the world."
</P>
<P>
Hefty television contracts - as in most sports - pay most of
the bills with merchandising, ticket sales and hospitality making
up the rest. Profits go to the Lawn Tennis Association, the
governing body of tennis in England.
</P>
<P>
"We could get more income if we marketed trash," McCowen said.
"There's a lot of money at the bottom of the marketplace. But we'd
kill the goose that laid the golden egg." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Builds World Biggest Transfer Factor Production Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, June 19 (Xinhua) -- A transnational enterprise group
based in Xi'an has established what is thought to be the world's
largest production base for transfer factor, a drug used for the
prevention and treatment of Hepatitis B.
</P>
<P>
The high-tech biological pharmaceutical can adjust and
strengthen immunologic functions and can be used to treat other
diseases caused by viruses.
</P>
<P>
The Xi'an Jinhua Group, which has engaged in the research into
and development of transfer factors for many years, invested over
200 million yuan (24 million U.S. dollars) in establishing the
production base.
</P>
<P>
The base is located in a high-tech development zone in Xi'an,
capital of northwest China's Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
Transfer factor is a biological compound normally extracted
from the spleens of animals.
</P>
<P>
The production base will have an annual production capacity of
100 million units of oral liquid and 100 million capsules of
transfer factor, as well as 100 million tablets of interferon.
</P>
</TEXT>
