<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the past
few days:
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- The economic growth of Chile in April reached 6.7
percent, the Central Bank said.
</P>
<P>
The growth was sustained by the recovery of the electric, gas,
and water sectors, in transportation, in the growth of import
duties, and a significant growth in mining, bank officials said.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Argentine steel output in the first five months
of this year increased compared to the same period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
A report shows that hot-finished laminated products had a 17.7
percent growth, and primary iron a 13.5 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
The report added that raw steel rose 6.5 percent in this period
and cold-finished laminates 5.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- Nicaragua exported 91,515 exotic animals last year,
representing about 3 million U.S. dollars in legal sales.
</P>
<P>
More than 60 percent of the specimens exported were raised in
captivity; there are quotas for the capture of wildlife. There
are 21 companies in the country that export animals, mainly to the
United States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- Costa Rican tax revenues during the first five
months of this year amounted to 173,055 colons (some 697 million
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
This figure represents a 22.9 percent increase compared to the
same period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The total spending of the central government amounted to 827
million dollars, a 17.3 percent increase compared to the same
period in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
