<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Marcos' Burial Opposed by Groups in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The incoming administration's
decision to bury former president Ferdinand Marcos in a heroes'
cemetery in Manila has aroused opposition in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Main Manila newspapers Friday reported that former president
Corazon Aquino Thursday led a street protest against the plan,
saying the heroes' cemetery was no place for a "dictator".
</P>
<P>
"Is it right to honor a dictator who ordered the killing of
thousands of Filipinos, who allowed the torture of those who
opposed him?" Aquino said at a mass rally near the Presidential
Palace.
</P>
<P>
She said if the new government continues insisting on its plan,
she would lead another "People's Power", in which Marcos was
ousted in a popular revolt in 1986.
</P>
<P>
Marcos fled to Hawaii, the United States, in February 1986 and
died there three years later. His remains returned to his hometown
for a private funeral in 1993, but his family has been asking for
a state honor burial in the heroes' cemetery, citing Marcos' role
in the second World War and as the president of the country.
</P>
<P>
The question of where Marcos should be buried is emerging as
the first test for Joseph Estrada, who is to assume presidency on
June 30. Pressure and protest against the interment of Marcos are
mounting in the country.
</P>
<P>
Former senator Rene Saguisag, a human rights lawyer, warned
that impeachment may be initiated against Estrada if he pushes
through with his decision to bury Marcos.
</P>
<P>
But Estrada was unfazed by the threat, saying no law prohibited
ex-presidents from being buried at the heroes' cemetery which is
normally for war heroes and former presidents.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-eight human rights groups and some 10,000 Marcos regime
victims are also launching a signature drive to convince Estrada
to change his mind. 
</P>
</TEXT>
