<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bringing Spring Water Back To Eastern Chinese City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Jinan, the capital of east China's
Shandong Province, will soon get its spring water back again,
according to Mayor Xie Yutang.
</P>
<P>
This "spring city" was once famous for its 162 springs in the
urban area, according to the garden department, but most of them
stopped flowing in the 1970s, and water only comes out of some of
them between August and the following February.
</P>
<P>
The loss is largely attributed to growth in the city and the
excessive use of underground water, so Jinan is building a
reservoir in the western part of the city to bring water from the
Yellow River and plans to reduce consumption of underground
water.
</P>
<P>
Another reservoir is being built to supplement the city's
water supplies, the mayor says, and it won't be long before the
city gets its springs flowing again, if the two projects can go
into operation within five years and the city can cut underground
water use by 80 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   Zberg Wins Second Stage in Swiss Cycle Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Swiss Markus Zberg outsprinted
compatriot Niki Aebersold to win the 159-km second stage of the
Tour of Switzerland cycle race from Aigle to Ulrichen on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Zberg powered his way out of the pack, crossing half a bike's
length in front of Swiss Post team mate Nike Aebersold in three
hours 33 minutes nine seconds.
</P>
<P>
Italy's Davide Rebellin, winner of Wednesday's first stage,
retained the leader's jersey. He holds a 27 seconds lead over
Frenchman Laurent Jalabert.
</P>
<P>
Riders will get a taste of what lies ahead with Friday's
gruelling climb up the Nufenen pass before finishing in Varese,
Italy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
