<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, June 19 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton met French Prime
Minister Lionel Jospin Thursday over subjects ranging from Asia's
financial crisis to the Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
Clinton and Jospin had a working lunch at the White House.
Jospin stressed his desire for cordial dealings with Washington.
</P>
<P>
"We had a good visit. We had a lot of areas of agreement,"
Clinton told reporters after the lunch. (US-France-Jospin)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- Iraq refused to include some of the priority
issues identified by the U.N. Special Commission on Iraq's
disarmament, the commision's Executive Chairman Richard Butler
said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Butler, who discussed the remaining disarmament issues with
Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz during his trip to Baghdad
on June 11-15, made the comment in his latest report to the U.N.
Security Council. (UN-Iraq-Disarmament)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States said Thursday that it has
agreed to allow Cuba's national airline to fly over U.S. territory
on its flights to Canada.
</P>
<P>
The State Department said that the authorization was negotiated
through the International Civil Aviation Organization in Montreal,
where Cuba had lodged a complaint that the U.S. ban violated
international overflight rules.
</P>
<P>
The United States has agreed to authorize Cuban airlines to
use two specified Cuba-Canada overland routes and to provide
normal air navigation services, said the State Department.
(US-Cuba-Airline)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. sanctions against India and Pakistan for
their nuclear tests will apply to American bank lending to the two
governments, some credits and guarantees, and military sales, a
senior U.S. official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott told a news conference
more details of exactly what the sanctions meant would be provided
soon.
</P>
<P>
The United States has already terminated certain military sales
and provoked licenses on some commercial sales of munitions to
India and Pakistan. (US-India-Pakistan-Sanctions)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton said Thursday that
the United States wanted reconciliation with Iran as the Gulf
country was changing in what he called "a positive way."
</P>
<P>
"We believe Iran is changing in a positive way, and we want to
support that," Clinton said at a ceremony in the White House Rose
Garden. "What we want is a genuine reconciliation with Iran."
(US-Iran-Clinton)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HARARE -- The Tokyo international conference on African
development (TICAD ii) starts a two-day second preparatory meeting
here Friday to deliberate on agenda for action to promote
development in the continent.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Information Center said in a statement to
the Zimbabwe News Agency Thursday that 24 members of the
preparatory committee were expected to attend the meeting which is
organized by the United Nations, Japan and the Global Coalition
for Africa. (Meeting-African Development) 
</P>
