<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan, Bellamy Praise Landmine Treaty's Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Kofi Annan,
secretary-general of the United Nations, and Carol Bellamy,
executive director of the United Nations Children's Fund, Thursday
congratulated the 19 countries that have now ratified the treaty
to ban anti-personnel landmines.
</P>
<P>
They said the actions of these countries would lend momentum to
the urgent push to put the accord into effect this year.
</P>
<P>
Peru's ratification, the 19th so far, was made official
Thursday morning. Approval by 40 countries will make the treaty
binding international law.
</P>
<P>
"Ratification will be a giant step towards the demining of the
world," Annan said. "Delay will only add to lives lost and to the
growing expense of removing these silent killers from the earth."
</P>
<P>
He urged all countries that have signed the treaty to move
swiftly to ratify it and expressed the hope that governments that
have not signed the treaty will now do so.
</P>
<P>
"The agreement to abolish these horrific weapons is being
achieved with remarkable swiftness and resolve," Bellamy said.
"Now that we have 50 percent of the requisite ratifications, we
have every hope that governments will complete the achievement
with the greatest possible haste."
</P>
<P>
The treaty, signed last December in Ottawa, prohibits the use,
production, development, acquisition, sale, stockpiling and
transfer of anti-personnel landmines, which kill and maim 26,000
civilians a year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0285 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> It's Essential for U.S. to Pay U.N. Dues: Annan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 18 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan said here Thursday that it is essential for the United
States to pay its 1.6 billion U.S. dollar debt owed to the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the nomination of Richard Holbrooke as U.S.
ambassador to the U.N. to replace Bill Richardson who will be U.S.
secretary of energy, Annan said it is the U.S. Congress that has
made Richardson's U.N. task "much more difficult" despite his
success during his tenure of one and half years.
</P>
<P>
"If they (Congress) would have honored their commitments, I
think he (Richardson) would have even been more successful.
</P>
<P>
"I hope Richard Holbrooke will be a bit more successful and
will be luckier with Congress," the U.N. chief told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Richardson, who stays in the U.N. through the end of summer
waiting for Congress confirmation, said, "It is shameful that we
have not paid our U.N. dues. The time has come for the U.S.
Congress to separate issues of abortion and U.N. dues."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government wants to pay the U.N. membership dues,
but the Congress has set preconditions for paying them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
