<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Rejects Some Priority Issues: Chief U.N. Inspector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Iraq refused to include
some of the priority issues identified by the U.N. Special
Commission on Iraq's disarmament, the commision's Executive
Chairman Richard Butler said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Butler, who discussed the remaining disarmament issues with
Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz during his trip to Baghdad
on June 11-15, made the comment in his latest report to the U.N.
Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The issues rejected by Iraq include the extent of the
production of warfare agent VX, the accounting for proscribed
missile propellants and the clarification of the concealment
actions and policies by Iraq, the 14-page report said.
</P>
<P>
Butler went to Baghdad with a so-called "road map" for Iraq to
follow in the disarmament process. Iraq was required to provide
materials, documents and information on its chemical and
biological weapons and ballistic missiles.
</P>
<P>
The report said Iraq did not accept the commission's
requirements as a "road map," disagreeing that all of the issues
identified were issues of disarmament.
</P>
<P>
Aziz accused the commission of pursuing "many trivial matters
not related to disarmament that only delayed lifting the embargo"
imposed on Iraq after its invasion of Kuwait in 1990, according to
the report.
</P>
<P>
"Iraq has destroyed its proscribed weapons and the details were
unimportant in view of the level of suffering in Iraq as a
consequence of sanctions," the report quoted Aziz as telling
Butler.
</P>
<P>
Butler insisted that the commission's work had been prolonged
"because of Iraq's incorrect declarations, unilateral
destructions, and policies and actions of concealment."
</P>
<P>
"In virtually all instances, Iraq remained firm in its
position that no relevant documents were available. However, in
limited cases Iraq would look again for documents," the report
said.
</P>
<P>
It said Aziz expressed the Iraqi government's willingness to
cooperate with the commission in the next two months as agreed
by both sides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
