<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Says U.S. Wants Reconciliation With Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 18 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton said
Thursday that the United States wanted reconciliation with Iran as
the Gulf country was changing in what he called "a positive way."
</P>
<P>
"We believe Iran is changing in a positive way, and we want to
support that," Clinton said at a ceremony in the White House Rose
Garden. "What we want is a genuine reconciliation with Iran."
</P>
<P>
He said he appreciated the comments made by Iranian President
Mohammad Khatami several months ago. "We are exploring what the
future might hold," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's comments reinforced an overture to Iran Wednesday by
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who urged Iran to join the
United States in drawing a "road map leading to normal relations."
But Albright offered no promises of specific American actions.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Asia Society, Albright noted that since Khatami
put out feelers, Washington had taken cautious steps, including
easing up on visas for Iranians, revising a travel warning and
promoting cultural exchanges.
</P>
<P>
"We are ready to explore further ways to build mutual
confidence and avoid misunderstandings. The Islamic Republic
should consider paralleled steps," she said.
</P>
<P>
"If such a process can be initiated and sustained in a way that
addresses the concerns of both sides, then we in the United States
can see the prospect of a very different relationship," she added.
</P>
<P>
Albright's remarks on relations with Iran weres made after she
discussed with the president, Clinton told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Albright also offered a proposal that Iran could be included in
"multilateral efforts to protect international security."
</P>
<P>
"This global network has grown largely without Iranian
participation," Albright said. "But Iran would be welcome if it is
willing to make a constructive contribution."
</P>
<P>
The United States and Iran have ceded their diplomatic
relations since Iran's Islamic revolution in 1979.
</P>
<P>
A senior U.S. official called Albright's speech at the Asia
Society "the first comprehensive, substantive policy statement on
Iran" since Khatami's interview with CNN on relations between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
It follows the important U.S. decision to waive sanctions
against three foreign companies of France, Russia and Malaysia,
which have a 2 billion dollar gas deal with Iran. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0294 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Backs China's Agriculture, Power Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank Thursday
approved two loans totaling 600 million U.S. dollars for two
projects in China.
</P>
<P>
The first loan of 300 million dollars will be used to help the
Hunan power development project. This project will alleviate power
shortages in Hunan province by providing efficient, reliable and
environmentally sound power supply.
</P>
<P>
The project will develop two modern thermal units, reinforcing
the critical transmission infrastructure to improve overall system
reliability, retiring a number of small, inefficient, aging and
pollution-generating units and avoiding further proliferation of
inefficient and more polluting small plants.
</P>
<P>
The other loan of also 300 million dollars is earmarked for the
irrigated agriculture intensification II project in the country.
The main activities of this project are to construct and improve
irrigation and farmland in the five provinces of Hebei, Henan,
Shandong, Jiangsu and Anhui in the Huang-Huai-Hai Plain of China.
</P>
<P>
The project will also promote food security, irrigation reform,
and environmental protection for the major lakes and groundwater
in the project area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
