<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Red-carded Substitutes Make History </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOULOUSE, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The 1-1 draw between South Africa and
Denmark on Thursday was the first game in the history of the World Cup
finals in which three substitutes were sent off.
</P>
<P>
Danes Morten Wieghorst and Miklos Molnar and South Africa's Alfred
Phiri were given the marching orders by Colombian referee John Tairo
Toro Rendo.
</P>
<P>
Only two previous World Cup games, in 1938 and 1954, had seen three
players sent off but it is the first time that three substitutes were
sent off. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0307 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Gives Some Details of Sanctions on India, Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 18 (Xinhua) -- U.S. sanctions against India
and Pakistan for their nuclear tests will apply to American bank
lending to the two governments, some credits and guarantees, and
military sales, a senior U.S. official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott told a news conference
more details of exactly what the sanctions meant would be provided
soon.
</P>
<P>
The United States has already terminated certain military sales
and provoked licenses on some commercial sales of munitions to
India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
He said the Clinton administration would support efforts in
Congress to exempt agricultural credits from the sanctions. And
U.S. bank lending to the private sector in the two countries would
not be affected by the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Talbott said, "The path down which India and Pakistan have
started to move with these tests is a dead end and no one else
should follow down that path."
</P>
<P>
India conducted five nuclear tests last month, sparking global
condemnations and raising tension with Pakistan, which retaliated
by carrying out its own tests.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton immediately announced sanctions against
both countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0308 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Supports Social Safety Nets in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank approved here
Thursday a 300 million U.S. dollar sing-tranche economic recovery
and social sector loan to Malaysia to help mitigate the social
consequences of the East Asia economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
The loan will help provide the Malaysian government with
necessary budget flexibility to maintain spending on social
sectors, mainly education and health, while increasing spending on
targeted programs for the poor in rural and urban areas.
</P>
<P>
The project will support the government's program of
pre-emptive measures to minimize the downturn in economic
activity, implement policy reforms to resume robust and
sustainable growth, expand safety nets to protect the hard core
and the near poor from the adverse effects of the crisis and
protect investments in the human resources base. 
</P>
</TEXT>
