<HEADLINE> Ousted Colombian Striker Apologizes Publicly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Colombian striker Faustino Asprilla has
apologized publicly on Thursday for his criticism on the team's
tactics, hoping the head coach Hernan Dario Gomez would recall him.
</P>
<P>
The Parma striker, who has been kicked out the national squad
following his remarks to a radio reporter, said he wanted the coach to
take him back to the ongoing World Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
"I would like to apologize to the (soccer association) president,
to his executive, to the coach, to my colleagues and above all to the
Colombian people," said a contrite Asprilla in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"If the team coach considers my participation to be important, I am
ready to submit willingly and in a disciplined way to the rules
demanded in a World Cup," said Asprilla.
</P>
<P>
"The coach decided to kick me out of the squad because of what I
said," Asprilla said. "Nobody wants to continue being a part of this
team more than I do."
</P>
<P>
Colombia will face Tunisia in their next group G game in
Montpellier next Monday in group G. The other teams in the group are
England, Romania and England. 
</P>
