<HEADLINE> UAE Promises to Help Afghan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU-DHABI, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Leader of the Taliban Interim
Council Sheikh Mullah Mohammad Rabbani said Thursday that the
United Arab Emirates had promised him to help the reconstruction
of the war-torn Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Rabbani made the remarks at the end of his four-day visit to
the UAE, the UAE News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
But he failed to get a specific assistance during the visit,
informed sources here told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Rabbani said he had held talks with Vice Commander-in-Chief of
the Armed Forces Crown Prince Sheikh Khalifa Bin Zayed Al-Nahyan,
discussing ways of enhancing bilateral cooperation, probing the
possibility of the UAE's participation in the rehabilitation of
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The Afghan militia group Taliban, which pursues strict islamic
rules and traditions, drove out the government troops led by
President Burhanuddin Rabbani and came to power in September 1996.
</P>
<P>
Ever since, a new civil war has been continuing between the
Taliban forces, which control 80 percent of the country, and the
northern guerrilla alliance.
</P>
<P>
The UAE recognized the islamic regime of Taliban last year
after Pakistan and Saudi Arabia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
