<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia to Have Only Short-Term Effects on Jet Makers: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Boeing said that Asia's
economic crisis will have only marginal long-term effects on the
company and the rest of the industry, although it is likely to
result in about 150 fewer commercial airplanes than anticipated
over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
In its 1998 "Current Market Outlook" report released Thursday,
the Seattle-based airplane manufacturer also said that
single-aisle jets such as the Boeing 737 will continue to dominate
the new aircraft market over the next 20 years.
</P>
<P>
In the coming two decades, airlines will add 17,750 airplanes
of all models worth 1.25 trillion U.S. dollars, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
The Asian economic crisis, which has brought delivery
deferrals, fleet-reduction sales and a few order cancellations,
still is expected to have only short-term effects on aircraft
purchases, although it has forced Boeing to plan to slow
production of its 747 jumbo jets next year.
</P>
<P>
Boeing's latest estimate said that the world's aircraft fleet
will grow 44 percent in 10 years, to 17,700 airplanes from 12,280
at the end of last year, but will double between now and 2017 to
26,200 planes.
</P>
<P>
More than 2,200 aging planes will be replaced, but about 60
percent of those already have been ordered, accounting for the
current surge of smaller jets.
</P>
<P>
Narrow-bodied aircraft, which include Boeing's 717, 737 and
757, as well as competing Airbus models, also will account for 43
percent of the dollars invested in new airplanes during the next
two decades, said the report, predicting 12,260 airplanes of this
size will be delivered in the period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
