<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Wants to End Oil-For-Food Program in 6 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The latest six-month phase
of the oil-for-food program should be the last one, Iraqi
Ambassador to the United Nations Nizar Hamdoon stressed here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The latest oil-for-food program should be the final one, to be
followed by the lifting of sanctions on the normal export of oil,"
Hamdoon told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"I have just delivered a couple of letters to the U.N.
secretary-general and to the president of the Security Council of
the United Nations, calling for a consideration by the council
that this is the last phase that Iraq will have to undertake," the
ambassador said.
</P>
<P>
"The immediate alternative should be a total lifting of the
embargo on Iraq, which means that there will be no need to
continue any of those phases of the oil-for-food plan," Hamdoon
noted.
</P>
<P>
The oil-for-food program which went into effect in 1996 aims to
ease the deteriorating humanitarian situation in Iraq caused by
U.N. sanctions since 1990. Under the program, Iraq is allowed to
sell 2 billion U.S. dollars worth of oil every six months to
import food, medicine and other necessities for its people. In
February 1998, the Security Council adopted a resolution to
upgrade the oil amount that Iraq could sell every six months to
5.2 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
