<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak Supports Peaceful Solution to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 18 (Xinhua) -- As African leaders set themselves to
restore peace in the Horn of Africa, Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak Thursday affirmed Egypt's support to all efforts towards a
peaceful solution of the Ethiopian-Eritrean border dispute.
</P>
<P>
The support was conveyed in a message Mubarak sent Thursday to
President of Burkina Faso Blaise Compaore who is the current
chairman of the Organization of African Unity (OAU) and the head
of a mediation team entrusted by the OAU to Eritrea and Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt fully believes that border problems will never be solved
by force, but rather through negotiations and respect of the OAU
Charter," Mubarak was quoted by the Middle East News Agency as
saying in his message.
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that the African mediation efforts will
succeed. African leaders met with Ethiopian and Eritrean leaders
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The OAU mission is made up of Presidents of Burkina Faso,
Djibouti and Zimbabwe, and OAU Secretary General Salem Ahmed
Salem, Deputy Assistant to the Egyptian Foreign Minister for
African Affairs Fayza Abu el Naga said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, she said, follows up ongoing diplomatic efforts to
contain the armed conflict between the two countries and hopes
efforts led by Compaore reach a comprehensive and peaceful
settlement to the conflict.
</P>
<P>
The OAU, at last week's meeting in Ouagadougou, Burkina Faso,
issued a resolution that affirmed the necessity to halt aggression
and implement the proposals of the mediators.
</P>
<P>
The conflict broke out in early May. Ground fighting has
subsided since June 11. The U.S. and Rwanda, mediating in the
conflict, have presented a four-point peace plan.
</P>
<P>
Last week Ethiopian and Eritrean foreign ministers paid
separate visits to Cairo to make their sides of story to
Egypt. Ethiopia and Eritrea accused each other of incursions.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian leader had sent two messages to leaders of both
countries, calling for an immediate end to fighting and
negotiations to resolve the border row that centers on a 400
square kilometers rocky triangle of land along their western
border.
</P>
<P>
Eritrea and Ethiopia, among the world's poorest, are at odds
over at least six areas along their common border. Eritrea gained
independence from Ethiopia in 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
