<HEADLINE> Ugandan PM Stresses Decentralization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan Prime Minister Kintu
Musoke said here Thursday that local governments have been given
the power to enable administrative control over delivery of
services in jurisdiction and to improve popular control over
local government agendas.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks when addressing local council leaders,
parliamentarians, permanent secretaries, resident district
commissioners and chief administrative officers, Radio Uganda
reported.
</P>
<P>
This is aimed at improving the service delivery,
decentralization, promoting transparency, accountability in the
conduct of public affairs, the report added.
</P>
<P>
He said the central government has retained inspection,
monitoring as well as supervisory and coordinating powers over
local governments.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister emphasized clean division of work between
local and central governments. He cautioned that the political
and executive powers of local governments are not absolute or
limitless. Instead they should be exercised according to
constitution and with great responsibility.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to those present to develop a culture of mutual
respect and compliment each other's efforts in developing their
areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
