<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Mulls Revision of Asylum System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 18 (Xinhua) -- South Africa is considering
measures to end the abuse of its asylum system by foreigners
posing as refugees, according to a draft refugee white paper
published Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Releasing the document in Pretoria, Home Affairs Minister
Mangosuthu Buthelezi said the new refugee policy will exclude
victims of poverty or environmental disasters.
</P>
<P>
"We do not accept that economic migrants should be able to use
the refugee determination process to obtain residence,
employment... or to avoid the consequences of the law concerning
illegal migration."
</P>
<P>
He said refugees should not be confused with illegal aliens.
</P>
<P>
In terms of the proposed new legislation, the process and time
for application for refugee status will be shortened
considerably.
</P>
<P>
The current system entitled migrants to live and work in the
country for a period pending their applications for refugee
status.
</P>
<P>
"A great number of people have found this a very useful avenue
for entering South Africa," said Deputy Home Affairs Minister
Lindiwe Sisulu.
</P>
<P>
Under the new law, the entire application process should not
be longer than six months and applications should include
interviews conducted by trained officials.
</P>
<P>
Sisulu said 7,676 people have been granted asylum since 1994,
and 13,934 applications are under consideration.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0324 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
