<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Trade Deficit Surges to Record High in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. trade deficit shot up
to a record high of 14.5 billion U.S. dollars in April, the
Commerce Department reported here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The department said that the April deficit was 9.5 percent
higher than the March imbalance of 13.2 billion dollars, the
previous record. The growth is largely blamed to the Asian
currency devaluation which facilitates their exports, pushing down
the U.S. sales abroad,
</P>
<P>
While imports declined a slight 0.9 percent in April after
hitting an all-time high the month before, U.S. exports fell even
more sharply, dropping 2.6 percent as the deepening recessions in
many Asian markets cut into U.S. sales.
</P>
<P>
For the first four months of this year, the U.S. deficit in
goods and services was running at an annual rate of 149 billion
dollars, on track to set a record this year, far surpassing last
year's imbalance of 110.2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The deficit with Japan edged down 6 percent in April to 5.4
billion dollars but was still running 13.3 percent ahead of the
same period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
For the entire Pacific Rim region, which includes South Korea
and other countries and regions hard hit by the currency crisis,
the U.S. trade deficit in the first four months of this year
totaled 48.7 billion dollars, 38 percent higher than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
In April, the 2.6 percent drop in exports of goods and services
pushed them down to 77.1 billion dollars. Exports of goods fell to
55.3 billion dollars, the lowest level since February 1997.
Exports of the U.S. farm products dropped to 3.8 billion dollars,
the lowest level since September 1994.
</P>
<P>
Among the export categories declining were sales of commercial
aircraft which fell 926 million dollars to 1.6 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Imports of goods and services, which hit a record high of 92.4
billion dollars in March, slipped 0.9 percent in April to 91.6
billion dollars, but still the second-highest level in history.
</P>
<P>
The 14.5 billion dollar deficit was the highest since the
government began tracking goods and services on a monthly basis in
1992. For goods alone, the deficit of 21.5 billion dollars was
also the highest in the U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
In another sign of the U.S. deteriorating trade performance,
the Commerce Department also reported Thursday that the deficit
in the widest measure of trade, the current account, widened in
the first quarter of this year to al all-time high of 47.2
billion dollars. This was up 4.8 percent from the previous
record, 45 billion dollar gap in the fourth quarter of last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Labor Department said that new applications
for unemployment benefits surged 13,000 to a total of 327,000
last week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
