<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Arrested for World Cup Ticket Fraud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
PARIS, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Three people, including a consultant
for the World Cup's marketing agency, have been arrested, French
police officials said.
</P>
<P>
The three people were arrested in a probe of a ticket fraud that
forze out thousands of Japanese soccer fans and more arrests could
follow, according to police officials.
</P>
<P>
Police arrested Gilles Favard, the consultant for ISL France, in
the western Paris suburb of Rueil-Malmaison on Monday. Police found
a large amount of cash and about 100 World Cup tickets there.
</P>
<P>
Police were urged to take the action after more than 12,000
Japanese fans were left ticketless for the World Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
Police said two other people were detained, one is Favard's
sister and the other Favard's friend who was believed to have helped
the consultant sell tickets by fax. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
