<HEADLINE> Matthaeus Says Hooligans Should Be Counted in 2006 Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
PARIS, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Veteran German player Lothar
Matthaeus said on Thursday that riot involving English hooligans at
the World Cup finals shoude be taken into account in the bid for the
2006 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
Germany are bidding for the 2006 World Cup finals against England
and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Interviewed by German sports magazine Kicker, Matthaeus
said:"Absolutely negative was the behavior of the English hooligans
in Marseille."
</P>
<P>
"It's always these English hooligans. FIFA shoul take this into
account for the 2006 finals even if England organized Euro'96 very
well," said Matthaeus, "The pictures we had from Marseille gave the
wrong impression of this World Cup."
</P>
<P>
Matthaeus didn't play in Germany's opening group match against the
United States. If he has the chance to play a match in the World Cup,
he would be the first player to play 22 matches at World Cup finals.
</P>
</TEXT>
