<HEADLINE> Batistuta Says Argentines to "Get Serious" against Jamaica </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Striker Gabriel Batistuta said his squad
would "get serious" when they meet minnows Jamaica at the Parc des
Princes here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"I think tings are going to get serious at the next match against
Jamaica," said the Fiorentina forward in l'Etrat near Saint Etienne.
</P>
<P>
"We need to remember the goal we scored against Japan. It was our
first in this World Cup and it's always good for team morale to star
off such a competition with a victory," said Batistuta.
</P>
<P>
He said he would expect better performance from the former World
Cup champion.
</P>
<P>
"We need to follow things up much better because we are still
aiming to be first. We need to convince ourselves that we're going to
be the champions and live up to the reputation of favorites," added
Batistuta.
</P>
<P>
As for himself, he hoped to score at least one goal at each game.
</P>
<P>
"I am the goal scorer (in the game against Japan) and I intend to
be exactly that for every match. The injury is not bothering me any
more."
</P>
<P>
Teammate Roberto Sensini called for the Argentine squad to look out
for Croatia, which they will face in their last group match on June
26.
</P>
<P>
"There is a lot of pressure on me as I've been made to feel that
I'm vital in the line-up. Without Maradona, I've got even more
responsibilities," said the Parma defender who is playing his third
World Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
"Croatia seems very dangerous. They are very strong both
technically and physically. It won't be easy to beat this team," he
warned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
