<DOCNO> XIE19980619.0353 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Democrats Trying to Revive Tobacco Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 18 (Xinhua) -- A Democratic attempt to attach
tobacco legislation to an appropriations bill was rejected by the
Senate Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"We will not let the issue die," Senate Minority Leader Tom
Daschle said, hours after Congress' first national tobacco
proposal perished on procedural votes Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Daschle tried to revive the legislation sponsored by Republican
Senator John McCain Thursday morning by tying it to an energy
appropriations bill only to be rebuffed, 54-44.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton has also pledged to keep the issue
alive in Congress and in this fall's election campaign, saying, "I
don't intend to stop fighting for this."
</P>
<P>
Daschle said, "We are going to continue this fight in whatever
vehicle, whatever form, whatever opportunity we have."
</P>
<P>
At an unrelated Rose Garden announcement Thursday morning,
Clinton again lashed out at Republicans for killing the tobacco
legislation. "It's dead today; it may not be dead tomorrow," he
said. "I think, in the end, we will prevail."
</P>
<P>
"Big tobacco owns the Republican party and they've just proven
it again," said Senator Tom Harkin, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
McCain blamed cigarette makers, who waged a 40 million dollar
advertising campaign against the bill. "They're the big winners
today," he said on ABC's "Good Morning America."
</P>
<P>
"More importantly, the children of America lost, because today
3,000 children will start smoking and a thousand of them will die
early," McCain said.
</P>
<P>
Republicans countered that the bill essentially killed itself
after numerous amendments bloated it beyond its original focus --
to curb teen smoking.
</P>
<P>
"We've lost sight of the original noble cause of just dealing
with teen-age smoking and drug abuse," said Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott.
</P>
<P>
Assistant Majority Leader Don Nickles called the bill "a crummy
effort at raising taxes."
</P>
<P>
McCain's bill would have raised at least 516 billion dollars
over 25 years, in part by raising the price. It also would have
granted the Food and Drug Administration authority to regulate
nicotine and severely limited the industry's ability to advertise.
</P>
<P>
The legislation would have settled three dozen state lawsuits
against the industry in which local governments are trying to
recoup the cost of treating sick smokers.
</P>
<P>
Negotiation last summer resulted in a deal between the states
and the tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
Their 368 billion-dollar settlement of the state lawsuits was
the model for McCain's bill. But during some 80 hours of debate
over nearly four weeks, senators added provisions to cut taxes for
some married couples and self-employed workers, limit the fees of
attorneys filing lawsuits against the industry and devote some of
the money raised to drug-fighting efforts.
</P>
<P>
Though many of those amendments are pet Republican proposals,
the Republicans turned against the bill in a climax in which
supporters twice failed to gain the 60 votes that would have kept
it alive.
</P>
<P>
In the House of Representatives, Republicans are reportedly to
unveil a narrower anti-smoking bill this week, aimed at curbing
teen smoking and drug abuse without raising hundreds of billions
of dollars in revenue.
</P>
<P>
"Our goal is to reduce teen smoking, not increase taxes," House
Speaker Newt Gingrich said in a statement. Senate Republicans
promised to pursue similar legislation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
